#### 1.4.3 FELINE as Synthesis of Major Frameworks

> See diagram: `diagrams/feline-synthesis.mmd`

FELINE is not proposing that existing major frameworks are wrong. Rather, FELINE proposes that **the Cellular Phase hypothesis, the PANTHOS/Lysosomal hypothesis, the Vascular Two-Hit hypothesis, and the Viral hypothesis are all correct -- and are describing different layers of the same multi-layer defense system.**

**The Major Frameworks and Their Central Claims:**

| Framework                   | Key Proponents                        | Central Claim                                                                                                                                                            |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Cellular Phase**    | De Strooper & Karran (VIB-Leuven/UCL) | AD involves decades-long cellular phase where astrocytes, microglia, and vasculature engage in feedback loops; perturbations transform from compensatory to irreversible |
| **PANTHOS/Lysosomal** | Nixon Lab (NYU/NKI)                   | Lysosomal acidification failure is upstream of amyloid; plaques form "inside-out" from neurons dying of lysosomal membrane permeabilization                              |
| **Vascular Two-Hit**  | Zlokovic Lab (USC)                    | BBB/pericyte dysfunction precedes and enables A-beta accumulation                                                                                                        |
| **Viral Hypothesis**  | Itzhaki Lab (Manchester)              | HSV-1/VZV infection triggers AD pathology; antivirals prevent AD in epidemiological studies                                                                              |

**How FELINE Maps These Frameworks to Defense Layers:**

| FELINE Layer                | Cellular Phase                                    | PANTHOS/Lysosomal                          | Vascular                                                 | Viral                        |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| **L (Lysosome)**      | "lysosomal/endolysosomal system... key regulator" | CENTRAL THESIS: v-ATPase failure           | Pericytes clear A-beta via LRP1-to-lysosomal degradation | VZV gM blocks autophagy      |
| **N (Neurovascular)** | "failing vascular system contributes"             | Microglial invasion after PANTHOS death    | CENTRAL THESIS: BBB breakdown, pericyte loss             | HSV-1 damages BBB, pericytes |
| **E (Export)**        | Glymphatic drainage mentioned                     | Failed clearance of autophagic cargo       | A-beta clearance failure across damaged BBB              | --                           |
| **I (Insulation)**    | "oligodendrocytes all contribute"                 | --                                         | --                                                       | HSV-1 LAT suppresses tau     |
| **Fe (Iron)**         | --                                                | LMP releases lysosomal iron -> ferroptosis | --                                                       | --                           |

**The Key Convergence: Reversibility -> Irreversibility Transition**

All major frameworks implicitly recognize that AD involves a transition from compensable dysfunction to irreversible degeneration:

- **De Strooper**: "perturbations initially amenable to compensatory feedback transform into irreversible, progressive neurodegeneration"
- **Nixon**: Once lysosomal membrane permeabilization occurs, the neuron is committed to death
- **Zlokovic**: Once pericyte loss crosses threshold, the vicious cycle becomes self-sustaining
- **Itzhaki**: Taiwan data shows prevention works but VALAD trial shows treatment of established disease fails

FELINE's synthesis contribution: These are all describing the **same transition point** from different vantage points. The irreversibility threshold is when L layer (lysosomal clearance capacity) becomes so compromised that it cannot process new damage, regardless of whether upstream insults continue.

**FELINE Is Not Competing -- It Is Translating:**

| Old Framing                       | New Framing                                                                                           |
| --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| "Here's my theory of Alzheimer's" | "Here's how De Strooper, Nixon, Zlokovic, and Itzhaki are all correct and describing the same system" |
| Proposing a novel hypothesis      | Synthesizing siloed literature into unified framework                                                 |
| Competing with major labs         | Translating between them                                                                              |

#### 1.4.4 Why FELINE Is Tighter Than Generic Hypotheses

FELINE incorporates elements from multiple existing hypotheses, but most of those hypotheses describe processes that are *downstream* of iron dysregulation. The framework focuses on the *driver* (Fe) and selectively incorporates only the immune mechanisms that amplify iron-mediated damage at specific defense layers.

This selectivity is supported by Mendelian randomization evidence. Huang et al. (2023, Neurology 100(6):e568-e581, [DOI: 10.1212/WNL.0000000000201489](https://doi.org/10.1212/WNL.0000000000201489), [PMID: 36384659](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36384659)) analyzed data from >2 million participants and >1.1 million individuals across 15 GWAS datasets. They found that the association between inflammatory diseases and AD risk "is unlikely to be causal and may be a result of confounding." Generic "neuroinflammation" does not cause AD.

But specific immune mechanisms *are* causal within FELINE's layer structure:

| FELINE Layer                | Immune Mechanism                                                              | Role                                                                                                                                                | Why It Matters                                                                                              |
| --------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **N (Neurovascular)** | BAM/PVM clearance-to-containment switch                                       | Border-associated macrophages attempt phagocytic clearance; when overwhelmed, switch to compact plaque formation (Hawkes 2009, Uekawa 2023)         | Not generic inflammation -- specific myeloid program analogous to TB containment biology (see Appendix 2.6) |
| **N (Neurovascular)** | TSP-1/TGF-β fibrotic loop                                                    | Thrombospondin-1 in composite deposits activates latent TGF-β, driving basement membrane fibrosis (Wyss-Coray 1997, 2000; Murphy-Ullrich 2018)     | Deposit actively remodels its microenvironment; explains why CAA vessels show fibrotic thickening           |
| **N (Neurovascular)** | Fibrin P2 epitope → CD11b microglial activation                              | Fibrin exposes cryptic P2 epitope (γ377-395) that binds CD11b/CD18 on microglia, triggering ROS and spine elimination (Davalos 2012, Merlini 2019) | Specific epitope-receptor interaction, not generic coagulation response                                     |
| **I (Insulation)**    | Complement tagging (C1q binds PS on ferroptotic OL membranes)                 | Tags damaged myelin for phagocytic destruction; blocks OPC remyelination via Wnt                                                                    | Not generic inflammation -- specific molecular recognition of iron-damaged membranes (see Appendix 2.1)     |
| **E (Export)**        | Hepcidin-mediated ferroportin degradation                                     | Inflammatory hepcidin internalizes the iron export channel on astrocyte endfeet                                                                     | Converts a protective export mechanism into an iron trap                                                    |
| **L (Lysosome)**      | IL-1α + TNF + C1q convert astrocytes to A1 phenotype (Liddelow et al. 2017)  | A1 astrocytes lose neuroprotective functions including iron handling                                                                                | Specific cytokine triad, not generic inflammation                                                           |
| **Fe**                | Ferroptosis-modified self-proteins (OSEs) trigger adaptive immune recognition | T cells target ferroptosis neoepitopes, amplifying damage                                                                                           | Antigen-specific response to iron-damaged tissue (see Appendix 2.3)                                         |

The generic iron hypothesis proposes that iron accumulation causes neurodegeneration but does not explain *where* iron accumulates, *why* the brain cannot export it, or *why* chelation (FAIRPARK-II) made things worse. The generic immune/neuroinflammation hypothesis proposes that inflammation drives neurodegeneration but cannot explain why MR finds no causal relationship, why broad anti-inflammatories fail in trials, or why some immune mechanisms (microglial plaque compaction) are protective.

FELINE resolves both: iron is the driver, but the immune system is the amplifier at specific, identifiable nodes. Targeting "neuroinflammation" broadly fails because it suppresses both pathogenic mechanisms (hepcidin upregulation, complement-mediated myelin destruction) and protective ones (microglial iron sequestration, plaque compaction). The correct therapeutic approach targets the specific immune-iron interactions at each layer, not inflammation generically.

#### 1.4.5 Iron Universality

**The core claim being tested**: FELINE proposes ferroptosis (iron-mediated cell death) as the universal final common pathway. If neurodegeneration can occur WITHOUT iron involvement, this challenges the claim.

**Systematic examination**:

| Disease                        | Iron Involved?                                             | FELINE Entry Point  | Key Reference            |
| ------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------ |
| **Alzheimer's disease**  | YES - brain iron elevated, ferroportin down                | N, L, E             | Consensus                |
| **Parkinson's disease**  | YES - SN iron elevated                                     | N, I                | Consensus                |
| **Huntington's disease** | YES - striatal iron elevated                               | L (autophagy)       | Multiple studies         |
| **ALS**                  | YES - motor neuron iron, GPX4                              | L, I                | Consensus                |
| **Prion disease (CJD)**  | YES - "increased total and redox-active Fe(II)"            | E (hepcidin -> Fpn) | Singh 2009               |
| **PSP** (pure tauopathy) | YES - "excessive iron accumulation in all 5 brain regions" | I                   | Lee 2017                 |
| **MSA**                  | YES - "iron metabolism" dysregulation                      | I (OLs)             | Kaji 2020                |
| **Friedreich's Ataxia**  | YES - "iron dyshomeostasis... lipid peroxidation"          | L (mitochondrial)   | Portillo-Carrasquer 2025 |

**Critical finding**: In EVERY major neurodegenerative disease examined, iron dysregulation is documented.

**Honest assessment**: The universality of iron involvement is striking but could represent:

1. True causality (FELINE is correct)
2. Common downstream marker (iron is consequence, not cause)
3. Publication bias (iron-negative findings not published)

The distinguishing test: Does preventing iron dysregulation prevent neurodegeneration? This is why ferroptosis inhibitor trials are so important.

#### 1.4.6 Testable Predictions From Synthesis

| Prediction                                                                       | Framework Integration              | Status                              |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Antivirals prevent but don't treat AD                                            | Viral + Lysosomal                  | Consistent (Taiwan vs. VALAD)       |
| Lysosomal acidification agents + NAD+ boosters should synergize                  | PANTHOS + FELINE L-layer           | Testable                            |
| Oligodendrocyte-targeted therapies benefit AD independent of amyloid             | Cellular Phase + FELINE I-layer    | Testable                            |
| Iron chelation fails if lysosomes can't process chelated iron                    | PANTHOS + FELINE Fe/L interaction  | Arguably confirmed (FAIRPARK-II)    |
| Pericyte-protective interventions should slow AD                                 | Vascular + FELINE N-layer          | Being tested (Korte 2024)           |
| AD patients with preserved lysosomal function respond better to any intervention | PANTHOS + FELINE threshold concept | Testable (biomarker stratification) |

