## 2. Core Mechanisms

### 2.1 Iron Biology Fundamentals

#### Iron Chemistry and the Fenton Reaction

Iron is uniquely dangerous among transition metals because it readily cycles between two oxidation states (Fe²⁺ and Fe³⁺) under physiological conditions. This redox cycling drives the **Fenton reaction**, the central chemical event in ferroptosis:

**Fe²⁺ + H₂O₂ → Fe³⁺ + OH⁻ + OH•**

The hydroxyl radical (OH•) produced is the most reactive oxygen species in biology. It attacks polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) in membranes, initiating lipid peroxidation chain reactions. Unlike copper (which also undergoes Fenton chemistry), iron is:

- **Abundant**: The most concentrated transition metal in the brain (~200 μg/g in some regions)
- **Compartmentalized**: Stored in ferritin, lysosomes, and mitochondria, each with distinct release triggers
- **Enzymatically recycled**: Cellular reductases continuously regenerate Fe²⁺ from Fe³⁺, sustaining the reaction
- **Self-amplifying**: Lipid peroxidation products (4-HNE, MDA) damage ferritin and lysosomes, releasing more iron

This chemistry explains why iron *mislocalization* (not just total iron) drives neurodegeneration: iron safely stored in ferritin is inert, but the same iron released into the cytosol or extracellular space becomes a ferroptosis catalyst.

#### Lipid Peroxidation

- PUFA-rich membranes (especially in OLs/myelin) are vulnerable to iron-catalyzed peroxidation
- cPLA2 (cytosolic phospholipase A2) liberates arachidonic acid, providing substrate for peroxidation
- ACSL4 re-esterifies oxidized lipids into membranes, propagating damage

**The cPLA2 pathway**: cPLA2 is the rate-limiting enzyme that liberates arachidonic acid (AA) and adrenic acid (AdA) from membrane phospholipids. These PUFAs are then oxidized by iron-catalyzed Fenton chemistry and enzymatic LOX activity. ACSL4 re-esterifies oxidized lipids back into membranes, propagating damage to adjacent lipids. This creates a chain reaction of lipid peroxidation that, once initiated, is self-amplifying until GPX4 detoxifies the peroxides or the cell dies.

**cPLA2 knockout prevents AD pathology** (Bhattacharjee et al. 2008, Nat Neurosci, [DOI: 10.1038/nn.2213](https://doi.org/10.1038/nn.2213)):

> "Neuronal expression of familial AD-mutant hAPP causes synaptic dysfunction, inflammation and abnormal cerebrovascular tone. cPLA2 reduction ameliorated cognitive deficits in hAPP mice"

Bhattacharjee et al. 2012 (Neurobiol Aging, [DOI: 10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2011.12.008](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2011.12.008)):

> "cPLA2 gene inactivation prevented the alterations of cognitive abilities and the reduction of hippocampal synaptic markers upon A-beta oligomer injection"

**cPLA2 is elevated at AD synapses** (Ma et al. 2025, Alzheimers Dement, [DOI: 10.1002/alz.70667](https://doi.org/10.1002/alz.70667)):

> "Elevated cPLA2 (cPLA2-alpha and cPLA2-beta) in AD synaptosomes... cPLA2 overactivation at synapses, dendrites, and excitatory neuronal somas is associated with synaptic loss, neuritic plaques and neurodegeneration"
> "cPLA2 inhibitor ASB14780 reversed A-beta-42O-induced synaptic marker reduction"

**APOE4 increases cPLA2 activity**: APOE4 astrocytes show greater cPLA2 phosphorylation, activity, and LTB4 levels compared to APOE3, with cPLA2 inhibition reducing LTB4, ROS, and iNOS.

| Factor           | Effect on cPLA2                           | Effect on Ferroptosis                                   |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| A-beta oligomers | Increased cPLA2 activation                | Increased AA substrate -> increased vulnerability       |
| APOE4            | Increased cPLA2 activity (via p38 MAPK)   | Increased AA release -> increased lipid peroxidation    |
| Ca2+ influx      | Increased cPLA2 translocation to membrane | Increased AA release -> excitotoxicity-ferroptosis link |
| Iron             | No direct effect on cPLA2                 | COMBINES with AA -> Fenton chemistry                    |
| cPLA2 inhibitors | Decreased AA release                      | Decreased substrate for ferroptosis -> PROTECTION       |

**Why cPLA2 explains multiple AD findings**:

1. **Excitotoxicity-Ferroptosis Link**: Glutamate -> Ca2+ influx -> cPLA2 activation -> AA release -> lipid peroxidation. This connects the calcium excitotoxicity and ferroptosis hypotheses.
2. **APOE4 Risk Beyond Lipid Transport**: APOE4 increases cPLA2 activity independent of its A-beta clearance role, providing additional substrate for ferroptosis.
3. **A-beta Oligomer Toxicity Mechanism**: A-beta oligomers activate cPLA2 -> AA release -> explains how soluble A-beta (not plaques) is toxic, and why cPLA2 knockout blocks A-beta neurotoxicity.

**Therapeutic implications**:

| Strategy                             | Mechanism                                   | Status                                    |
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| cPLA2 inhibitors (ASB14780, AACOCF3) | Block AA release                            | Preclinical; cognitive protection in mice |
| Omega-3 supplementation              | Compete with AA for membrane incorporation  | Mixed clinical results                    |
| GPX4 activators                      | Detoxify lipid peroxides (downstream of AA) | Active development                        |
| Combined cPLA2 + iron management     | Block BOTH substrate AND catalyst           | NOT YET TESTED                            |

#### Iron Compartmentalization: Why Chelation Fails

The FELINE model reframes the "iron overload" concept as **iron mislocalization**:

| Conventional View          | FELINE View                                   |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Too much iron in the brain | Iron in wrong compartments                    |
| Solution: remove iron      | Solution: restore proper compartmentalization |
| Chelation should help      | Chelation worsens (removes functional iron)   |

**The FAIRPARK-II validation**: Deferiprone (iron chelator) **worsened** clinical outcomes in Parkinson's disease despite successfully reducing brain iron on MRI. Deferiprone relocated iron OUT of cells to the bloodstream, worsening functional iron deficiency while leaving lysosomal iron trapped.

**Critical quote from Ayton et al. (Brain 2025)**:

> "Results from these trials have challenged this paradigm, with deferiprone markedly worsening outcomes in patients with Alzheimer's disease and, in certain contexts, patients with Parkinson's disease. These findings underscore the vital role of iron for brain health."

#### The Astrocyte Iron Distribution Hub

Astrocytes are iron DISTRIBUTORS, not accumulators. The ceruloplasmin-ferroportin system in astrocytes is the key pathway for brain iron homeostasis. **Note (February 2026 correction)**: Astrocyte Fpn/Cp exports iron FROM astrocytes INTO brain interstitial fluid, distributing it to neurons and oligodendrocytes. Iron does NOT exit the brain via this route; the actual exit is via CSF/glymphatic drainage.

Normal iron flow: Blood -> BBB endothelium -> Astrocyte endfeet -> Ceruloplasmin oxidizes Fe2+ to Fe3+ -> Ferroportin distributes into ISF -> Transferrin binds Fe3+ -> delivers to OLs/neurons.

**Astrocyte ceruloplasmin knockout** (Cheli et al. 2023, [DOI: 10.1002/glia.24424](https://doi.org/10.1002/glia.24424)):

- Hypomyelination during postnatal development
- Iron deficiency in oligodendrocytes (OLs can't get iron they need)
- Exacerbated myelin deficits through first 2 postnatal months
- In AGED mice: iron ACCUMULATION + neurodegeneration

**Astrocyte ferroportin knockout** (Schulz et al. 2012, [DOI: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5328-11.2012](https://doi.org/10.1523/JNEUROSCI.5328-11.2012)):

- REDUCED remyelination after LPC demyelination
- OPC proliferation reduced
- Microglia couldn't express TNF-alpha and IL-1beta (need iron)
- Astrocytes couldn't produce FGF-2 and IGF-1 (repair factors)

**Key insight from Cheli et al. 2020** (DOI: 10.1177/1759091420962681):

> "A small proportion of astrocytes stain for iron... This observation supports the notion that astrocytes may be mostly involved in iron trafficking and not iron accumulation"

This confirms astrocytes function as iron transit stations, not storage sites. When transit fails (endfoot damage, hepcidin upregulation), iron cannot reach its proper destinations.

#### Hepcidin-Ferroportin Axis

Hepcidin is the master regulator of iron export via ferroportin:

**Hepcidin's dual role**:

- Systemic hepcidin: Produced by liver, regulates gut iron absorption
- Brain hepcidin: Produced locally, regulates iron distribution from astrocytes and iron import at the BBB

**When brain hepcidin fails**: Upregulated hepcidin causes ferroportin degradation on astrocyte endfeet, blocking iron distribution from astrocytes to neurons and oligodendrocytes. This is the E-layer mechanism observed in prion disease (Chaudhary 2021: "upregulation of brain hepcidin plays a significant role in iron accumulation and associated neurotoxicity").

**The causal chain**:

1. Inflammation/infection -> hepcidin upregulation in brain
2. Hepcidin -> ferroportin internalization/degradation on endfeet
3. Ferroportin loss -> iron trapped in astrocytes, cannot reach neurons/OLs
4. Iron accumulates in parenchyma -> ferroptosis

#### Bai 2024: Brain-Specific Hepcidin Conditional Knockout

Bai et al. 2024 demonstrated using brain-specific hepcidin conditional knockout (cKO) mice:

- Brain-specific hepcidin loss -> ferroportin upregulation in astrocytes -> excessive iron distribution into ISF
- Brain iron depletion with elevated peripheral iron
- Cognitive deficits from functional brain iron deficiency
- Confirms brain hepcidin is an independent regulator of brain iron homeostasis, separate from liver hepcidin

**FELINE implication**: The hepcidin-ferroportin axis operates as a LOCAL regulatory system at astrocyte endfeet. Inflammation upregulates brain hepcidin -> ferroportin degradation -> iron trapping. This is distinct from (and can be opposite to) systemic hepcidin regulation.

#### The Endothelial Iron Trap

BBB dysfunction creates a compartmentalized iron dysregulation where iron gets trapped in endothelial cells.

**Clinical Observation** (Liu et al. 2024, [DOI: 10.1111/cns.14925](https://doi.org/10.1111/cns.14925)): In cerebral small vessel disease (CSVD) patients:

| Peripheral Marker   | Change    | Interpretation                    |
| ------------------- | --------- | --------------------------------- |
| Serum ferritin (SF) | INCREASED | Iron stored, not mobilized        |
| TIBC                | INCREASED | Transport capacity up but unused  |
| UIBC                | INCREASED | Binding sites unfilled            |
| Serum iron (SI)     | DECREASED | Iron sequestered, not circulating |

Correlation with white matter injury: TIBC/UIBC positively correlated with Fazekas WMH score. Same pattern in AIS and CAA patients. Zinc and copper levels stable (iron-specific phenomenon).

**Mouse Model Reveals Mechanism** (UCCAO model):

- Peripheral blood mirrors human data: increased SF, TIBC, UIBC; decreased SI
- Brain tissue shows DECREASED iron concentration (ICP-MS), decreased ferritin, transferrin, FPN-1
- TFRC INCREASED (cells desperately trying to import iron)
- Contradiction: Peripheral iron surplus, brain iron deficiency

**The Endothelial Trapping Mechanism**:

1. Hypoperfusion damages white matter -> myelin debris
2. Endothelial cells phagocytose myelin debris (non-professional phagocytes attempting cleanup)
3. Myelin is iron-rich -> endothelial cells become iron-overloaded
4. Iron-overloaded endothelial cells undergo ferroptosis:
   - TEM shows mitochondria with shrunken volume, condensed density, reduced cristae, ruptured outer membrane
   - Lipid hydroperoxides elevated in ipsilateral BVECs
   - BVECs comprise 87.82+/-9.00% of lipid ROS+ cells in UCCAO brains
5. Ferroptotic endothelial cells can't transport iron -> iron trapped in BBB
6. OLs become iron-deficient:
   - MOG+ myelinating OLs: decreased ferritin, increased TFRC, decreased FPN-1
   - IV FITC-TF less accessible to PDGFRa+ OPCs and CC1+ mature OLs
7. Iron deficiency impairs remyelination -> more myelin debris -> vicious cycle

**In Vitro Confirmation**:

- Organotypic brain slices (OGD model): Remyelination enhanced by mock BVECs; remyelination ABOLISHED by myelin-pretreated BVECs
- Iron gradient model: Myelin-engulfing BVECs impair iron transport to OPCs; OPC maturation downregulated; OPC proliferation unaffected (problem is MATURATION, not proliferation)

**Therapeutic Proof: Intranasal Iron Delivery**

Intranasal holo-transferrin (bypasses BBB):

- Delivers iron directly to parenchyma
- Upregulates ferritin in oligodendroglial lineage cells
- Enhances OPC proliferation and differentiation
- Increases NG2+ OPCs and CC1+ OLs in corpus callosum
- Upregulates MBP, PLP, MOG, MAG expression
- Improves MBP/SMI32 ratio and G-ratio (TEM)
- Reduces myelin defects (split layers, discontinuity, detachment)
- Improves novel object recognition (cognitive function)

Critically, intranasal hTF also reverses peripheral ferrokinetic inactivity (normalizes SF, TIBC, UIBC, SI), proving the entire peripheral iron storage pattern is a RESPONSE to blocked brain delivery, not a primary abnormality.

#### Peripheral Iron Biomarkers: A Window into Brain Iron Transport

The endothelial iron trap finding creates a diagnostic opportunity:

| Peripheral Marker        | Brain Correlate        | Interpretation                               |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Increased TIBC           | Increased WMH severity | Iron transport capacity increased but unused |
| Increased UIBC           | Increased WMH severity | Iron binding sites unfilled                  |
| Increased serum ferritin | Increased WMH severity | Iron being stored, not delivered             |
| Decreased serum iron     | Increased WMH severity | Iron sequestered, not circulating            |

Key insight: Demyelination CAUSES this peripheral pattern, not vice versa. Artificially increasing TIBC does NOT cause demyelination.

This pattern appears across multiple conditions (arteriosclerotic CSVD, acute ischemic stroke, cerebral amyloid angiopathy), suggesting a common NVU iron transport dysfunction mechanism.

**Potential clinical applications**:

- Screening for subclinical white matter disease
- Monitoring response to NVU-targeted therapies
- Identifying patients who might benefit from direct brain iron delivery
- Stratifying patients for clinical trials

#### Oligodendrocyte Centrality

> See diagram: `diagrams/oligodendrocyte-centrality.mmd`

Oligodendrocytes have the highest iron requirements of any brain cell. Iron is essential for:

- Cholesterol synthesis (rate-limiting for myelination)
- Fatty acid synthesis
- Energy metabolism (cytochrome oxidase)
- Cofactor for enzymes in myelin wrapping

**The vulnerability trade-off**: The same metabolic demand that makes OLs essential for brain function makes them the most vulnerable cell type to ferroptosis:

| Feature                              | Implication                              |
| ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| Highest iron content in brain        | First to experience iron-mediated damage |
| High PUFA content (myelin membranes) | More substrate for lipid peroxidation    |
| Low baseline GPX4 expression         | Minimal ferroptosis defense              |
| High metabolic rate                  | Greater oxidative stress                 |
| Dependent on iron-sulfur clusters    | Vulnerable to iron mislocalization       |

**The Iron-Myelination-Ferroptosis Triangle**: Iron is required for myelination, but the iron-rich environment makes OLs vulnerable to ferroptosis. When OLs die, they release their iron stores into the extracellular space. This released iron damages neighboring cells and triggers further ferroptosis, creating a self-amplifying cascade.

**Evidence for iron release from OLs** (Haider et al. 2014):

> "Iron was stored primarily within oligodendrocytes and myelin fibres and released upon demyelination... In the course of myelin and oligodendrocyte destruction, iron is liberated into the extracellular space and in part converted into the potentially toxic ferrous form."

#### Oligodendrocyte Iron Requirements in Detail

Myelination is extraordinarily energy-intensive. OLs must synthesize massive amounts of cholesterol, fatty acids, sphingolipids, and myelin proteins. All require iron-dependent enzymes:

- **Fatty acid synthase** -- requires iron
- **Stearoyl-CoA desaturase** -- iron-containing enzyme
- **Cholesterol synthesis enzymes** -- iron-dependent
- **Plasmalogen synthesis** -- requires selenoproteins (GPX4)
- **Cytochrome c oxidase** -- iron + copper
- **Fe-S cluster proteins** -- electron transport chain
- **TCA cycle enzymes** -- iron-dependent

**Iron Deficiency Causes Hypomyelination** (proof of requirement):

Guitart et al. 2019 (DOI: 10.1002/glia.23647) showed that developmental iron deficiency causes:

- OLs stuck in immature state (fail to mature)
- Increased Hes5 (blocks OL maturation)
- Decreased Sox10 and Olig1 (pro-maturation factors)
- Selective death of immature OLs
- Result: hypomyelination and impaired sensorimotor function

Rosato-Siri et al. 2023 (DOI: 10.1007/s12035-022-03149-y):

- Iron-deficient OLs have mitochondrial dysfunction
- Decreased spare respiratory capacity
- Increased ROS production
- Cannot generate enough energy to myelinate

#### The Critical Discovery: OLs Protect Neurons from Iron

Mukherjee et al. 2020 (Cell Metabolism, [DOI: 10.1016/j.cmet.2020.05.019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cmet.2020.05.019)) -- paradigm-shifting finding:

> "Oligodendrocytes provide antioxidant defense function for neurons by secreting ferritin heavy chain"

The pathway:

1. OLs accumulate iron (needed for myelin synthesis)
2. Excess iron stored in ferritin heavy chain (FTH1)
3. FTH1 packaged into extracellular vesicles
4. Vesicles released to neurons
5. Neurons receive "iron insurance" against ferroptosis
6. Disrupting this -> neuronal loss + oxidative damage

This means OLs serve TWO insulation functions:

1. **Barrier insulation**: Myelin physically shields axons from extracellular ROS
2. **Iron insulation**: FTH1 export provides neurons with iron-buffering capacity

OL death is therefore a **double hit**: Loss of the myelin barrier (axons exposed to oxidative environment) AND loss of iron buffering for neurons.

**The OL-Ferroptosis Vulnerability Trade-off**:

OLs are inherently vulnerable to the very element they need most:

| OL Property         | Benefit              | Vulnerability             |
| ------------------- | -------------------- | ------------------------- |
| High iron content   | Enables myelination  | Ferroptosis substrate     |
| High lipid content  | Makes myelin         | Lipid peroxidation target |
| High metabolic rate | Supports synthesis   | ROS generation            |
| GPX4 dependence     | Prevents ferroptosis | Single point of failure   |

Ma et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1016/j.abb.2025.110509):

> "GPX4 [is] recognized as the master regulator of ferroptosis, a non-apoptotic form of cell death characterized by iron-dependent lipid peroxidation... mutations in many genes mediating these processes converge on a phenotype characterized by hypomyelination, cognitive impairment, neurodegeneration, and motor deficits."

#### The Four Iron-Protein Hypotheses

Four apparently competing hypotheses about iron-protein interactions are all correct within FELINE:

| Hypothesis                        | Claim                                                    | FELINE Layer             | Key Evidence                                              |
| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| A-beta as iron concentrator       | A-beta binds and concentrates iron, plaques sequester it | I (emergency buffering)  | Fe-A-beta coordination chemistry                          |
| Tau as iron regulator             | Tau mediates iron efflux; aggregation traps iron         | I (compartmentalization) | Tau has iron-binding motif, Fe3+ promotes tau aggregation |
| Alpha-synuclein as ferrireductase | Alpha-syn reduces Fe3+ to Fe2+                           | I (iron handling)        | Ferrireductase activity demonstrated                      |
| Ferritin dysfunction              | Ferritinophagy releases stored iron                      | L (lysosomal)            | Ferritinophagy drives ferroptosis                         |

FELINE resolves the apparent contradiction: Each protein represents a different aspect of the Insulation layer's iron-handling capacity. When any of these systems fails, the others compensate -- until multiple fail simultaneously.

#### A-beta's Third Protective Function: Fibrinogen Neutralization

Beyond iron concentration/sequestration and antimicrobial activity, A-beta serves as a vascular defense protein: it binds fibrinogen with nanomolar affinity (Kd = 26.3 nM, Ahn et al. 2010), sequestering blood-derived fibrinogen that leaks through the compromised BBB. Free fibrinogen in brain parenchyma activates microglia via its cryptic P2 epitope binding CD11b/CD18, triggering ROS generation and dendritic spine elimination independent of amyloid plaques (Merlini et al. 2019). A-beta-fibrinogen binding prevents this microglial activation but creates fibrinolysis-resistant vascular deposits (CAA). Hereditary CAA mutations (Dutch E22Q, Iowa D23N) increase A-beta-fibrinogen binding up to 50-fold, directly linking enhanced binding to worse vascular disease (Cajamarca et al. 2020). Three proteins (A-beta, fibrinogen, tau) independently evolved iron-catalyzed alpha-helix to beta-sheet conversion as compartment-specific damage responses; AD arises when compartment boundaries fail and these defense systems collide. None are true prions: tau seeding is exhausted after one generation without RNA cofactors (Fichou et al. 2018), A-beta requires >1000x physiological concentration for spontaneous aggregation, and fibrin amyloid conversion requires inflammagen triggers (LPS, iron, spike protein). The disease is in the compartment conditions, not in the proteins. See Appendix 2.5 for the complete A-beta-fibrinogen-iron convergence analysis, including the compartment breach theory, anti-fibrin immunotherapy (THN391), and AD-Long COVID molecular bridge via fibrin.

#### HFE H63D: When "Iron Overload" Mutations Protect the Brain

The H63D variant of the HFE gene provides a natural experiment:

- H63D carriers have mildly increased iron absorption
- H63D is counterintuitively **protective** against AD in some populations
- Combined with APOE4, H63D shows complex interactions

**Resolution**: H63D increases iron availability to mitochondria and myelin-synthesizing machinery. In the context of FELINE's "functional iron deficiency" model, mild systemic iron increase actually helps cells that are starving for properly compartmentalized iron.

**The APOE4 Context Changes Everything**: APOE4 impairs both iron recycling (via reduced TREM2 function) and BBB integrity (via CypA-MMP9 pathway). H63D + APOE4 creates a scenario where increased iron absorption meets impaired iron handling, producing net harm rather than benefit.

#### Dexras1-DMT1 Pathway

Excitotoxicity drives pathological iron entry through a specific molecular pathway:

1. NMDA receptor over-activation
2. Dexras1 activation (via nitric oxide signaling)
3. DMT1 (divalent metal transporter 1) upregulation
4. Pathological iron uptake into neurons

This explains why:

- **Low-dose ketamine works**: Blocks hyperactive NMDA circuits, reducing Dexras1-mediated iron entry
- **High-dose ketamine fails**: Causes compensatory NMDA upregulation
- **Memantine shows modest benefit**: Partial NMDA antagonism reduces but does not eliminate pathological iron entry

#### Adaptive Immunity as Active FELINE Layer Modulator

The adaptive immune system is not merely reactive to iron-driven damage -- it bidirectionally modulates all five FELINE defense layers. CD8 T cells show stage-dependent effects: early-stage effector CD8 T cells suppress microglial DAM transition via CCL5-CCR5 signaling, impairing amyloid clearance (Ohyagi et al. 2025), while late-stage exhausted CD8 TRM cells permit DAM transition and support clearance. Regulatory T cells (Tregs) directly boost the I layer by enhancing microglial phagocytosis via PD-L1/PD-1 signaling (Yeapuri et al. 2023; Zuo et al. 2025). The adaptive immune response maps onto every FELINE layer: IFN-gamma worsens Fe-layer compartmentalization via hepcidin induction, PSMB8-mediated GPX4 reduction worsens L-layer vulnerability, T cell infiltration worsens N-layer integrity, and pro-inflammatory cytokines impair E-layer export. FELINE predicts that the antigens driving brain-infiltrating CD8 T cells are ferroptosis-generated oxidation-specific epitopes (OSEs) -- self-proteins covalently modified by lipid peroxidation byproducts (4-HNE, MDA adducts) -- connecting three previously siloed literatures (atherosclerosis OSE paradigm, RA AMPA paradigm, cancer immunogenic cell death). See Appendix 2.3 for the complete analysis including the CD8 temporal switch, stage-aware therapeutic implications, and the OSE cross-domain synthesis.

### 2.2 Lysosomal-Ferroptosis Connection

#### Lysosomal Membrane Permeabilization (LMP)

Lysosomes are the primary iron storage organelle in cells. When lysosomal membranes fail (LMP), stored iron floods the cytosol, triggering ferroptosis.

**The NAD+/SIRT3/GPX4 Axis**:

1. NAD+ is required for SIRT3 function
2. SIRT3 deacetylates GPX4, keeping it active
3. Active GPX4 detoxifies lipid peroxides (prevents ferroptosis)
4. NAD+ also feeds NADPH production -> GSH synthesis (GPX4 substrate)

When NAD+ is depleted (by aging, viral infection, or metabolic stress), this entire chain collapses:

- SIRT3 inactive -> GPX4 hyperacetylated -> reduced activity
- NADPH depleted -> GSH depleted -> GPX4 has no substrate
- Lipid peroxides accumulate -> ferroptosis

**Evidence for SIRT3-GPX4 axis** (Guo et al. 2024, Redox Biology, [DOI: 10.1016/j.redox.2024.103179](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.redox.2024.103179)):

- SIRT3 (NAD+-dependent deacetylase) was reduced in cadmium-induced kidney injury
- Mitochondrial GPX4 acetylation was ELEVATED
- Mitochondrial GPX4 protein was REDUCED
- NMN pretreatment alleviated GPX4 acetylation and ferroptosis

> "Mitochondrial GPX4 acetylation, probably caused by SIRT3 downregulation, is involved in Cd-evoked renal cell ferroptosis"

**NMN directly enhances GPX4** (Feng et al. 2021, [DOI: 10.1016/j.bbadis.2021.166287](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bbadis.2021.166287)):

- NMN rescued imbalanced NAD+/NADH ratio
- NMN recruited GSH production
- NMN promoted resistance to lipid peroxidation in a GPX4-dependent manner

> "NMN recruits GSH to enhance GPX4-mediated ferroptosis defense"

#### The NAD Kinase (NADK) Hub

Chen et al. 2025 (Antioxidants, [DOI: 10.3390/antiox14121396](https://doi.org/10.3390/antiox14121396)) demonstrated:

- NADK inhibition (thioNAM) -> depleted NADP(H) -> sensitized cells to ferroptosis
- NADK knockdown -> reduced NADP(H) -> amplified lipid peroxidation
- NADK overexpression -> restored NADPH/GSH -> rescued ferroptosis
- NADK was essential for G6PD- and ME1-mediated NADPH production

> "NADK is a metabolic hub in ferroptosis regulation, bridging NMN-driven NAD salvage to NADPH synthesis via G6PD/ME1"

**Two parallel pathways from NAD+ to ferroptosis resistance**:

**Pathway 1**: NAD+ -> SIRT3 -> GPX4 deacetylation -> active GPX4 -> detoxifies lipid peroxides

**Pathway 2**: NAD+ -> NADK -> NADP+ -> G6PD/ME1 -> NADPH -> Glutathione reductase -> GSH regeneration -> GPX4 substrate

Both pathways converge on GPX4. Both fail when NAD+ is depleted.

#### NAD+ to Lysosomal Biogenesis

NAD+ also links to lysosomal function via a distinct pathway:

1. NAD+ restoration (via P7C3-A20/NAMPT)
2. SIRT1 activation (NAD+-dependent deacetylase)
3. SIRT1 deacetylates TFEB (Transcription Factor EB)
4. Deacetylated TFEB translocates to nucleus
5. TFEB binds CLEAR motif (Coordinated Lysosomal Expression and Regulation)
6. Transcription of lysosomal/autophagy genes: LAMP1, LAMP2, v-ATPase subunits, cathepsins, BECN1, ATG5, LC3, UVRAG, RAB7

**Critical distinction: biogenesis vs. repair**:

What NAD+/SIRT1/TFEB CAN do:

- Promote NEW lysosomal biogenesis (synthesizing fresh lysosomes)
- Upregulate lysosomal genes (cathepsins, LAMP proteins, v-ATPase subunits)
- Increase autophagosome-lysosome fusion efficiency
- Clear protein aggregates (if functional lysosomes exist)

What NAD+/SIRT1/TFEB probably CANNOT do:

- Fix existing damaged lysosomes with oxidized v-ATPase
- Clear accumulated lipofuscin (permanently clogs old lysosomes)
- Reverse PSEN1/2-mediated acidification defects
- Restore cathepsin activity in lysosomes with elevated pH

This distinction is critical for understanding why P7C3-A20 shows dramatic effects in mouse models (short disease duration, limited lysosomal damage) but may show attenuated effects in human trials (decades of accumulated damage).

**Evidence for early lysosomal dysfunction** (Transl Neurodegener 2023, [DOI: 10.1186/s40035-023-00362-0](https://doi.org/10.1186/s40035-023-00362-0)):

> "Early lysosomal acidification dysfunction occurs well before neurodegeneration. Mice expressing mutant human APP or PS1 consistently show early faulty lysosomal acidification characterized by the PANTHOS pattern, which was detectable as early as 5-6 months before extracellular A-beta deposition."

**Oxidized cathepsins in AD** (Front Mol Biosci 2024, [DOI: 10.3389/fmolb.2024.1490275](https://doi.org/10.3389/fmolb.2024.1490275)):

> "Cathepsin D was found oxidized in the AD brain. Moreover, the oxidized V-ATPase was also found, which indicates that the impairment of cathepsin D enzymatic activity is related to the incorrect lysosome acidification."

#### The Lysosomal Bottleneck in Human Translation

| Parameter                        | 5xFAD/PS19 Mice | Human AD Patient |
| -------------------------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |
| Disease duration at treatment    | Months          | Decades          |
| Lysosomal damage accumulation    | Limited         | Extensive        |
| Lipofuscin burden                | Minimal         | Substantial      |
| Oxidized cathepsins              | Some            | Widespread       |
| v-ATPase oxidation               | Acute           | Chronic          |
| New lysosome generation capacity | High            | Reduced (aging)  |

This explains the recurring pattern: mouse models show dramatic reversal because treatment starts when 1-2 layers are damaged. Human trials show modest benefit because treatment starts when 4-5 layers have sustained decades of damage.

**Combination therapy implication**: P7C3-A20 (NAD+ restoration) + C381 (UCSF compound, direct lysosomal acidification) may be more effective than either alone. C381 physically targets the lysosome and promotes lysosomal acidification, addressing the damaged lysosomes that NAD+ cannot repair.

> "Small molecule C381 targets the lysosome to reduce inflammation and ameliorate disease in models of neurodegeneration... C381 physically targets the lysosome, promotes lysosomal acidification, increases breakdown of lysosomal cargo." -- PNAS 2022 (DOI: 10.1073/pnas.2121609119)

#### OL Ferroptosis: Specific Vulnerability Mechanisms

**AKR1C1 as Anti-Ferroptotic Defense** (Saverio et al. 2024, Redox Biol, [DOI: 10.1016/j.redox.2024.103463](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.redox.2024.103463)):

- Maturation-dependent iron accumulation in OLs acts as a pro-ferroptotic signal
- AKR1C1 (aldo-keto reductase) counters this by detoxifying lipid peroxides
- MS-related neuroinflammation downregulates AKR1C1 through miRNA mechanisms
- Result: mature OLs become MORE vulnerable to ferroptosis in inflammatory environments

**HDAC3-PDK4 Pathway** (Xu et al. 2025, [DOI: 10.1111/cns.70471](https://doi.org/10.1111/cns.70471)):

- HDAC3 (histone deacetylase 3) drives white matter ferroptosis
- Mechanism involves PDK4 (pyruvate dehydrogenase kinase 4) pathway
- HDAC3 inhibition (RGFP966) preserves myelin integrity
- Links epigenetic regulation to metabolic programming to ferroptosis

**FoxO1a-SLC7A11 Axis** (Zhao et al. 2025, Redox Biol, [DOI: 10.1016/j.redox.2025.103763](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.redox.2025.103763)):

- FoxO1a directly regulates SLC7A11 (cystine-glutamate antiporter) promoter
- SLC7A11 imports cystine for glutathione synthesis
- FoxO1a knockout -> oxidative stress -> ferroptosis in myelin
- Evolutionarily conserved in jawed vertebrates

**The Exercise Connection** (Gutierre et al. 2024, Brain Res, [DOI: 10.1016/j.brainres.2024.149419](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brainres.2024.149419)):

- In aged rats, iron overload in OLs induces ferroptosis
- Physical exercise reduces inflammaging and improves axon-myelin volume relations
- Tau, amyloid, iron, and hippocampal cells show statistical correlations
- Exercise may protect white matter partly through iron metabolism effects (E-layer intervention)

#### Complement-Mediated Myelin Loss: The F-to-L-to-I Bridge

Complement provides the molecular mechanism connecting oligodendrocyte ferroptosis to myelin phagocytosis. C1q localizes directly to myelin basic protein (MBP), with colocalization increasing significantly with age (R-squared = 0.31, p = 0.0017) and correlating with cognitive impairment in rhesus monkeys (DeVries et al. 2024). Simultaneously, the "don't eat me" signal CD47 decreases on myelin in middle age, and oligodendrocyte CD47 mRNA drops 38.7% with aging, while microglial C1qA mRNA increases 125.5%. C1q creates a vicious cycle: it tags existing myelin for phagocytic destruction via the classical cascade (C1q -> C3 -> iC3b opsonization -> CR3+ microglial phagocytosis) while simultaneously blocking OPC differentiation into replacement oligodendrocytes via Wnt/beta-catenin signaling (Gao et al. 2021). C1QA deficiency prevents obesity-induced white matter damage despite continued obesity (Graham et al. 2020), and C3aR deletion reverses hypoperfusion-induced white matter injury (Zhang et al. 2020). This connects three FELINE layers: iron overload in oligodendrocytes triggers lipid peroxidation (F layer), microglial phagocytosis of tagged myelin overloads lysosomal processing (L layer), and myelin loss plus remyelination failure produces axonal exposure (I layer). See Appendix 2.1 for the complete cascade analysis, cross-validation across disease contexts, and therapeutic targets.

#### Ferritinophagy: The Iron Release Trigger

NCOA4 (nuclear receptor coactivator 4) is the selective cargo receptor for ferritinophagy -- the autophagic degradation of ferritin to release iron. Under normal conditions, this is a homeostatic mechanism to supply iron when needed. Under pathological conditions:

1. NCOA4 expression increases (in response to iron demand or stress)
2. Ferritin is targeted for lysosomal degradation
3. Iron is released from ferritin in lysosomes
4. Released iron can trigger Fenton chemistry inside lysosomes
5. Lysosomal membrane permeabilization (LMP) follows
6. Iron floods the cytosol -> ferroptosis

**Evidence in MS** (Jhelum et al. 2023, [DOI: 10.1186/s40478-023-01617-7](https://doi.org/10.1186/s40478-023-01617-7)):

- NCOA4 expression increased at peak and progressive stages of chronic EAE
- Redox-active ferrous iron increased parallel to NCOA4
- Antioxidant pathway (system xCT, GPX4, GSH) all REDUCED
- Ferroptosis inhibitor treatment for 2 weeks improved function and pathology
- Human SPMS tissue: NCOA4+ cells express LESS ferritin -> evidence of active ferritinophagy -> iron release

### 2.3 Neurovascular Unit and Endfoot Failure

#### Pericyte-Endfoot Anatomy

The neurovascular unit (NVU) is the structural foundation for FELINE's Export layer:

- **Pericytes** wrap capillaries, regulate BBB permeability, and maintain basement membrane
- **Astrocyte endfeet** attach to the basement membrane surrounding pericytes
- **Endfoot polarization**: AQP4 and ferroportin/ceruloplasmin are specifically enriched at endfeet (not the astrocyte soma)

When pericytes die or detach:

1. Basement membrane degrades
2. Endfoot attachment weakens
3. AQP4 depolarizes (redistributes away from endfeet)
4. Ferroportin loses its perivascular localization
5. Both clearance AND iron export fail simultaneously

**Evidence (Eide 2022)**: In iNPH patients, reduced AQP4 at astrocytic endfeet, reduced dystrophin (Dp71) at perivascular endfeet, altered basement membrane, and impaired BBB integrity were all documented together, confirming coordinated endfoot failure.

#### APOE4-CypA Pathway

APOE4 is the strongest genetic risk factor for AD. FELINE explains why through the NVU:

1. APOE4 fails to suppress CypA (cyclophilin A) in pericytes
2. CypA activates MMP9 (matrix metalloproteinase 9)
3. MMP9 degrades basement membrane
4. Basement membrane loss -> endfoot detachment
5. Endfoot detachment -> AQP4 depolarization + ferroportin loss

This is a direct N-layer -> E-layer cascade. APOE4 carriers have accelerated pericyte loss, earlier endfoot failure, and correspondingly earlier onset of both glymphatic dysfunction and brain iron accumulation.

**Evidence (Long 2023)**: APOE-epsilon-4 -> AQP4 loss -> A-beta AND iron accumulation demonstrated in mouse models.

### 2.4 The Myelination-Iron-Lifespan Triangle

Human brains are ~75% white matter by volume. Oligodendrocytes (OLs), the cells that produce and maintain myelin, are the most iron-rich cells in the brain. This creates a fundamental vulnerability that connects the F-layer (iron) and I-layer (insulation) in developmental and evolutionary context.

**The developmental pattern:**

1. Late-myelinating regions (prefrontal cortex, temporal association areas) require the highest iron investment over the longest time
2. These same regions are the FIRST to show AD pathology (Braak staging)
3. Iron accumulates in heavily myelinated regions over decades of normal aging
4. When OLs die (via ferroptosis or other insults), they release their iron stores into the surrounding tissue

**The APP 5'UTR IRE connection:** APP mRNA contains an iron-responsive element (IRE) in its 5'UTR. When intracellular iron rises (e.g., from OL death releasing iron into the local environment), IRE-binding protein releases, APP translation increases, and amyloidogenic processing shifts toward A-beta production (Tsatsanis 2020). This directly links OL iron release to A-beta generation.

**The species comparison:**

| Feature                   | Human                   | Mouse                   |
| ------------------------- | ----------------------- | ----------------------- |
| White matter fraction     | ~75%                    | ~15%                    |
| Lifespan                  | ~80 years               | ~2 years                |
| OL iron accumulation time | Decades                 | Months                  |
| Aβ His13                 | Present (3 metal sites) | Arg13 (2 metal sites)   |
| Spontaneous AD            | Yes (age-dependent)     | Never                   |
| Iron-Aβ composites       | Form readily            | Cannot form effectively |

Mice have less myelin, shorter lifespans (less iron accumulation time), and rodent A-beta cannot concentrate iron (lacking His13). All three factors must align for AD: sufficient myelination to create iron-rich OLs, sufficient lifespan for iron to accumulate, and A-beta capable of concentrating the released iron. Only humans (and perhaps great apes) satisfy all three conditions.

**FELINE integration:** The myelination-iron-lifespan triangle explains why AD is uniquely human and age-dependent. It is not enough to have protein aggregation machinery; the brain must accumulate enough iron in enough myelinated tissue over enough time to overwhelm the FELINE defense layers.

### 2.5 Ferroptosis as Immune Defense: The Weapon Behind the Disease

Ferroptosis is not a design flaw. It is an ancient, deliberately deployed immune weapon that the body uses for tumor suppression, antimicrobial defense, and elimination of damaged cells. The five FELINE defense layers exist precisely to keep this weapon under control. Neurodegeneration is what happens when the safety systems around an inherently dangerous but necessary defense mechanism fail chronically.

#### Why ferroptosis exists: tumor suppression

The tumor suppressor p53 promotes ferroptosis through at least two independent pathways, separate from its canonical apoptosis and cell-cycle arrest functions:

1. **SLC7A11 repression** (Jiang et al. 2015, *Nature*): p53 directly suppresses SLC7A11, a subunit of the System Xc- cystine/glutamate antiporter. This limits cystine import, depletes glutathione, and sensitizes pre-cancerous cells to iron-dependent lipid peroxidation. A p53 mutant (3KR) that cannot induce apoptosis, senescence, or cell-cycle arrest **fully retains** ferroptosis-inducing ability and tumor suppression. Ferroptosis alone is sufficient for p53's anti-cancer function.
2. **ALOX12 pathway** (Chu et al. 2019, *Nature Cell Biology*): p53 activates ALOX12 (arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase) to trigger ferroptosis independently of GPX4 and ACSL4. Loss of a single *Alox12* allele accelerates tumorigenesis. ALOX12 mutations found in human cancers abolish this pathway.

SLC7A11 is overexpressed in many human tumors — cancer cells evolve to suppress the very mechanism designed to kill them. This confirms that ferroptosis is a primary anti-cancer defense, not collateral damage.

#### The immune system weaponizes ferroptosis

CD8+ T cells — the adaptive immune system's primary killers — use ferroptosis as a direct killing mechanism against tumor cells:

- **IFN-gamma → System Xc- downregulation** (Wang et al. 2019, *Nature*): Activated CD8+ T cells release IFN-gamma, which downregulates both SLC3A2 and SLC7A11 on target cells, collapsing their cystine import and triggering ferroptotic death. This contributes directly to anti-tumor efficacy of checkpoint immunotherapy (anti-PD-1). In patients, clinical benefit from nivolumab correlates with reduced SLC3A2 and increased IFN-gamma.
- **ACSL4 orchestration** (Liao et al. 2022, *Cancer Cell*): IFN-gamma combined with arachidonic acid induces tumor ACSL4, remodeling tumor cell membranes to incorporate more oxidation-prone PUFAs. This makes tumor cells ferroptosis-sensitive. Tumor ACSL4 deficiency accelerates cancer progression.

Meanwhile, the immune cells that deploy ferroptosis protect themselves from it:

- **M1 macrophage resistance** (Kapralov et al. 2020, *Nature Chemical Biology*): Pro-inflammatory (M1) macrophages resist ferroptosis via iNOS/NO-mediated inhibition of 15-lipoxygenase. Anti-inflammatory (M2) macrophages lack this protection. Evolutionary logic: the cells that need to persist during active immune engagement are specifically shielded from the weapon they deploy.

#### Antimicrobial ferroptosis

Macrophages use iron-dependent oxidative killing against intracellular pathogens:

- **Ferroptotic stress kills bacteria** (Ma et al. 2022, *Theranostics*): During early bacterial infection, macrophages increase intracellular ferrous iron and lipid peroxidation. Ferroptosis inducers enhance intracellular bacterial killing. The macrophage reverses ferroportin to import iron into bacterial vacuoles, inducing ferroptosis-like death in the pathogen.
- **Nutritional immunity**: The hepcidin/ferroportin axis, lactoferrin (in neutrophil granules and human milk), and lipocalin-2 (scavenges bacterial siderophores) all restrict iron availability to extracellular pathogens. The immune system treats iron as a weapon to be withheld from invaders and deployed against them.
- **Pathogens can hijack it**: *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* expresses a lipoxygenase (pLoxA) that oxidizes host PUFAs to trigger ferroptosis in airway epithelium — "theft-ferroptosis" (Dar et al. 2018, *Journal of Clinical Investigation*). This confirms that pathogens recognize ferroptosis as a real threat and have evolved to co-opt it.

#### Evolutionary conservation

Ferroptosis is ancient. It arises from the fundamental vulnerability of incorporating PUFAs into membranes in an oxygen-rich, iron-containing environment — a situation that has existed since aerobic metabolism evolved billions of years ago (Stockwell et al. 2017, *Cell*).

- Ferroptosis-like cell death occurs in plants, fungi, and protozoa
- Plant GPX proteins (Arabidopsis) can functionally substitute for mammalian GPX4 in preventing ferroptosis, demonstrating billion-year conservation (Oesterle et al. 2021)
- GPX4 knockout is embryonically lethal in mice — ferroptosis defense is non-negotiable for multicellular life (Friedmann Angeli et al. 2014, *Nature Cell Biology*)

The elaborate multi-layer defenses (GPX4, glutathione, ferritin, System Xc-, ferroportin) evolved precisely because iron-catalyzed lipid peroxidation is both essential for immune defense and existentially dangerous when uncontrolled.

#### The dual nature: defense becomes disease

The same mechanism that makes ferroptosis effective against tumors and pathogens makes it devastating when chronic and dysregulated:

| Context | Iron-dependent lipid peroxidation | Outcome |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Tumor suppression** | p53 triggers ferroptosis in pre-cancerous cells | Beneficial: cancer prevented |
| **Anti-tumor immunity** | CD8+ T cells induce ferroptosis via IFN-gamma | Beneficial: tumors killed |
| **Antimicrobial defense** | Macrophages deploy iron against intracellular pathogens | Beneficial: infection contained |
| **Acute tissue damage** | Ferroptosis eliminates damaged cells | Beneficial: damage limited |
| **Chronic neurodegeneration** | Age-related iron accumulation overwhelms defenses | Pathological: cascading cell death |

The FELINE defense layers map directly onto ferroptosis containment:

- **Fe**: Keep iron compartmentalized so it cannot catalyze lipid peroxidation in the wrong place
- **L (Lysosome)**: GPX4, GSH, and NAD+/SIRT3 directly neutralize lipid peroxides — the molecular products of ferroptosis
- **I (Insulation)**: Myelin, ferritin, and iron-binding proteins physically separate iron from vulnerable membranes
- **N (Neurovascular)**: BBB and pericytes prevent uncontrolled iron entry; astrocyte endfeet manage distribution
- **E (Export)**: Ferroportin, glymphatic flow, and hepcidin regulation remove excess iron before it accumulates to dangerous levels

When these layers fail with age and comorbidity, the weapon that was designed to kill cancer cells and pathogens turns on the brain's own cells — particularly the iron-rich oligodendrocytes that produce myelin. This is not a new disease mechanism. It is the body's oldest defense, running without a safety net.

#### Amyloid-beta: the iron mop, not the iron weapon

Structural biology resolves a long-standing confusion about Aβ's role at plaques. Aβ has two structurally independent domains that serve independent functions:

- **Domain B (residues 17-42)**: Hydrophobic, membrane-inserting. Kills pathogens by physically disrupting their membranes. This is the antimicrobial function. It requires NO metals — Aβ kills bacteria via membrane pore formation, pathogen agglutination, and fibrillar entrapment, the same mechanisms as other antimicrobial peptides. No published experiment has shown that chelating metals from Aβ reduces its antimicrobial killing.
- **Domain A (residues 1-16)**: Hydrophilic, faces outward into the aqueous phase. Contains all metal-binding residues (His6, His13, His14, Asp1, Glu3). Chelates and concentrates iron released from dying neurons. This is the cleanup function.

The geometric proof: when Aβ inserts into a bacterial membrane via Domain B, the metal-binding Domain A faces AWAY from the target. This is the opposite of piscidin, a well-characterized antimicrobial peptide where the Cu-ATCUN complex inserts INTO the membrane to generate ROS directly at the bacterial lipid bilayer (Hayden et al. 2015). Piscidin's copper enhancement of killing is well-documented (2-16x, Oludiran et al. 2019); Aβ's metal enhancement of antimicrobial killing has never been demonstrated. The geometry explains why.

But this same outward-facing geometry is exactly what makes plaque iron dangerous to neurons. Iron concentrated in the extracellular space generates omnidirectional hydroxyl radicals that hit neuronal membranes on all sides. Piscidin's copper is a scalpel. Aβ's iron is a grenade.

**The Mop Analogy:** The field observed someone mopping up biohazardous waste (iron released from dying cells). They noticed the mop (Aβ) was covered in hazardous material (iron) and that people near dirty mops were sick. They concluded: "mops make people sick."

This reframes the disease transition. It is not WEAPON → COLLATERAL DAMAGE. It is CLEANUP → OVERLOAD → TOXICITY:

1. Tissue damage occurs (vascular leak, infection, aging, OL death)
2. Two independent responses activate: Domain B kills pathogens if present; Domain A chelates iron from the debris
3. Microglia compact both (pathogen remains + iron-loaded Aβ) into dense-core plaques
4. If damage is acute and limited: cleanup succeeds, plaques are cleared
5. If damage is chronic and escalating: the mop becomes saturated, iron-Aβ composites accumulate, Fenton chemistry generates omnidirectional ROS, and the cleanup tool becomes a source of damage

Clinical trial results map precisely onto this model. Therapies that handle the WASTE (iron) perform better than those that merely remove the MOP:

| Therapy | Mop Analogy | Clinical outcome |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Gantenerumab | Removes mops, dumps waste on floor | No clinical benefit |
| Aducanumab | Removes mops aggressively | Marginal benefit, high ARIA |
| Lecanemab | Removes mops, some waste handling | Modest benefit (27%) |
| Donanemab | Targets dirtiest mops (dense-core) | Best benefit (35%) |
| Deferiprone | Removes waste from wrong location | WORSENED decline (Ayton 2025) |

The Fc-silenced lecanemab variant is the critical test: if microglial processing of iron-laden plaques (not just antibody-mediated clearance) drives benefit, then silencing the Fc domain should abolish benefit — because the dirty mop is removed but the waste is left behind.

**Key citations for this section:** Jiang et al. 2015 (*Nature*), Wang et al. 2019 (*Nature*), Kapralov et al. 2020 (*Nature Chemical Biology*), Ma et al. 2022 (*Theranostics*), Stockwell et al. 2017 (*Cell*), Hayden et al. 2015, Oludiran et al. 2019, Moir et al. 2018 (*Journal of Alzheimer's Disease*), Ayton et al. 2025 (*JAMA Neurology*), Streit et al. 2022.

