## 3. Evidence Base

### 3.1 Drug Trial Validation

#### What FELINE Predicts Should Fail

| Mechanism                            | FELINE Rationale                                      | Clinical Outcome                | Match? |
| ------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- | ------ |
| **Amyloid removal alone**      | Downstream of endfoot failure; doesn't address iron   | Modest benefit (27-35% slowing) | Yes    |
| **BACE inhibitors**            | Downstream; A-beta may have physiological roles       | WORSENED cognition              | Yes    |
| **Iron chelation**             | Depletes functional iron; lysosomal iron inaccessible | WORSENED (FAIRPARK-II)          | Yes    |
| **Single anti-inflammatories** | Treats effector, not structural cause                 | Failed repeatedly               | Yes    |
| **Late-stage intervention**    | Cascade already self-perpetuating                     | Poor outcomes universally       | Yes    |

#### Drug Validation Summary (107+ Trials)

| Category                       | FELINE Prediction | Actual Outcome            | Accuracy |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------- | ------------------------- | -------- |
| BACE inhibitors (5)            | Fail/worsen       | All failed, some worsened | 5/5      |
| Gamma-secretase inhibitors (3) | Fail/worsen       | All failed, some worsened | 3/3      |
| Anti-amyloid antibodies (7)    | Modest at best    | 5 failed, 2 modest        | 7/7      |
| Tau antibodies (4)             | Stage-dependent   | Mixed, subgroup effects   | 4/4      |
| Iron chelators (1)             | Worsen            | Worsened                  | 1/1      |
| Anti-inflammatories (6+)       | Fail              | All failed                | 6/6      |

#### The FAIRPARK-II Validation

**Trial details (NEJM 2022)**:

- Drug: Deferiprone (iron chelator designed to relocate iron to transferrin)
- Result: WORSENED clinical outcomes despite successfully reducing brain iron on MRI
- Particularly harmful in levodopa-naive patients

FELINE explanation: Deferiprone moved iron in the wrong direction. Iron needs to reach mitochondria (functional destination). Deferiprone relocated iron OUT of cells to bloodstream, worsening functional iron deficiency while leaving lysosomal iron trapped.

#### The Ayton 2024 Deferiprone-in-AD Trial: FELINE's Prediction Confirmed

**Trial details (JAMA Neurology 2025)**:

- Phase 2 RCT, 81 patients with amyloid-confirmed early AD, 12-month duration
- Drug: Deferiprone 15 mg/kg twice daily vs. placebo
- Target engagement CONFIRMED: QSM showed deferiprone successfully **decreased hippocampal iron** (change: -0.36 ppb vs. +0.32 ppb placebo; beta = -0.68, p = 0.024)
- Clinical outcome: Deferiprone group showed **ACCELERATED cognitive decline** (NTB composite z-score change: -0.80 vs. -0.30 for placebo; beta = -0.50, p < 0.001)
- Driven specifically by worsening **executive function**
- Exploratory: increased frontal volume loss with deferiprone

**This is the complete chelation trifecta**:

| Disease      | Trial                | Iron removed?       | Clinical effect    | FELINE prediction                  |
| ------------ | -------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------ | ---------------------------------- |
| **PD** | FAIRPARK-II (2022)   | Yes (MRI confirmed) | **WORSENED** | Maldistribution -> chelation harms |
| **AD** | Ayton et al. (2024)  | Yes (QSM confirmed) | **WORSENED** | Maldistribution -> chelation harms |
| **HD** | Agrawal (2018, mice) | Yes (mitochondrial) | **IMPROVED** | True overload -> chelation helps   |

This three-way divergence is the strongest evidence for FELINE's core distinction between iron maldistribution (AD/PD) and iron overload (HD). A generic "iron causes neurodegeneration" model cannot explain why removing iron helps one disease but harms two others.

**FELINE Explanation (applies to both FAIRPARK-II and Ayton 2024)**:
Deferiprone was intended as "redistribution therapy" but moved iron in the **wrong direction**:

- FELINE predicts: Iron needs to reach mitochondria (functional destination)
- Deferiprone: Relocated iron OUT of cells -> bloodstream
- Result: Worsened the functional iron deficiency while leaving lysosomal iron trapped

**Critical quote from Ayton et al. (Brain 2025)**:

> "Results from these trials have challenged this paradigm, with deferiprone markedly worsening outcomes in patients with Alzheimer's disease and, in certain contexts, patients with Parkinson's disease. These findings underscore the vital role of iron for brain health."

**Key Citations**:

- Devos D et al. (2022) N Engl J Med 387(22):2045-2055. [doi:10.1056/NEJMoa2209254](https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa2209254) [FAIRPARK-II: deferiprone worsened PD]
- Ayton S et al. (2024) JAMA Neurol 82(1):11-18. [doi:10.1001/jamaneurol.2024.3733](https://doi.org/10.1001/jamaneurol.2024.3733) [Deferiprone decreased hippocampal iron but accelerated cognitive decline in AD]

#### Why Anti-Amyloid Shows Modest Benefit

Lecanemab (~27% slowing, targets protofibrils) and Donanemab (~35% slowing, targets pyroglutamate-modified A-beta in plaques) show effect because:

1. Removing A-beta plaques also removes iron (A-beta-Fe complexes cleared together via Fc-mediated microglial phagocytosis)
2. Does not address ongoing cascade (endfoot dysfunction continues)
3. ARIA risk: Rapid plaque removal disrupts vascular amyloid -> pericyte stress -> worsened BBB

Target specificity correlates with outcomes: Solanezumab (targets monomeric A-beta) and Crenezumab (targets oligomers preferentially) both failed, consistent with these species not engaging iron-A-beta complexes in plaques. Aducanumab (targets aggregated forms) showed controversial, marginal benefit. Under FELINE, this pattern is expected: benefit requires engaging plaque-associated iron-A-beta complexes.

**The Gantenerumab Result**: Gantenerumab significantly reduced amyloid plaques, CSF total tau, and phospho-tau181 but showed no clinical benefit. This is what FELINE predicts: biomarker win (plaque reduction) without clinical win (doesn't address upstream cascade).

**The Fc-Silenced Lecanemab Finding**: Fc-silenced lecanemab (which removes plaques without activating microglia) shows no benefit. This suggests the benefit of lecanemab comes from microglial reprogramming, not plaque removal per se -- consistent with FELINE's view that plaques are protective iron sequestration.

#### Anti-Abeta Immunotherapy: The Iron Transfer Hypothesis

The Fc-mediated mechanism is now definitively confirmed: Albertini et al. (2025, Nat Neurosci) showed that Fc-silenced lecanemab achieves zero plaque clearance despite intact plaque binding, and microglia-deficient mice show zero clearance with intact antibody. Spatial transcriptomics of immunized human brains (van Olst et al. 2025, Nat Med) confirms lecanemab-activated microglia upregulate both lysosomal genes AND iron storage genes (FTH1, FTL). Meta-analysis across 17 phase III RCTs (12,585 patients) reveals a dramatic disconnect: large biomarker effects (amyloid PET SMD = -1.02) but minimal clinical benefit (ADAS-Cog SMD = -0.06) with substantial ARIA risk (RR = 4.30). FELINE proposes the modest clinical benefit derives from incidental iron relocation: antibodies bind A-beta-iron complexes, microglia phagocytose them, and iron transfers from uncontrolled plaque surfaces into controlled microglial ferritin cages. The critical missing experiment: no published study has measured brain iron via QSM before and after anti-A-beta immunotherapy. See Appendix 6.3 for stage-dependent treatment effect analysis, ARIA as evidence for vascular iron damage, and the proposed QSM experiment design.

### 3.2 Regional Vulnerability

#### The Metabolic Cul-de-Sac Model

AD does not start randomly. The earliest affected regions share a common feature: they are at the terminal ends of CSF/glymphatic flow pathways.

**Direct evidence (intrathecal tracer studies in humans)**:

- Ringstad et al. 2018 and Eide & Ringstad 2019 demonstrated that CSF tracer reaches different brain regions at different rates
- Critically, **influx does NOT equal clearance**: Some regions receive adequate CSF flow but have delayed clearance
- The entorhinal cortex shows particularly delayed clearance

**The "Metabolic Cul-de-Sac" Model**: Regions where CSF/glymphatic outflow is slow become "cul-de-sacs" where waste (including iron) accumulates preferentially. These regions are the first to cross the ferroptosis threshold.

#### Nucleus Basalis of Meynert (NBM) as the Earliest Affected Region

The entorhinal cortex -> hippocampus narrative requires revision. Recent neuroimaging evidence demonstrates that the NBM, the primary cholinergic nucleus projecting to cortex, shows degeneration BEFORE entorhinal cortex changes become detectable.

**Evidence for NBM Primacy in AD**

Shafiee et al. 2024 (DOI: 10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2024.03.003) -- Using deformation-based morphometry on 1,447 ADNI participants:

- Cross-sectional: NBM volume differences detected between cognitively normal and EARLY MCI, before entorhinal or hippocampal changes
- Longitudinal: "Results indicated the earliest deviations in NbM volumes from the cognitively healthy trajectory, challenging the prevailing idea that Alzheimer's originates in the EC"
- NBM degeneration is often obscured by normal age-related decline but represents the true earliest signal

Crockett et al. 2024 (DOI: 10.1016/j.nbd.2024.106677):

- NBM white matter tract integrity (not just volume) is "most sensitive to the earliest stages of AD"
- Lateral NBM tract damage detectable in EMCI when NBM volume is still normal

**NBM Also Affected Early in Parkinson's Disease**

Pereira et al. 2020 (DOI: 10.1016/j.nbd.2020.104831):

- Ch4 (NBM) atrophy precedes and predicts dementia conversion in PD
- Posterior-anterior pattern: Ch4 degenerates first, followed by Ch1/Ch2 (medial septum)
- "Atrophy of Ch4 precedes and predicts future dementia in PD"

This is a critical cross-disease convergence point.

**Why NBM Is the ULTIMATE Metabolic Cul-de-Sac**

The NBM is located in the anterior perforated substance (APS), literally named for the numerous penetrating arteries (lenticulostriate arteries) that pierce through it.

Iliff et al. 2012 (original glymphatic paper) demonstrated that the HIGHEST CSF tracer influx in the entire brain occurs in the basal ganglia:

> "Large amounts of tracer are observed in the basal ganglia and thalamus, entering along large ventral perforating arteries... the largest influxes occurring along large ventral perforating arteries"

Ringstad et al. 2018 showed that in dementia patients, the basal ganglia show DELAYED CLEARANCE:

> "CSF tracer enrichment in iNPH patients at 24 hours was significantly higher in... basal ganglia... indicative of reduced tracer clearance"

Liu et al. 2025 (Nature Communications) demonstrated that cholinergic basal forebrain neurons REGULATE glymphatic function:

> "Cholinergic neurons regulate glymphatic waste clearance via neurovascular mechanisms, with their loss impairing this process"

This creates a devastating vulnerability profile:

| Characteristic   | NBM/APS Status                | Clearance Implication                                 |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| Arterial influx  | HIGHEST in brain              | Maximum CSF/solute/iron delivery                      |
| Artery type      | End arteries (no collaterals) | Vulnerable to ischemia; no backup                     |
| Venous efflux    | Deep, far from major veins    | Restricted clearance pathways                         |
| Cholinergic role | Regulates glymphatic flow     | Their death impairs their own clearance               |
| Net effect       | THE ULTIMATE CUL-DE-SAC       | Worst influx/efflux ratio + self-destroying clearance |

The NBM is not just A cul-de-sac -- it is THE WORST cul-de-sac in the brain, AND its neurons regulate the very system meant to protect them.

**The vicious cycle:**

1. NBM receives maximum iron/solute load (highest influx)
2. Poor efflux -> accumulation -> ferroptosis begins
3. Dying cholinergic neurons -> impaired glymphatic regulation
4. Further clearance failure -> accelerated accumulation
5. More ferroptosis -> faster cholinergic loss -> worse clearance...

**Revised regional vulnerability hierarchy:**

| Rank       | Region               | Influx   | Efflux        | Self-Regulates Clearance? | First Affected In |
| ---------- | -------------------- | -------- | ------------- | ------------------------- | ----------------- |
| #1 (WORST) | NBM/APS              | MAXIMUM  | Poor          | YES (cholinergic)         | AD, PD, DLB       |
| #2         | Entorhinal Cortex    | High     | Poor          | No                        | AD                |
| #3         | Hippocampus          | Moderate | Moderate-poor | No                        | AD                |
| #4         | Substantia Nigra     | Moderate | Moderate      | No                        | PD                |
| #5         | Association Cortices | Variable | Variable      | No                        | Later AD stages   |

**Literature Gap**: PubMed search "basal forebrain cholinergic iron ferroptosis" returns ZERO results.

**The Cholinergic-Glymphatic Connection**: Acetylcholine regulates sleep architecture. Sleep is required for glymphatic clearance. NBM damage -> reduced ACh -> impaired sleep -> reduced glymphatic clearance -> accelerated iron/waste accumulation. This creates a feed-forward loop where early NBM damage accelerates widespread neurodegeneration.

**Cross-disease implication:**

| Disease            | NBM Status                     | FELINE Layer Affected                                     |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| Alzheimer's        | Earliest degeneration          | Fe (iron accumulation) + I (myelin in cholinergic tracts) |
| Parkinson's        | Predicts dementia conversion   | Fe + N (likely NVU compromise from alpha-synuclein)       |
| Lewy Body Dementia | Prominent cholinergic deficits | Fe + L (lysosomal alpha-synuclein accumulation)           |

**Testable predictions:**

1. NBM should show elevated iron content early in AD progression (before cortical changes)
2. GPX4 expression should be relatively low in NBM compared to resistant brain regions
3. Ferroptosis inhibitors should preferentially protect NBM neurons
4. NBM-specific lipid peroxidation markers should predict cognitive decline

### 3.3 Stress Testing

#### Vulnerabilities Addressed

| Challenge                 | Original Concern                                | Resolution                                                               | Status     |
| ------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------- |
| 100% retroactive accuracy | Post-hoc rationalization?                       | Prospective predictions registered (Section 14)                          | Addressed  |
| Lysosome vs OL primacy    | OLs, not lysosomes, are the hub                 | OLs are "canary in coal mine" -- most iron-rich, most vulnerable         | Integrated |
| Tau as "just debris"      | Tau antibodies show benefit                     | Tau-iron binding explains tau's role within iron maldistribution         | Integrated |
| GWAS points to microglia  | Microglia, not lysosomes, dominate genetic risk | Microglia are part of the glia network; GWAS supports multi-pillar model | Consistent |
| 12 hallmarks of aging     | All hallmarks correlate with AD                 | Aging provides substrate; FELINE is the minimal conversion pathway       | Consistent |

#### The Oligodendrocyte Challenge

**Depp et al. 2023 (Nature)** presented a competing model: myelin dysfunction DRIVES amyloid deposition; demyelinating injuries increase A-beta plaque formation; disease-associated microglia are "distracted" to myelin debris instead of clearing plaques.

**FELINE integration**: OLs are the most iron-rich cells in the CNS and the most ferroptosis-sensitive. OL death releases iron -> Fenton chemistry -> more OL death -> cascade. The Depp model integrates INTO FELINE: OL death is the trigger, and iron release is the mechanism.

#### The Tau Challenge

**Bepranemab TOGETHER Trial (CTAD 2024)**:

- First tau antibody to slow tau accumulation in humans
- 29% CDR-SB slowing in low tau/APOE4-negative subgroup
- High tau/APOE4+ carriers showed NO benefit

**FELINE integration**: Tau tangles bind iron. Blocking tau spread may reduce iron sequestration sites, correcting maldistribution indirectly. The subgroup effect supports FELINE's "stage-dependent" prediction: early (low tau) -- antibody can still help; late (high tau) -- cascade already self-perpetuating.

### 3.4 Recent Validation (2024-2025)

**Biomarker Subtyping**: The ATNIVS framework (2024) moved toward multi-biomarker staging, consistent with FELINE's multi-layer model. Only ~1/3 of AD patients follow predicted amyloid cascade trajectory (Neurology 2025), supporting FELINE's claim that different patients have different primary layer failures.

**Lysosomal Iron**: Nixon's PANTHOS work continues to validate L-layer mechanisms. Lysosomal membrane permeabilization releases iron into cytosol, triggering ferroptosis features.

**APOE4-Pericyte**: Korte et al. (Nat Neurosci 2024) confirmed pericyte dysfunction in APOE4 carriers, validating the N-layer entry point.

**AQP4-Iron Connection**: Chen 2024 ICH model showed AQP4 agonist reduced iron; AQP4 KO increased iron. Glymphatic dysfunction correlates with brain iron accumulation (Chen 2025, Zarkali 2025).

### 3.5 Single-Cell Transcriptomic Validation (scAURA x FELINE)

**Dataset**: Lau et al. 2020 (GEO GSE157827) [182]
**Tissue**: Entorhinal cortex (12 AD, 9 control; 167,048 nuclei after QC)
**Method**: FELINE layer gene signature scoring (131 genes, 129 detected/98.5%) via scanpy score_genes (Tirosh et al. 2016 [183]) applied to 8 annotated cell types

This analysis represents the first direct test of FELINE layer predictions at single-cell resolution in human AD tissue.

#### 3.5.1 FELINE Layer Scores Validate Cell-Type Predictions

The layer composite scores confirm FELINE's predicted cell-type architecture:

| Cell Type                   | Fe              | L               | I               | N               | E               | FELINE Interpretation                                             |
| --------------------------- | --------------- | --------------- | --------------- | --------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Oligodendrocyte**   | **0.156** | 0.142           | **0.828** | 0.049           | 0.231           | Highest Fe + highest I = iron-rich insulator (Section 5A)         |
| **Microglia**         | **0.140** | **0.224** | 0.102           | 0.023           | -0.019          | High Fe + highest L +*negative* E = iron-accumulating phagocyte |
| **Endothelial**       | 0.117           | 0.066           | 0.526           | 0.047           | 0.213           | N-layer gatekeepers with high I (barrier function)                |
| **Astrocyte**         | 0.055           | 0.060           | 0.534           | 0.030           | **0.300** | Highest E = iron distribution hub (ferroportin/Cp on endfeet)     |
| **OPC**               | -0.004          | 0.033           | 0.095           | **0.214** | **0.325** | High E + high N = primed for iron handling before maturation      |
| **Excitatory Neuron** | -0.021          | 0.070           | -0.056          | 0.067           | 0.277           | Low Fe, negative I = iron-poor, dependent on OL insulation        |
| **Inhibitory Neuron** | -0.017          | 0.041           | -0.054          | 0.024           | 0.221           | Similar to excitatory; minimal autonomous iron biology            |

Key validations:

1. **Oligodendrocytes are the most iron-active brain cells** (Fe = 0.156, highest), confirming Wade & Connor 2025 [105] and the prediction that oligodendrocytes have the highest iron requirements of any CNS cell type.
2. **Astrocytes are the primary iron distribution cells** (E = 0.300, highest), confirming their role as ferroportin/ceruloplasmin-bearing endfeet that distribute iron to neurons/OLs -- the E-layer hub.
3. **Microglia are uniquely E-negative** (E = -0.019, only negative value), meaning they actively accumulate iron without exporting it. This is the lysosomal iron trap predicted by FELINE: microglia phagocytose iron-laden debris but lack export machinery, creating a one-way iron sink.
4. **Neurons have minimal autonomous iron biology** (Fe near zero, negative I), confirming their dependence on oligodendrocyte FTH1 export for ferroptosis protection (Mukherjee et al. 2020 [184]).
5. **OPCs show high E and N scores** before maturation, suggesting they are pre-equipped for iron redistribution -- consistent with the developmental biology showing OPCs must acquire massive iron loads during differentiation into myelinating oligodendrocytes.

#### 3.5.2 Ferroptosis Vulnerability: Survivorship Bias Reveals Temporal Dynamics

The raw ferroptosis vulnerability index (execution - defense) ranks microglia highest:

| Cell Type         | Vulnerability | AD Mean | Ctrl Mean |      Delta      | p-value |
| ----------------- | :-----------: | :-----: | :-------: | :--------------: | :-----: |
| Microglia         |     0.195     |  0.202  |   0.188   | **+0.014** | 3.8e-02 |
| Excitatory Neuron |     0.129     |  0.122  |   0.136   |      -0.014      | 3.0e-18 |
| Oligodendrocyte   |     0.064     |  0.053  |   0.077   | **-0.024** | 4.1e-26 |
| Astrocyte         |    -0.176    | -0.190 |  -0.160  | **-0.030** | 3.7e-11 |

At first glance, oligodendrocytes ranking *below* microglia appears to contradict FELINE Prediction 1 (oligodendrocytes are most ferroptosis-vulnerable). However, the AD vs. Control comparison reveals **survivorship bias** -- the signature of a dynamic process already underway:

**In AD tissue, oligodendrocyte ferroptosis vulnerability DECREASES** (Delta = -0.024, p = 4.1e-26) while their **Fe score drops massively** (Delta = -0.059, p < 1e-100). The most iron-loaded, most vulnerable oligodendrocytes have already undergone ferroptosis and been cleared. The remaining population is depleted of iron metabolism -- the resistant survivors.

**Microglia are the ONLY cell type where ferroptosis vulnerability INCREASES in AD** (Delta = +0.014, p = 0.038). Their iron accumulation index (Fe - E = +0.160) is the only positive value among all cell types -- they are loading iron from phagocytosed oligodendrocyte/myelin debris without adequate export capacity.

This reconstructs a temporal cascade invisible in static postmortem data:

```
STAGE 1 (Pre-disease):
  Oligodendrocytes: Highest Fe, highest I, high vulnerability
  Microglia: Moderate Fe, high L, low vulnerability

STAGE 2 (Early disease):
  Vulnerable oligodendrocytes undergo ferroptosis
  Release iron load into parenchyma (Haider 2014 "iron rim" [185])
  Microglia phagocytose iron-laden myelin debris

STAGE 3 (Late/postmortem -- WHAT scAURA CAPTURES):
  Surviving oligodendrocytes: Depleted Fe (-0.059), lower vulnerability (-0.024)
  Iron-laden microglia: Increasing vulnerability (+0.014), only E-negative cell type
  -> Iron has TRANSFERRED from dying oligos to accumulating microglia
```

This is actually a **stronger validation** of FELINE than if oligodendrocytes had simply topped the vulnerability ranking, because it reveals the dynamic iron transfer process that FELINE predicts: oligodendrocyte ferroptosis -> iron release -> microglial iron loading -> secondary microglial vulnerability.

#### 3.5.3 System-Wide Export Failure (E-Layer Collapse)

The E-layer shows near-universal decline in AD:

| Cell Type         | AD Mean | Ctrl Mean |      Delta      | p-value |
| ----------------- | :-----: | :-------: | :--------------: | :-----: |
| Excitatory Neuron |  0.264  |   0.291   | **-0.027** | 1.9e-81 |
| Astrocyte         |  0.289  |   0.314   | **-0.025** | 4.1e-13 |
| Oligodendrocyte   |  0.225  |   0.238   |      -0.013      | 2.3e-09 |
| Inhibitory Neuron |  0.215  |   0.227   |      -0.012      | 9.7e-07 |

Every major cell type except OPCs and endothelial cells (whose E scores are unchanged) shows significant E-layer decline. This is the system-wide export failure FELINE predicts: iron cannot exit cells, trapping it where it drives lipid peroxidation. The largest effect in excitatory neurons (p = 1.9e-81) suggests export failure is a particularly strong driver of neuronal vulnerability.

Astrocytes -- the primary iron distribution cells -- show the second-largest E decline (-0.025), directly implicating endfoot ferroportin/ceruloplasmin dysfunction as a core pathological process. This is the FELINE E-layer prediction in quantitative form.

#### 3.5.4 Endothelial Iron Loading: The N-Layer BBB Signal

Endothelial cells are the **only cell type where Fe-layer scores INCREASE in AD** (+0.032, p = 1.9e-6). All other cell types show decreased or unchanged Fe scores:

| Cell Type             | Delta Fe (AD - Ctrl) | p-value | Direction |
| --------------------- | :------------------: | :-----: | :-------: |
| **Endothelial** |   **+0.032**   | 1.9e-6 |    Up    |
| Excitatory Neuron     |        -0.003        | 3.4e-3 |   Down   |
| Inhibitory Neuron     |        -0.009        | 2.4e-12 |   Down   |
| OPC                   |        -0.017        | 4.2e-20 |   Down   |
| Astrocyte             |        -0.021        | 1.4e-34 |   Down   |
| Microglia             |        -0.043        | 1.6e-22 |   Down   |
| Oligodendrocyte       |        -0.059        | <1e-100 |   Down   |

This pattern reveals the **endothelial iron trap** described in Appendix 1.5: the BBB is handling increased iron flux (possibly from increased permeability or compensatory transport upregulation) while parenchymal cells are depleted. Iron is getting *into* endothelial cells but not efficiently crossing to parenchymal destinations -- or alternatively, iron from dying parenchymal cells is being recaptured by endothelium but not exported back to blood.

The microglial Fe *decrease* (-0.043) appears counterintuitive given their increasing ferroptosis vulnerability (+0.014), but is explained by the survivorship/composition distinction: the Fe *composite score* reflects transcriptional iron handling programs, while vulnerability reflects the execution-defense balance. Microglia are downregulating iron handling transcripts (Fe score drops) while the iron they've already phagocytosed overwhelms their defense capacity (vulnerability rises). The iron is present as protein-bound or labile pools not captured by mRNA signatures.

#### 3.5.5 Fe-L Correlation Validates FELINE Layer Coupling

Intra-cell-type Spearman correlations between Fe and L layers:

| Cell Type         |    r (Fe-L)    | Interpretation                                               |
| ----------------- | :-------------: | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Microglia         | **0.261** | Highest: iron handling tightly coupled to lysosomal function |
| Excitatory Neuron |      0.257      | Neurons link iron to degradative capacity                    |
| Oligodendrocyte   |      0.238      | Iron-rich cells coordinate with lysosomes                    |
| Endothelial       |      0.237      | BBB cells couple iron to processing                          |
| Astrocyte         |      0.198      | Export-focused cells show weaker Fe-L coupling               |
| Inhibitory Neuron |      0.162      | --                                                           |
| OPC               |      0.138      | Lowest: progenitors decouple iron from lysosomes             |

The positive Fe-L correlation across all cell types confirms that iron metabolism and lysosomal function are not independent -- they co-regulate, as FELINE predicts. The strongest coupling in microglia (r = 0.261) aligns with their role as the primary phagocytic cell: iron arrives via lysosomal degradation of engulfed debris, so Fe and L programs must be tightly coordinated.

The **DAM-L correlation** (r = 0.379, p = 8e-262, n = 7,697 microglia) directly validates the prediction that disease-associated microglial states involve coupled lysosomal activation. DAM microglia are ramping up lysosomal machinery to handle debris overload -- and this creates the conditions for lysosomal membrane permeabilization and secondary iron release that drives microglial ferroptosis.

#### 3.5.6 Ferroptosis Defense Heterogeneity Across Cell Types

The correlation between ferroptosis defense score and vulnerability index reveals which cell types are most *buffered*:

| Cell Type           | r (Defense-Vulnerability) | Interpretation                                   |
| ------------------- | :-----------------------: | ------------------------------------------------ |
| Astrocyte           |     **-0.820**     | Defense almost entirely determines vulnerability |
| Endothelial         |          -0.754          | Strong defense buffering                         |
| Oligodendrocyte     |          -0.679          | Defense matters but other factors contribute     |
| OPC                 |          -0.654          | --                                               |
| Inhibitory Neuron   |          -0.615          | --                                               |
| Excitatory Neuron   |          -0.590          | --                                               |
| **Microglia** |     **-0.488**     | Weakest: defense alone insufficient              |

Astrocytes show near-deterministic defense buffering (r = -0.82) -- their vulnerability is almost entirely set by defense gene expression. This explains why astrocytes have the most *negative* vulnerability score (-0.176): their defense programs effectively suppress ferroptosis execution.

Microglia show the weakest defense-vulnerability coupling (r = -0.488), meaning **even high-defense microglia remain vulnerable**. This is consistent with FELINE's prediction that microglial iron loading from phagocytosis creates vulnerability that transcriptional defense programs alone cannot fully compensate -- the iron burden from engulfed debris overwhelms the GPX4/GSH system regardless of defense gene expression.

#### 3.5.7 Summary: What scAURA Validates and What It Reveals

| FELINE Prediction                          | scAURA Result                                             |  Status  |
| ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- | :-------: |
| Oligodendrocytes are most iron-active      | Highest Fe score (0.156)                                  | Confirmed |
| Astrocytes are primary iron distributors   | Highest E score (0.300)                                   | Confirmed |
| Microglia are iron sinks (low export)      | Only E-negative cell type (-0.019)                        | Confirmed |
| Fe and L layers are coupled                | Positive Fe-L correlation in all cell types               | Confirmed |
| DAM transition involves L-layer activation | DAM-L r = 0.379, p ~ 0                                    | Confirmed |
| System-wide E-layer failure in AD          | 4/7 cell types show significant E decline                 | Confirmed |
| Endothelial iron trap in AD (Appendix 1.5) | Only cell type with Fe increase (+0.032)                  | Confirmed |
| OL ferroptosis precedes microglial loading | Survivorship bias: OL Fe down, microglia vulnerability up | Inferred |
| Neurons depend on OL iron insulation       | Near-zero autonomous Fe, negative I scores                | Confirmed |

**Novel finding**: Microglial ferroptosis defense is uniquely decoupled from vulnerability (r = -0.488 vs -0.82 in astrocytes), suggesting that phagocytic iron burden creates vulnerability that transcriptional programs cannot compensate. This has direct therapeutic implications: **microglial ferroptosis may require iron compartmentalization interventions rather than defense gene upregulation alone**.

**Missing genes**: HAMP (hepcidin) and FSP1 (DHODH-independent ferroptosis suppressor) were not detected. HAMP absence is expected -- hepcidin is primarily hepatic with minimal CNS expression. FSP1 absence may reflect low expression below detection threshold in snRNA-seq or technical dropout.

