## 4. Competing Models

### 4.1 Model Comparison Framework

The AD field has generated numerous competing hypotheses, each with supporting evidence but also significant explanatory gaps. FELINE represents a synthesis that incorporates the validated elements while resolving contradictions.

### 4.2 Eight Major Models

#### Amyloid Cascade Hypothesis

**Core claim**: A-beta accumulation is the primary trigger; downstream tau, inflammation, and neurodegeneration follow.

**What it gets right**: A-beta is clearly involved; amyloid PET predicts progression; rare familial mutations in APP/PSEN confirm A-beta relevance.

**What it gets wrong**: BACE inhibitors worsen outcomes; amyloid-negative AD exists; many amyloid-positive people never develop dementia; anti-amyloid antibodies show only modest benefit.

**FELINE integration**: A-beta is a RESPONSE (iron sequestration, membrane repair) rather than a CAUSE. Plaques are protective iron containment structures. Removing them (BACE inhibitors) removes protection.

#### Tau-Centric Model

**Core claim**: Tau hyperphosphorylation and aggregation drive neurodegeneration; tau correlates with symptoms better than amyloid.

**What it gets right**: Tau pathology tracks with clinical severity; tau PET predicts cognitive decline.

**What it gets wrong**: Anti-tau therapies show limited benefit; tau aggregation may be protective (iron binding).

**FELINE integration**: Tau is an I-layer component. Tau binds iron (Fe3+ promotes tau aggregation with 4x higher affinity than Fe2+). Tau tangles sequester toxic iron. Removing tau removes protection in advanced disease.

#### Vascular/Two-Hit Hypothesis (Zlokovic)

**Core claim**: BBB/pericyte dysfunction is an early event that enables A-beta accumulation and neurodegeneration.

**What it gets right**: Vascular risk factors are major AD risk factors; pericyte loss precedes cognitive decline; BBB breakdown visible on MRI.

**What it gets wrong**: Pure vascular dementia differs from AD; not all vascular damage leads to AD.

**FELINE integration**: This IS the N-layer. Pericyte loss -> endfoot detachment -> dual failure of clearance and iron export. Zlokovic's framework describes the structural damage; FELINE adds the iron distribution/drainage consequence.

#### Iron Overload / Ferroptosis Model

**Core claim**: Excess brain iron drives oxidative damage and cell death via ferroptosis.

**What it gets right**: Brain iron is elevated in AD, PD, and other neurodegenerative diseases; ferroptosis markers present; iron chelation logic.

**What it gets wrong**: Iron chelation FAILS (FAIRPARK-II, JAMA Neurol 2024). This is the key failure.

**FELINE integration**: The problem is not iron OVERLOAD but iron MISLOCALIZATION. Cells have functional iron deficiency despite elevated total iron. Chelation worsens this by removing functional iron while trapped iron persists.

#### Glymphatic Hypothesis

**Core claim**: Impaired glymphatic clearance during sleep allows waste accumulation.

**What it gets right**: Sleep deprivation increases AD risk; AQP4 variants affect AD risk; glymphatic flow reduced in aging.

**What it gets wrong**: Glymphatic system itself is debated (see Section 10.1); doesn't explain iron specifically.

**FELINE integration**: Glymphatic clearance is one component of the E-layer. AQP4 on endfeet handles waste clearance; ferroportin on the SAME endfeet handles iron distribution to neurons/OLs. Endfoot damage causes BOTH to fail.

#### Oligodendrocyte/Myelin-Centric Model

**Core claim**: White matter damage and OL death are early, underappreciated events in AD.

**What it gets right**: White matter changes precede gray matter atrophy; OL transcriptomic changes are earliest cellular events.

**What it gets wrong**: Doesn't explain WHY OLs die first.

**FELINE integration**: OLs die first BECAUSE they have the highest iron content. They are the most ferroptosis-sensitive cell type. This model describes the I-layer vulnerability.

#### Neuroinflammation / Microglia Model

**Core claim**: Microglial activation drives neurodegeneration via chronic inflammation.

**What it gets right**: TREM2 variants are major AD risk factors; microglia surround plaques; anti-inflammatory genes associated with AD.

**What it gets wrong**: Anti-inflammatory trials consistently fail; microglial activation may be protective (plaque compaction).

**FELINE integration**: Microglia are part of the defense system, not the cause. Plaque compaction sequesters toxic iron. TREM2 maintains lysosomal function (L-layer). When TREM2 fails, microglia can't process iron-laden debris.

#### Metabolic / Mitochondrial Model

**Core claim**: Mitochondrial dysfunction and metabolic failure drive neurodegeneration.

**What it gets right**: Mitochondrial dysfunction is universal in AD; metabolic changes precede symptoms.

**What it gets wrong**: Mitochondrial therapies alone show limited benefit.

**FELINE integration**: Mitochondria require iron for electron transport chain. Iron mislocalization starves mitochondria -> metabolic failure. NAD+ depletion (L-layer) directly impairs mitochondrial function.

### 4.3 Summary: What Each Model Gets Right and Wrong

| Model                       | Core Insight (Correct)       | Key Limitation                         | FELINE Resolution                        |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Amyloid Cascade**   | A-beta involved in AD        | Downstream, not causal                 | Clearance failure -> A-beta accumulation |
| **Tau-Centric**       | Tau correlates with symptoms | Iron binding role ignored              | Tau-iron = toxic species                 |
| **Vascular**          | BBB damage initiates         | Mechanism to neurodegeneration unclear | Pericyte -> endfoot -> dual failure      |
| **Iron Overload**     | Iron is toxic                | Maldistribution, not overload          | Export failure -> trapping               |
| **Glymphatic**        | Clearance matters            | Upstream cause unknown                 | Endfoot loss depolarizes AQP4            |
| **Oligodendrocyte**   | OLs die early                | Why vulnerable?                        | Most iron-rich, ferroptosis-sensitive    |
| **Neuroinflammation** | Microglia involved           | Reactive, not causal                   | Response to upstream damage              |
| **Metabolic**         | Bioenergetics fail           | Mechanism unclear                      | Iron deficiency -> mitochondrial failure |

### 4.4 What FELINE Uniquely Provides

**Novel Integration #1: The Endfoot Dual Failure**

- PubMed "AQP4 ferroportin" returns zero results (as of January 2026)
- Two separate research communities study the same structure without cross-citation
- FELINE proposes coordinated failure of clearance + iron export at the endfoot

**Novel Integration #2: Functional Iron Deficiency (Not Overload)**

- Cells starve for iron despite high total iron because export machinery is broken
- Explains FAIRPARK-II failure (chelation worsened PD)
- Explains IRP activation despite brain iron elevation

**Novel Integration #3: Cascade Logic**

- NVU damage -> endfoot loss -> dual export failure -> iron accumulation -> ferroptosis
- Specific causal chain absent from prior literature

**Novel Integration #4: Cell Type Vulnerability Hierarchy**

- OLs (highest iron, lowest GPX4) > neurons > astrocytes > microglia
- Predicts disease progression pattern

**Novel Integration #5: APOE4 Mechanism**

- APOE4 -> CypA -> MMP9 -> basement membrane -> endfoot -> dual failure
- Connects strongest genetic risk factor to specific structural pathway

### 4.5 Evidence Scorecard

#### Testable Predictions: Actual Evidence Assessment

**4.5.1 Iron Chelation Should Fail**

FELINE Prediction: Iron chelation should WORSEN neurodegeneration (removes functional iron, leaves trapped iron).

Actual Evidence: FAIRPARK-II (NEJM 2022) -- Deferiprone WORSENED Parkinson's disease progression despite reducing brain iron on MRI.

- Status: Consistent with prediction
- Citation: Devos et al. 2022 (DOI: 10.1056/NEJMoa2209254)

This outcome is consistent with FELINE -- the maldistribution (not overload) hypothesis aligned with the counterintuitive outcome.

**4.5.2 AQP4 Loss Increases Amyloid Pathology**

FELINE Prediction: Endfoot AQP4 loss should impair clearance -> A-beta accumulation.

Actual Evidence:

- Pedersen et al. 2023 (DOI: 10.1016/j.nbd.2023.106100): Both AQP4 KO and AQP4 mislocalization (Snta1 KO) significantly increase parenchymal A-beta plaque deposition
- Simon et al. 2022 (DOI: 10.1186/s13195-022-00999-5): Loss of perivascular AQP4 impairs glymphatic exchange and promotes amyloid plaque formation; human post-mortem confirms reduced perivascular AQP4 in AD
- Key finding: AQP4 MISLOCALIZATION had MORE impact than complete AQP4 deletion

Status: Consistent with prediction for clearance arm of dual failure

**4.5.3 Ferroportin Reduced in AD Brain**

FELINE Prediction: Endfoot ferroportin/ceruloplasmin loss should cause iron export failure.

Actual Evidence:

- Raha et al. 2022 (DOI: 10.3390/ijms23031060): "Ferroportin is strikingly reduced in the AD brain compared to age-matched controls"
- Wu et al. 2020 (DOI: 10.1096/fj.202000167RR): FPN1 ablation in neurons/astrocytes caused iron DEFICIENCY in cortex and hippocampus (functional iron deficiency)

Status: Partially consistent

- Ferroportin IS reduced in AD brain
- But: No study has examined ferroportin specifically at astrocyte ENDFEET
- Critical gap: No studies examining whether AQP4 loss and ferroportin/Cp loss occur together under endfoot-damaging conditions

**4.5.4 Pericyte Protection Reduces Dementia Risk**

FELINE Prediction: CypA inhibitors (which protect pericytes) should reduce AD risk.

Actual Evidence:

- Silva et al. 2023 (DOI: 10.3233/JAD-230526): Patients prescribed tacrolimus, sirolimus, or cyclosporine have REDUCED dementia prevalence
- Key finding: Brain-penetrant tacrolimus showed better results than peripherally-restricted cyclosporine
- "Calcineurin inhibition within the brain has a greater probability of reducing dementia relative to peripherally-restricted calcineurin inhibition"

Status: Partially consistent (epidemiological support; no prospective RCT)

**4.5.5 PARTIALLY SUPPORTED: Iron Regulates AQP4 (Co-regulation exists)**

FELINE's Novel Claim: AQP4 (clearance) and iron metabolism are functionally linked.

Actual Evidence -- better than expected:

- Zhong et al. 2019 (DOI: 10.1016/j.neuro.2019.03.006): "Ferrous iron exposure... increased AQP4 expression" in astrocytes. Iron directly regulates AQP4 via MAPK activation.
- Isasi et al. 2022 (DOI: 10.1007/s12035-022-02798-3): Iron deficiency -> reduced AQP4 expression AND shorter AQP4+ capillaries. Also affected pericytes (reduced PDGFRbeta associated with AQP4+ capillaries).
- Abdul et al. 2020 (DOI: 10.1007/s12975-020-00844-7): Deferoxamine improved AQP4 polarity in diabetic stroke AND reduced endothelial ferroptosis.
- Li et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1186/s12987-025-00651-y): Hemin (iron-rich porphyrin) treatment affects AQP4 polarization recovery.

Implication: The evidence is BETTER than "untested" -- there IS functional coupling between iron metabolism and AQP4. The direction of regulation (iron affects AQP4 rather than shared endfoot loss affecting both) suggests an even tighter coupling than FELINE proposed.

**4.5.6 EMERGING SUPPORT: Glymphatic Dysfunction Drives Iron Accumulation**

STRONG NEW EVIDENCE (2025-2026):

- Chen et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1093/braincomms/fcaf365): "Glymphatic dysfunction as a potential driver of cerebral iron deposition in Parkinson's disease." Glymphatic dysfunction (reduced ALPS index) "was significantly correlated with regional iron deposition patterns."
- Zarkali et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1002/mds.30325): Lower DTI-ALPS (impaired glymphatic) associated with "changes in brain iron distribution" in PD patients with poor outcomes.
- Leong et al. 2026 (DOI: 10.1002/cns.70677): Iron accumulation correlates with glymphatic function. "Enhanced glymphatic clearance... may facilitate recovery."

Multiple independent groups showing the same pattern: impaired clearance -> iron deposition.

**4.5.7 CRITICAL SUPPORT: Iron Transport Machinery on Astrocyte Endfeet (Cheli 2020)**

Cheli et al. 2020 (DOI: 10.1177/1759091420962681) -- "Iron Metabolism in Oligodendrocytes and Astrocytes, Implications for Myelination and Remyelination" (ASN Neuro)

Key findings:

1. **DMT1 confined to astrocyte endfeet**: "The in vivo expression of DMT1 was reported to be confined to astrocytic perivascular end-feet" (citing Moos and Morgan, 2004)
2. **Ferroportin-ceruloplasmin on astrocyte membranes**: "Ferroportin and ceruloplasmin are highly expressed on astrocytic cell membranes, and both proteins likely play an important role in iron mobilization from these cells into the extracellular brain space"
3. **AQP4 on same endfeet** (cited reference): Amiry-Moghaddam et al. 2003 confirmed AQP4 in astroglial end-feet
4. **Astrocytes are iron TRANSPORTERS, not accumulators**: "A small proportion of astrocytes stain for iron... This observation supports the notion that astrocytes may be mostly involved in iron trafficking and not iron accumulation"
5. **Astrocyte-specific ferroportin KO impairs remyelination**: "OPC differentiation and remyelination were impaired in a mouse model of focal chemical demyelination when ferroportin was specifically deleted in astrocytes" (Schulz et al., 2012)

This is the closest to direct evidence for FELINE's anatomical claim: iron transport machinery (DMT1, ferroportin) and water/clearance machinery (AQP4) are BOTH localized to astrocyte endfeet at the blood-brain interface.

**4.5.8 STRONG SUPPORT: APOE-epsilon-4 -> AQP4 Loss -> A-beta AND Iron Accumulation (Long 2023)**

Long et al. 2023 (DOI: 10.1002/mco2.298) -- Critical passage:

> "APOE-epsilon-4 can reduce the expression of aquaporin-4 (AQP4), a set of perivascular water channels, contributing to aberrant A-beta plaque accumulation. Notably, the BBB dysfunction caused by APOE-epsilon-4 in the capillaries is similar to the pathomechanism of cerebral small vessel disease, where iron leakage occurs in the brain due to BBB dysfunction. APOE-epsilon-4 and mild cognitive impairment were associated with higher cortical iron in a neuroimaging study using a 7.0T QSM."

This review independently arrives at a mechanistic framework nearly identical to FELINE.

**4.5.9 RETRACTED PAPER NOTE**

Liu et al. 2022 (PMC9233479) proposed exactly the pathway FELINE needs (AQP4 depolarization -> transferrin infiltration -> ferroptosis) but was RETRACTED in 2024. Cannot be cited as primary evidence. The concept remains plausible and supported by other non-retracted work.

