### 4.7 Microglial Plaque Compaction as Iron Sequestration

FELINE extends the microglial compaction literature by proposing that dense-core plaques function as compact iron-sequestration structures.

**Core hypothesis**: Microglia compact diffuse A-beta into dense-core plaques not as "cleanup" but as iron isolation. Dense-core plaques have LESS toxic effect than diffuse plaques because iron is contained.

**Direct evidence**:

1. **Dense-core plaques are compact iron-sequestration structures**: Plaque structure resembles organized immune containment (sequestering toxic material behind a physical barrier)
2. **A-beta deposition = iron concentration**: A-beta coordinates iron via histidine residues (His6, His13, His14). Plaque iron content correlates with plaque density.
3. **TREM2 loss -> diffuse plaques -> more damage**: TREM2 KO mice have diffuse, not compact, plaques and worse outcomes. Suggests compaction is protective.
4. **Plexin-B1 deletion -> more compact plaques -> less damage**: Genetic manipulation increasing compaction improves outcomes (Huang 2024, Gotkiewicz 2024).

**Evidence Scorecard -- Microglial Compaction**

| Claim                                                                | Evidence Status | Key Citation                |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------- | --------------------------- |
| Dense-core plaques are microglia-constructed                         | Consistent      | Lemke 2022                  |
| Dense-core plaques function as compact iron-sequestration structures | PROPOSED        | Lemke 2022                  |
| A-beta deposits sequester iron                                       | Consistent      | Streit 2022                 |
| A-beta deposition is "neuroprotective"                               | STATED          | Streit 2022                 |
| Iron co-localizes with plaque cores                                  | Consistent      | Streit 2022, Falangola 2005 |
| TREM2 loss -> diffuse plaques -> more damage                         | Consistent      | Yuan 2016                   |
| More compaction -> less neuritic damage                              | Consistent      | Huang 2024                  |
| Microglia physically compact plaques                                 | Consistent      | Gotkiewicz 2024             |
| Dense-core plaques release less toxic oligomers                      | SUPPORTED       | Condello 2015               |

**Therapeutic Implications of Plaque Compaction**

| Therapeutic Approach                          | Predicted Effect                                                               |
| --------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Anti-A-beta immunotherapy (plaque removal)    | DANGEROUS -- may release sequestered iron -> acute toxicity                    |
| TREM2 agonists                                | Should ENHANCE compaction -> better iron sequestration                         |
| Plexin-B1 inhibitors                          | Should allow better microglial access -> more compaction                       |
| Iron chelation                                | Wrong target -- iron is concentrated in redox-active composites within plaques |
| Prevent plaque formation (early intervention) | Best approach -- prevent iron release in first place                           |

**Critical warning from Lemke & Huang 2022**:

> "If dense-core plaques are indeed compact containment structures, their simple disassembly may be contraindicated as an Alzheimer's therapy" (Lemke & Huang 2022, paraphrased)

#### APP Dual-Function Model: Iron Export AND A-beta as Iron Concentrator

APP has TWO distinct iron-related roles, and the shift from one to the other represents a key transition in AD pathogenesis.

**Function 1: APP Stabilizes Ferroportin for Iron Export (Normal Physiology)**

Duce et al. 2010 (Cell, [DOI: 10.1016/j.cell.2010.08.014](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2010.08.014)) reported that APP interacts with ferroportin and promotes iron export:

> "Ablation of APP in HEK293T cells and primary neurons induces marked iron retention, whereas increasing APP695 promotes iron export"

**Critical correction**: Duce 2010 originally claimed APP possesses intrinsic ferroxidase activity homologous to H-ferritin. This was retracted by the same laboratory. Wong et al. 2014 (PLoS ONE, [DOI: 10.1371/journal.pone.0114174](https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0114174)) demonstrated:

> "β-Amyloid precursor protein does not possess ferroxidase activity but does stabilize the cell surface ferrous iron exporter ferroportin"

The iron oxidation Duce 2010 observed originated from phosphate in the assay buffer, not from APP. However, the functional finding stands: APP stabilizes ferroportin at the neuronal surface, promoting iron export. Neurons lacking APP retain iron.

**Contested ferroxidase identity**: Ji et al. 2018 (Cell Mol Neurobiol, [DOI: 10.1007/s10571-017-0568-z](https://doi.org/10.1007/s10571-017-0568-z)) found that the ferroxidase hephaestin, not APP, is required for ferroportin-supported iron efflux in primary hippocampal neurons. APP knockdown did not affect surface ferroportin stability or iron efflux in their system. This remains an active area of investigation: APP may stabilize ferroportin through a non-enzymatic mechanism while hephaestin provides the ferroxidase activity.

**Function 2: A-beta Production is a COST of Amyloidogenic Processing**

Tsatsanis et al. 2020 (Mol Psychiatry, [DOI: 10.1038/s41380-020-0762-0](https://doi.org/10.1038/s41380-020-0762-0)) demonstrated a critical new mechanism:

> "Endocytotic amyloidogenic processing of APP impairs iron export by destabilizing ferroportin on the cell surface. Conversely, preferential non-amyloidogenic processing of APP at the cell surface promotes ferroportin stabilization to decrease intraneuronal iron."

When BACE1 cleaves APP (amyloidogenic pathway), it removes APP from the cell surface, destabilizing ferroportin. The released A-beta then concentrates iron extracellularly via His6/His13/His14 coordination, reducing Fe3+ to redox-active Fe2+ (Everett 2014, Telling 2017; see §Aβ-Iron Biophysics below). This creates dangerous iron-A-beta composites requiring microglial compaction for containment.

The shift from Function 1 to Function 2 is therefore doubly harmful:

- Surface APP loss destabilizes ferroportin -> intracellular iron rises
- Released A-beta concentrates and reduces extracellular iron -> creates toxic composites
- Microglia must compact these composites into dense-core plaques for damage control

**The Zn2+ Feedback Loop Creates Spreading Pathology**

Zn2+ from maturing plaques disrupts APP-ferroportin interaction in neighboring neurons. This creates a self-propagating cycle:

1. Neuron 1: Iron export fails -> ferroptosis -> iron released
2. A-beta concentrates released iron into redox-active composites (DANGEROUS)
3. A-beta plaques accumulate Zn2+ (normal plaque maturation)
4. Zn2+ DISRUPTS APP-ferroportin stabilization in NEIGHBORING Neuron 2
5. Neuron 2: Cannot export iron -> iron accumulates -> ferroptosis
6. More iron released -> more A-beta deposited -> more Zn2+ -> SPREADING WAVE

Plaque compaction breaks this cycle:

| Plaque State           | Iron                                   | Zn2+                     | Effect on Neighbors                                                                |
| ---------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Diffuse                | Concentrated but accessible, Fe2+ form | Can reach nearby neurons | DANGEROUS: Zn2+ disrupts APP-ferroportin stabilization -> spreading iron retention |
| Compacted (dense-core) | Sequestered inside                     | Sequestered inside       | SAFE: ApoE layer + microglial barrier prevents Zn2+ from reaching neighbors        |

**Literature Support for ZnÂ²âº Sequestration Hypothesis**

According to PubMed, several lines of evidence support this model:

**1. ZnÂ²âº is concentrated in plaques** - Miller et al. (2005) used synchrotron X-ray fluorescence to show Cu and Zn "hot spots" co-localized with Î²-amyloid plaques in human AD brain ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2005.09.004)):

> "strong spatial correlation between elevated beta-sheet content in AÎ² plaques and accumulated Cu and Zn ions"

**2. Mouse plaques bind LESS metal than human plaques** - Leskovjan et al. (2009) found PSAPP mouse plaques contained only 29% more Zn than surrounding tissue, compared to much higher enrichment in human AD ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2009.05.063)):

> "Since metal binding to AÎ² is thought to induce redox chemistry that is toxic to neurons, the reduced metal binding in PSAPP mice is consistent with the lack of neurodegeneration in these animals"

**3. Plaque metal reflects surrounding tissue** - James et al. (2017) showed plaque metal content correlates with local neuropil ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1021/acschemneuro.6b00362)):

> "After correcting for tissue density, only Zn levels remained elevated in plaques"
> This suggests Zn is ACTIVELY bound/sequestered by plaques, not just passively accumulated.

**4. ZnÂ²âº stabilizes toxic oligomers, inhibits fibril formation** - Xu et al. (2015) showed ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.jcim.5b00063)):

> "ZnÂ²âº stabilizes nonfibrillar AÎ² oligomers and, thus, **inhibits formation of less toxic AÎ² fibrils**"

**5. Dissolving fibrils INCREASES toxicity** - Sharma et al. (2012) made a critical observation when testing bifunctional compounds (BFCs) that both chelate metals and bind AÎ² ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1021/ja210588m)):

> "the formation of soluble AÎ²42 oligomers in the presence of metal ions and BFCs leads to an **increased cellular toxicity**"
> "the previously employed strategy of inhibiting AÎ² aggregation and promoting amyloid fibril disaggregation **may not be optimal** for the development of potential AD therapeutics, due to formation of neurotoxic soluble AÎ²42 oligomers"

**FELINE interpretation**: These findings directly support the compaction-as-protection model:

- Diffuse plaques contain loosely-bound metals (ZnÂ²âº, Fe) that can interact with surrounding neurons
- Compact/fibrillar plaques tightly sequester these metals
- Dissolving plaques (via anti-amyloid antibodies or metal chelators) RELEASES toxic oligomers and metals
- This explains why aggressive plaque-clearing strategies cause ARIA and may worsen outcomes

#### Aβ-Iron Biophysics: Why Compaction is Essential Damage Control

A-beta does not simply "chelate" iron protectively. The biophysical evidence shows A-beta concentrates iron and shifts it toward more dangerous redox states:

**Step 1: Iron accumulation.** A-beta's three histidine residues (His6, His13, His14) coordinate Fe3+ from the surrounding environment. This concentrates iron within aggregates far above ambient levels.

**Step 2: Redox reduction.** During aggregation, Fe3+ is reduced to Fe2+. Everett et al. 2014 ([DOI: 10.1098/rsif.2014.0165](https://doi.org/10.1098/rsif.2014.0165)) demonstrated this in vitro; Telling et al. 2017 ([DOI: 10.1016/j.chembiol.2017.07.014](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chembiol.2017.07.014)) confirmed it in vivo: dense-core plaques in APP/PS1 mouse cortex contain Fe2+, while diffuse plaques contain Fe3+.

**Step 3: Mineral transformation.** Magnetite (Fe3O4) forms within plaque-associated iron deposits (Telling 2017). This mixed-valence mineral can catalyze Fenton chemistry if exposed to H2O2.

**Step 4: Compaction as damage control.** The Fe2+/magnetite composites within A-beta aggregates are dangerous if diffuse (accessible to surrounding neurons). TREM2-mediated microglial compaction into dense-core plaques physically isolates these composites behind an ApoE/microglial barrier. Compaction does not make the iron safe; it makes it inaccessible.

**The Aβ paradox resolved:**

- APP on the cell surface PROTECTS (stabilizes ferroportin for iron export)
- A-beta released by amyloidogenic processing is HARMFUL (concentrates iron, reduces it to Fe2+)
- A-beta production is a COST of losing surface APP
- Compaction provides CONTAINMENT of the damage (not amplification of protection)

This reframing explains why BACE inhibitors worsen outcomes: they preserve surface APP (good) but also signal that iron dysregulation is severe enough that the system cannot maintain normal processing. Simply blocking BACE1 does not fix upstream iron accumulation or ferroportin destabilization.

#### Species Comparison: His13 as Linchpin for Iron-A-beta Interaction

Human and rodent A-beta differ at three residues within the metal-binding domain (positions 5, 10, 13). The critical substitution is **His13 (human) -> Arg13 (rodent)**, which eliminates one of three metal coordination sites.

Istrate et al. 2012 (Biophys J, [DOI: 10.1016/j.bpj.2011.11.4006](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bpj.2011.11.4006)) determined the NMR structure of rat Aβ(1-16) and found:

> "The zinc coordination site was found to involve residues His-6 and His-14 of both peptide chains... the C-tails of the two polypeptide chains of the rat Aβ(1-16) dimer are oriented in opposite directions to each other, which hinders the assembly of rat Aβ dimers into oligomeric aggregates"

With only 2 metal-binding histidines (vs. human's 3), rodent A-beta forms zinc-bridged dimers whose C-terminal tails point in opposite directions, blocking further oligomerization. Human A-beta, with His13 providing a third coordination site, forms metal-bridged aggregates that can extend into fibrils.

**Consequences for AD modeling:**

- Mice never develop spontaneous AD because rodent A-beta cannot form metal-bridged aggregates
- All transgenic AD models require HUMAN APP/A-beta to produce plaques
- This is not just an aggregation difference: rodent A-beta cannot concentrate iron effectively because it lacks the His13 coordination site

**Cross-species metal content variability:** Chourrout et al. 2023 (Acta Biomater, [DOI: 10.1016/j.actbio.2023.07.046](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actbio.2023.07.046)) showed dramatic differences across transgenic models:

> "J20 (zinc and iron) and TgF344 (copper) strains showed greater metal accumulation than APPPS1 and ArcAβ mice... metal accumulation is the main reason why Aβ plaques are detected"

Different transgenic constructs produce plaques with different metal profiles, reinforcing that the A-beta-metal interaction, not A-beta alone, drives plaque pathology.

**Evolutionary interpretation:** His13 makes human A-beta both more dangerous (can concentrate iron into Fe2+ composites) and more useful as a containment substrate (can form the dense fibrillar structures microglia compact). This may reflect a trade-off in long-lived, heavily myelinated brains where iron containment capacity matters.

**Tau is Required for APP Surface Trafficking**

Lei et al. 2012 (Nature Medicine, [DOI: 10.1038/nm.2613](https://doi.org/10.1038/nm.2613)):

> "Loss of tau causes iron retention, by decreasing surface trafficking of APP"

Tau knockout mice develop age-dependent brain atrophy, iron accumulation, substantia nigra neuronal loss, cognitive deficits, and parkinsonism -- ALL prevented by iron chelator (clioquinol).

FELINE interpretation: Tau's normal function includes facilitating APP trafficking to the membrane for iron export. When tau is sequestered binding excess cytosolic iron (its emergency buffer function), it can't support APP trafficking -> further iron export failure -> vicious cycle.

#### The Causal Reordering: Iron-First, Not Amyloid-First

Streit et al. 2025 stated: "first step in neuritic plaque creation is neuronal degeneration driven by iron overload and ferroptosis" -- a paradigm shift from amyloid-first to iron-first.

Iron accumulation triggers A-beta production as a defensive response. A-beta plaques are the body's attempt to sequester dangerous iron. Removing plaques (anti-amyloid therapy) removes protection, explaining why BACE inhibitors worsen outcomes and why anti-amyloid antibodies show only modest benefit.

**5xFAD Mice Show Early Iron Dysregulation**

Gurel et al. (2018) demonstrated iron accumulation in 5xFAD mice at just 3 monthsâ€”**before plaque formation** ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.3233/JAD-170329)):

> "Alterations in extracellular matrix proteins in addition to increasing amount of hippocampal IL6 and **iron in the early stages** of AD may reveal **inflammation-mediated iron dyshomeostasis in the early stages of neurodegeneration**"

Petralla et al. (2024) showed HIF-1 pathway activation in 5xFAD cortex ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1007/s12035-024-03990-3))â€”HIF-1 is activated when cells sense functional iron deficiency, causing them to upregulate iron import (TfR1), which worsens the iron accumulation problem.

