**Why Anti-Amyloid Antibody Results Stratify by Metal Content of Targets**

The clinical record of anti-amyloid antibodies is not a simple story of failure—it stratifies in a pattern consistent with metal-mediated toxicity rather than intrinsic Aβ toxicity.

**First-generation antibodies (targeting metal-poor Aβ species) → ALL FAILED:**

- Solanezumab: targets soluble monomers (metal-free form) → no clinical benefit
- Bapineuzumab: targets N-terminal epitope on monomers/plaques → no clinical benefit
- Crenezumab: targets multiple soluble forms including monomers → no clinical benefit

**Second-generation antibodies (targeting metal-laden aggregates) → MODEST BENEFIT:**

- Lecanemab: targets protofibrils (aggregated, metal-binding forms) → 27% slowing
- Donanemab: targets pyroglutamate-modified deposited Aβ (N3pG) → 35% slowing
- Aducanumab: targets aggregated forms/plaques → controversial benefit
- Gantenerumab: targets fibrils/plaques but showed no clinical benefit despite plaque clearance and tau reduction

FELINE interpretation: The pattern is consistent with benefit coming from removal of metal-laden deposits rather than Aβ removal per se. First-gen antibodies cleared metal-free monomers and showed nothing. Second-gen antibodies clear metal-enriched aggregates and show modest benefit—potentially by removing sequestered iron/copper/zinc reservoirs.

**Donanemab's Mechanism Is Particularly Informative for FELINE**

Donanemab specifically targets pyroglutamate-modified Aβ at position 3 (N3pG)—a post-translational modification found almost exclusively in **established, deposited plaques** that have undergone enzymatic maturation (Mintun et al. 2021, NEJM; [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa2100708)). It does NOT target soluble monomers, oligomers, or protofibrils—only old, deposited material. These are precisely the deposits that have had the longest time to accumulate metals. TRAILBLAZER-ALZ achieved 85 centiloid reduction in amyloid PET signal at 76 weeks with ~35% clinical slowing.

Kim et al. 2025 ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1186/s40035-025-00465-w)) reviewed the mechanistic landscape: first-gen MABs targeting "non-toxic monomeric Aβ" all failed, while second-gen MABs "directed against pathogenic Aβ species and aggregates" showed that reducing deposited Aβ can slow cognitive decline. FELINE reframes this: the "pathogenic" species are pathogenic because they carry metals, not because they are Aβ.

**The Gantenerumab Puzzle**: Gantenerumab cleared plaques and reduced tau biomarkers but showed NO clinical benefit. This is surprising for the amyloid hypothesis but potentially explained by FELINE: if gantenerumab's mechanism of plaque removal released iron/metals into surrounding tissue rather than safely clearing them (unlike lecanemab/donanemab which may trigger microglial phagocytosis that processes the metal content), the net effect could be neutral—plaque iron removed but redistributed locally rather than exported.

**Therapeutic Implications**

| Strategy                                  | Rationale                   | Expected Outcome                                                                              |
| ----------------------------------------- | --------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Restore ferroportin** (CBD, etc.) | Fix Function 1 (export)     | ✅ Prevents need for Function 2                                                               |
| **TREM2 agonists**                  | Enhance plaque compaction   | ✅ Makes Function 2 safer                                                                     |
| **Iron chelators** (targeted)       | Reduce labile iron burden   | ✅ Addresses root cause (but avoid depleting functional iron—see FAIRPARK-II)                |
| **Zn²⁺ chelators**                | Break feedback loop         | ⚠️ May help, needs testing                                                                  |
| **Anti-Aβ antibodies (2nd gen)**   | Remove metal-laden deposits | ⚠️ Modest benefit by removing metal reservoirs, but doesn't fix upstream iron dysregulation |
| **Anti-Aβ antibodies (1st gen)**   | Remove metal-free monomers  | ❌ Removes non-toxic species                                                                  |
| **BACE inhibitors**                 | Block Aβ production        | ❌ Eliminates backup sequestration AND destabilizes ferroportin (Tsatsanis 2020)              |

