#### Copper: The OTHER Redox-Active Metal in Plaques

While FELINE focuses on iron as the primary driver, copper (Cu) also accumulates in AD plaques and plays a distinct but related role.

**Copper is ALSO Elevated in AD Plaques**

According to PubMed, multiple studies have confirmed copper co-accumulates with zinc and iron:

Miller et al. (2005) showed Cu and Zn "hot spots" co-localized with AÎ² plaques ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2005.09.004)):

> "strong spatial correlation between elevated beta-sheet content in AÎ² plaques and accumulated Cu and Zn ions"

Hobin et al. (2024) found altered copper isotopic composition (heavier Cu isotope ratio) in AD patient blood, suggesting dysregulated Cu metabolism ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtemb.2024.127515)):

> "Cu and Fe in the vicinity of plaques produce reactive oxygen species (ROS) resulting in oxidative stress, whereas Zn plays a role in the antioxidant defence"

**Copper vs Iron vs Zinc: Different Mechanisms**

| Metal                                      | Redox Active? | Primary Toxicity Mechanism                                     | Role in Plaques                      |
| ------------------------------------------ | ------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| **Iron (FeÂ²âº/FeÂ³âº)** | âœ… YES    | Fenton reaction â†’ hydroxyl radicals â†’ ferroptosis    | Primary driver of lipid peroxidation |
| **Copper (Cuâº/CuÂ²âº)**   | âœ… YES    | Fenton-like reactions + Hâ‚‚Oâ‚‚ generation              | Amplifies oxidative damage           |
| **Zinc (ZnÂ²âº)**              | âŒ NO     | Disrupts APP-ferroportin interaction â†’ blocks iron export | Prevents protective iron export      |

Greenough et al. (2012) review on metal dyshomeostasis ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuint.2012.08.014)):

> "Copper, zinc and iron are naturally abundant in the brain but Alzheimer's disease brain contains elevated concentrations of these metals in areas of amyloid plaque pathology. Amyloid beta can become pro-oxidant and when complexed to copper or iron it can generate hydrogen peroxide."

**Copper-AÎ² Complexes Generate Hâ‚‚Oâ‚‚**

The Cu-AÎ² complex is catalytically active and generates reactive oxygen species:

Barnham et al. (2004) identified the key mechanism ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1096/fj.04-1890fje)):

> "AÎ² coordinates the redox active transition metals, copper and iron, to catalytically generate reactive oxygen species... tyrosine10 (Y10) was identified as a pivotal residue for this reaction"

Lynch et al. (2000) described the electrochemistry ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/s0531-5565(00)00112-1)):

> "AÎ² converts molecular oxygen into hydrogen peroxide by reducing copper or iron, and this may lead to Fenton chemistry. Hydrogen peroxide is a freely permeable prooxidant"

**FELINE Integration: Cu Amplifies Fe Toxicity**

