All three in a diffuse plaque = **catastrophic synergy**

**Why Compaction Still Protects Against Copper**

Just like iron and zinc, copper in diffuse plaques can:

1. Generate Hâ‚‚Oâ‚‚ that diffuses to surrounding neurons
2. Participate in Fenton-like reactions with neighboring iron
3. Directly oxidize membrane lipids

Compacted dense-core plaques:

1. Sequester copper away from surrounding tissue
2. Limit Hâ‚‚Oâ‚‚ diffusion
3. Break the Cu-Fe amplification loop

**The Complete Metal Picture**

| Plaque State        | Iron             | Copper                    | Zinc                       | Net Effect                               |
| ------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Diffuse**   | Fenton reactions | Hâ‚‚Oâ‚‚ generation | APP-ferroportin disruption | âš ï¸ CATASTROPHIC: Triple threat |
| **Compacted** | Sequestered      | Sequestered               | Sequestered                | âœ… PROTECTED: All three neutralized  |

**Model Differences in Metal Accumulation**

Chourrout et al. (2023) showed dramatic differences across AD models ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actbio.2023.07.046)):

> "J20 (zinc and iron) and TgF344 (copper) strains showed greater metal accumulation than APPPS1 and ArcAÎ² mice... metal accumulation is the main reason why AÎ² plaques are detected"

Key finding: Different transgenic models accumulate different metals, which may explain why therapies work in some models but not others.

