#### Iron as Required Cofactor for Aβ Oligomer Toxicity

A critical challenge to FELINE's iron-centric interpretation is the large oligomer toxicity literature claiming Aβ oligomers are directly synaptotoxic independent of metals. However, closer examination reveals that metal dependence is pervasive and inadequately controlled.

**Iron Is a SPECIFIC Cofactor for Aβ Toxicity In Vivo**

Ott et al. (2015) provided definitive evidence in Drosophila ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1242/dmm.019042)):

The interaction between iron and Aβ is **specific**—not seen for other aggregation-prone polypeptides. The toxicity is mediated through three N-terminal histidines (His6, His13, His14), which are the known metal-binding residues. Systematic His→Ala substitutions revealed:

- **Position-dependent mechanisms**: Some histidines mediate metal-dependent aggregation toxicity under non-oxidizing conditions
- **Position-independent mechanisms**: Other histidines mediate toxicity under oxidizing conditions (Fenton chemistry)
- Both pathways require iron as cofactor
- Iron is important for Aβ dimerization—the first step in oligomer formation

This demonstrates that even the *formation* of toxic Aβ species depends on iron availability, not just their downstream effects.

**Metal Ions Determine Oligomer Morphology and Toxicity**

The literature reveals that different metals produce radically different Aβ aggregate forms:

| Metal              | Effect on Aβ Aggregation | Morphology                                 | Toxicity                                   |
| ------------------ | ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------ |
| **Fe³⁺**   | Promotes aggregation      | Annular protofibrils + fibrillar oligomers | ⚠️ HIGH - generates ROS via Fenton       |
| **Cu²⁺**   | Inhibits fibril formation | Amorphous aggregates (non-fibrillar)       | ⚠️ Generates H₂O₂ via redox cycling    |
| **Zn²⁺**   | Inhibits fibril formation | Stabilizes non-fibrillar oligomers         | ⚠️ Prevents protective fibril maturation |
| **No metal** | Forms fibrils normally    | Mature amyloid fibrils                     | Lower toxicity than oligomeric forms       |

Iron specifically produces the aggregate morphologies (annular protofibrils, fibrillar oligomers) considered most neurotoxic. Without iron, Aβ preferentially forms mature fibrils—the form associated with LESS neuronal damage.

**The Synthetic Oligomer Problem: Uncontrolled Metal Contamination**

The foundational "oligomers impair LTP within minutes" experiments use synthetic Aβ₄₂ preparations (ADDLs, Aβ*56, etc.). A critical methodological concern:

- Synthetic Aβ is prepared in standard laboratory buffers NOT treated to remove trace metals
- Aβ's N-terminal histidines avidly scavenge any available Fe, Cu, Zn from solution, labware, and culture media
- The binding affinities are picomolar for Cu²⁺ (Sarell et al. 2009) and low-micromolar for Zn²⁺/Fe³⁺
- Standard culture media (DMEM, ACSF) contain micromolar iron and zinc
- No major LTP/synaptotoxicity study has used chelexed, metal-free conditions as a control

Therefore, the "metal-free oligomer" preparations used in these experiments almost certainly contain metal-Aβ complexes. The rapid LTP impairment attributed to "oligomer binding to PrPC" may reflect metal-Aβ complex generation of local ROS at synaptic membranes—which occurs on the same timescale. PrPC itself is a copper-binding protein, making the entire system metal-dependent.

**FELINE Interpretation**: The decades of oligomer toxicity research do not contradict FELINE's iron-centric model—they are confounded by uncontrolled metal variables. When iron is specifically manipulated (Ott 2015), it emerges as a required cofactor. The "intrinsic toxicity" of Aβ oligomers may substantially reflect the toxicity of the metals they invariably carry.

**Testable Prediction**: Preparing Aβ oligomers under rigorously metal-free conditions (chelexed buffers, metal-free labware, confirmed by ICP-MS) and testing their synaptotoxicity in metal-free ACSF should show dramatically reduced LTP impairment compared to standard preparations. Adding back Fe³⁺ or Cu²⁺ should restore toxicity.

**Key Citations for Section 4.7 (Iron-Aβ Cofactor)**:

- Ott S et al. (2015) Dis Model Mech 8(7):657-67. [doi:10.1242/dmm.019042](https://doi.org/10.1242/dmm.019042) [Iron is specific cofactor for Aβ toxicity; His6/13/14 mediate metal-dependent mechanisms]
- Bolognin S et al. (2011) Int J Biochem Cell Biol 43(6):877-85. [doi:10.1016/j.biocel.2011.02.009](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biocel.2011.02.009) [Fe³⁺/Al³⁺ induce annular protofibrils; Cu²⁺/Zn²⁺ prevent fibril formation]
- Sarell CJ et al. (2009) Biochemistry 48(20):4388-402. [doi:10.1021/bi900254n](https://doi.org/10.1021/bi900254n) [Cu²⁺ binding to Aβ fibrils at picomolar affinity]
- Chen WT et al. (2011) J Biol Chem 286(11):9646-56. [doi:10.1074/jbc.M110.177246](https://doi.org/10.1074/jbc.M110.177246) [Fe³⁺/Cu²⁺ inhibit fibril formation; Zn²⁺ promotes annular protofibrils; distinct metal effects on Aβ stability]

