## 6. Multiple Sclerosis

> See diagram: `diagrams/ms-progression-bifurcation.mmd`

### 6.1 EBV-Iron-Ferroptosis Axis

MS has traditionally been framed as a pure autoimmune disease. FELINE proposes a bifurcated model:

**Phase 1 (RRMS) -- Autoimmune-dominant**: EBV infection triggers molecular mimicry -> anti-myelin autoimmunity -> relapsing-remitting attacks. Anti-CD20 therapy effectively prevents new attacks.

**Phase 2 (Progressive MS) -- Iron/ferroptosis-dominant**: Repeated OL destruction releases iron into lesions. Iron becomes trapped in microglia (visible as paramagnetic rim lesions on MRI). This smoldering iron-driven neurodegeneration proceeds independently of autoimmune attacks.

**Key distinction**: The transition from RRMS to progressive MS is the transition from autoimmune attack to iron-driven ferroptosis. This explains why immunosuppression helps in RRMS but not progressive MS.

#### Ferroptosis Creates Neoantigens: The Autoimmune Amplification Loop

Ferroptotic cells don't just die -- they activate the adaptive immune system against healthy neural tissue, creating a devastating amplification loop.

**Oxidation-Specific Epitopes (OSEs)**:

Ferroptosis generates modified self-proteins that become immunogenic (Binder et al. 2016, Nat Rev Immunol, [DOI: 10.1038/nri.2016.63](https://doi.org/10.1038/nri.2016.63)):

> "Oxidation-specific epitopes (OSEs) function as markers of oxidative damage of membrane lipids... OSEs represent endogenous damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs)"

| OSE Type      | Structure                         | Recognized By                    | Function                          |
| ------------- | --------------------------------- | -------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| MDA adducts   | Malondialdehyde-protein           | IgM NAb, SR-A, CFH               | Marks damaged cells for clearance |
| 4-HNE adducts | 4-hydroxynonenal-protein          | B1 cell IgM, scavenger receptors | Creates immunogenic neoantigens   |
| OxPC          | Oxidized phosphatidylcholine      | CD36, EO6 IgM, CRP, TLR2         | Pro-inflammatory signaling        |
| OxPS          | Oxidized phosphatidylserine       | CD36                             | "Eat-me" signal for phagocytes    |
| OxPE          | Oxidized phosphatidylethanolamine | TLR2                             | Ferroptosis execution signal      |

**Breakthrough: Ferroptotic Neurons Directly Activate T Cells** (Luoqian et al. 2022, Cell Mol Immunol, [DOI: 10.1038/s41423-022-00883-0](https://doi.org/10.1038/s41423-022-00883-0)):

> "Ferroptotic lipid peroxidation was elevated BEFORE T-cell activation at the early stage of EAE. When naive CD4+ T cells were activated, ferroptotic supernatants [from neurons] enhanced the secretions of IL-2 and IFNgamma from T cells"

Key experimental proof:

1. Neurons treated with RSL3 (ferroptosis inducer) release factors into supernatant
2. This supernatant enhances T cell activation (increased IL-2, IFNgamma)
3. Adoptive transfer of these T cells exacerbates EAE (MS model)
4. Liproxstatin-1 (ferroptosis inhibitor) blocks T cell infiltration
5. ACSL4 knockdown prevents ferroptosis AND prevents EAE onset

Critical finding: Ferroptosis PRECEDES T cell activation -- it initiates immune activation, not the reverse.

**The Complete Autoimmune Amplification Loop**:

1. Iron dysregulation (FELINE root cause)
2. Functional iron deficiency in OLs
3. GPX4 dysfunction -> ferroptosis initiation -> lipid peroxides, MDA, 4-HNE adducts form
4. Modified self-proteins become immunogenic (OSEs displayed)
5. T cell activation: ferroptotic products activate CD4+ T cells; IFNgamma released
6. IFNgamma induces immunoproteasome (PSMB8) in neurons -> metabolic shift -> further GPX4 suppression (Woo et al. 2025, Cell, [DOI: 10.1016/j.cell.2025.05.030](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2025.05.030))
7. Autoimmune attack on healthy tissue: activated T cells infiltrate CNS, attack cells displaying OSEs
8. Attacked cells undergo ferroptosis -> MORE OSEs -> MORE T cells -> EPITOPE SPREADING

**IFNgamma Creates a Feed-Forward Destruction Loop**:

Woo et al. 2025 (Cell):

> "IFNgamma-mediated induction of the immunoproteasome subunit PSMB8 impairs proteasomal balance... leading to enhanced neuronal glycolysis, reduced pentose phosphate pathway activity, oxidative injury, and ferroptosis"

Mechanism: T cells release IFNgamma -> IFNgamma induces PSMB8 in neurons -> PSMB8 impairs proteasomal activity -> PFKFB3 accumulation -> metabolic shift -> reduced antioxidant capacity -> neurons become VULNERABLE to ferroptosis -> MORE ferroptosis -> MORE T cell activation -> MORE IFNgamma.

Therapeutic validation: PSMB8 inhibitors (ONX-0914) protect neurons in EAE.

**4-HNE Modified Proteins Trigger Epitope Spreading** (Kurien and Scofield 2008, Autoimmun Rev, [DOI: 10.1016/j.autrev.2008.04.019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.autrev.2008.04.019)):

> "Proteins modified by 4-hydroxy-2-nonenal are highly immunogenic... Immunization with HNE-modified 60 kD Ro autoantigen induces accelerated epitope spreading"

Once the immune system recognizes 4-HNE-modified self-proteins, it progressively expands to recognize unmodified versions: 4-HNE-modified myelin protein -> initial T/B cell response -> epitope spreading -> recognition of NATIVE myelin -> autoimmune attack on healthy myelin. This explains progressive MS: initial ferroptotic damage creates neoantigens, then the immune response SPREADS.

**B Cell Long-Term Memory Problem**: Persistent ferroptosis -> chronic OSE exposure -> B cell class switching (IgM -> IgG) -> memory B cells form -> PERMANENT autoimmune potential. Even if ferroptosis stops, immune memory persists.

**Why anti-CD20 fails to stop progression**: Depletes peripheral B cells but:

- Cannot address upstream ferroptosis (debris keeps being generated)
- Cannot eliminate CNS-resident iron-laden microglia
- Cannot stop ongoing lipid peroxidation
- May impair protective OSE-recognizing natural IgM

#### OPC Differentiation Dynamics: The Constitutive Repair Problem

**The Mironova 2026 Breakthrough** (Science, [DOI: 10.1126/science.adu2896](https://doi.org/10.1126/science.adu2896)): OPCs attempt to differentiate constitutively throughout the adult CNS at a constant rate -- INDEPENDENT of myelin demand or oligodendrocyte loss.

Previous assumption: Demyelination -> signal to OPCs -> OPCs respond -> differentiation -> remyelination.

Reality: OPCs differentiate CONSTITUTIVELY everywhere. Most differentiating OPCs DIE before maturing. Successful OL formation is rare. Demyelination does NOT increase differentiation rate. Aging DECREASES it. Inflammation SUPPRESSES it.

| Factor        | Effect on OPC Differentiation     | FELINE Interpretation              |
| ------------- | --------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Demyelination | NO CHANGE in differentiation rate | OPCs can't "sense" demyelination   |
| Aging         | DECREASED differentiation rate    | Age-related decline                |
| Inflammation  | SUPPRESSED differentiation rate   | Clearance response PREVENTS repair |

**The Unified Remyelination Failure Cascade**:

1. OPCs constitutively attempt differentiation (baseline process)
2. Iron dysregulation (FELINE root cause): astrocyte Cp-Fpn dysfunction -> iron maldistribution
3. Differentiating OPCs undergo ferroptosis: high metabolic demand, high iron requirement, limited antioxidant capacity during transition, GPX4 vulnerability during state change
4. Ferroptotic OPCs generate DAMPs/OSEs (oxidized lipids, modified proteins, debris)
5. Immune system responds TO CLEAR DEBRIS (microglia activate, T cells respond)
6. Clearance response SUPPRESSES OPC differentiation (IFNgamma, TNF-alpha inhibit maturation)
7. Iron dysregulation CONTINUES (root cause unaddressed) -> more ferroptosis
8. More debris -> more clearance -> more suppression -> LOOP

**The Critical Reframe**:

| Old Model                                        | New Model                                                        |
| ------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Ferroptosis + "Autoimmune attack" (two problems) | Ferroptosis -> Clearance response (one problem, one consequence) |
| Immune system as "attacker"                      | Immune system as "janitor" responding to genuine damage          |
| Need to suppress immune system                   | Need to stop generating debris                                   |
| Inflammation is pathological                     | Inflammation is appropriate but becomes chronic                  |

**The tragic irony**: OPCs constantly try to repair. They undergo ferroptosis during differentiation. The immune system correctly responds to clear debris. But that clearance response suppresses other OPCs from differentiating. The solution is not immunosuppression -- it is stopping ferroptosis.

**Distinguishing Test**: In progressive MS patients on anti-CD20, adding a ferroptosis inhibitor should increase successful OPC differentiation, reduce PRL iron content, improve remyelination markers (MTR recovery), and potentially stabilize disability. This has NOT been tested but is a specific, falsifiable prediction.

#### Mendelian Randomization: Genetic Proof of Functional Iron Deficiency

Tang et al. 2024 (Front Immunol, [DOI: 10.3389/fimmu.2024.1376838](https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1376838), [PMID: 38590521](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38590521)):

| Iron Biomarker         | Effect on MS Risk        | OR (95% CI)      | p-value  |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------ | ---------------- | -------- |
| Transferrin            | Increased INCREASES risk | 1.22 (1.10-1.36) | 2.18E-04 |
| Transferrin saturation | Increased DECREASES risk | 0.86 (0.75-0.98) | 2.22E-02 |
| Serum iron             | No effect                | 0.96 (0.79-1.17) | 0.68     |
| Serum ferritin         | No effect                | 1.04 (0.70-1.55) | 0.83     |

**Why this is a smoking gun for FELINE**: The apparent contradiction resolves when understanding what these biomarkers mean:

- High transferrin = body compensating for iron deficiency (making more carrier protein)
- Low transferrin saturation = carriers empty (iron not being delivered)
- Total iron/ferritin = not predictive (confirms problem is DISTRIBUTION, not AMOUNT)

This genetic evidence is UNCONFOUNDED (MR eliminates reverse causation and confounders) and proves that functional iron delivery failure is CAUSAL for MS -- exactly what FELINE predicts.

**Therapeutic implication**: Need to RESTORE astrocyte iron distribution to neurons/OLs and glymphatic drainage, not chelate total iron. Ceruloplasmin supplementation showed benefit in PD models (Ayton et al. 2013, [DOI: 10.1002/ana.23817](https://doi.org/10.1002/ana.23817)). Ferroportin stabilizers and hepcidin antagonists are conceptual targets.

### 6.2 MS Predictions vs. Observed Outcomes

| Intervention                         | Autoimmune Prediction        | FELINE Prediction                                                     | Observed Outcome                      |
| ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Anti-CD20 in RRMS                    | Works                        | Works (prevents new attacks)                                          | WORKS                                 |
| Anti-CD20 in progressive MS          | Should work (same mechanism) | FAILS (can't cross BBB, can't clear trapped iron)                     | FAILS                                 |
| Iron chelation in MS                 | Might help                   | IS INEFFECTIVE/HARMS (removes functional iron, trapped iron persists) | 5/9 worsened (Lynch 2000)             |
| PRL count predicts PIRA              | Not predicted                | More PRL = more trapped iron = worse progression                      | Consistent with FELINE (OR 2.24-2.87) |
| PRL count predicts anti-CD20 failure | Not predicted                | More PRL = worse response                                             | Consistent with FELINE                |

**Critical Finding: CSF Transferrin Decreased = Iron Export Failure**

Khalil et al. 2014 (Mult Scler, [PMID: 24777275](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24777275)):

- CSF transferrin significantly decreased in CIS/early MS vs controls (p<0.001)
- Higher CSF transferrin correlated with LOWER physical disability (r=-0.3, p<0.05)
- Serum transferrin was NOT different between groups

FELINE interpretation: This is evidence for the MISLOCATION hypothesis. Iron is being trapped in tissue (not exported to CSF). Lower CSF transferrin = less iron being properly exported = worse outcomes. The correct biomarker is PRL on MRI (directly visualizes trapped iron in microglia), not CSF iron measures.

**Approved MS Drug Works Via Anti-Ferroptosis**: Fischer et al. 2025 (J Neuroinflammation, [DOI: 10.1186/s12974-025-03592-3](https://doi.org/10.1186/s12974-025-03592-3)) showed dimethyl fumarate (DMF) and diroximel fumarate (DRF) work by activating Nrf2 pathway -> upregulating anti-ferroptotic enzymes. Anti-ferroptotic enzymes upregulated in oligodendrocytes upon DRF treatment, cerebellum of DMF-treated mice, and PBMCs of patients receiving DMF. Effect is disease-specific: NOT seen in fibroblasts from arthritis patients. This represents inadvertent L-layer therapy -- DMF/DRF were thought to work primarily via immunomodulation, but their efficacy in progressive MS may be due to direct anti-ferroptotic effects on OLs.

#### Anti-CD20 in Progressive MS: Observed Outcome

Dal-Bianco/Absinta (eBioMedicine 2023) tracked 202 PRLs in 72 MS patients on anti-CD20 therapy:

- NONE of the treated paramagnetic rims disappeared at 2-year follow-up
- No treatment effect on PRL volume, magnetic susceptibility, or T1 time
- PIRA occurred in 20% of treated patients; more frequent with 4+ PRLs (p=0.027)
- Only 4.3% of lymphocytes in chronic active lesions were CD20+ B cells

The iron-laden microglia driving smoldering inflammation are NOT targeted by anti-CD20.

#### PRL Count and Disability Progression

Systematic review (Zarco et al., Mult Scler Relat Disord 2025, [PMID: 41205558](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41205558)), meta-analysis of 5 studies (n=744):

- PRLs associated with 2.24x higher risk of PIRA (OR 2.24; 95% CI: 1.17-4.29; p=0.01)
- PRLs associated with 2.87x higher risk of CDP (OR 2.87; 95% CI: 1.01-8.1; p=0.05)

Additional validation (Reeves et al., Neurology 2024, [PMID: 39447104](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39447104)):

- PRL disappearance associated with REDUCED PIRA (beta=-0.283, p=0.036)
- New PRL appearance associated with INCREASED PIRA (beta=0.223, p=0.036)

**10-year longitudinal study** (Reeves et al., Mult Scler 2024, [PMID: 38366920](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38366920)):

- n=172 MS patients, mean follow-up 10.2 years
- Greater PRL number -> greater rate of yearly EDSS change (beta=0.045, p=0.01)
- Greater PRL number -> greater odds of PIRA (exp(beta)=1.171 per PRL, p=0.009)
- Association between PRL presence and EDSS increase was 96.7% INDEPENDENT of relapse number

This proves trapped iron (visualized as PRL) drives disability progression through non-relapse mechanisms.

#### Ferroptosis in OL Death in MS

Jhelum et al. 2023 (Acta Neuropathol Commun, [DOI: 10.1186/s40478-023-01617-7](https://doi.org/10.1186/s40478-023-01617-7)) in chronic EAE AND human SPMS autopsy tissue:

- NCOA4 (ferritinophagy receptor) expression increased at peak and progressive stages
- Redox-active ferrous iron increased parallel to NCOA4
- Antioxidant pathway (system xCT, GPX4, GSH) all REDUCED
- Lipid peroxidation markers ELEVATED
- Ferroptosis inhibitor treatment for 2 weeks improved function and pathology
- Human SPMS tissue: NCOA4+ cells express LESS ferritin -> evidence of active ferritinophagy

#### The NLGH Profile: Molecular Signature of "Smoldering" MS

Rodero-Romero et al. 2025 (Front Immunol, [DOI: 10.3389/fimmu.2025.1729500](https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2025.1729500)) identified NLGH = Normal NfL + High GFAP (non-inflammatory disability worsening):

| Marker                     | Change | Implication                                |
| -------------------------- | ------ | ------------------------------------------ |
| EGF                        | Down   | Astrocyte-derived repair factor DEPLETED   |
| CCL2                       | Down   | Monocyte/memory T cell recruitment REDUCED |
| CCL3, CCL4, CCL7           | Down   | Chemokine network SUPPRESSED               |
| FLT3LG, TNFSF12, TNF-alpha | Down   | Adaptive immune activation REDUCED         |

FELINE interpretation: NLGH = "burned out" peripheral inflammation + ongoing CNS-compartmentalized pathology. This is why anti-CD20 fails in progressive MS: peripheral inflammation (NfL) is LOW (nothing to target), while CNS glial pathology (GFAP) is HIGH (inaccessible to B cell depletion).

#### Gut-Brain Axis: Stool GFAP in Progressive MS

Schwerdtfeger et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1212/NXI.0000000000200466): Stool GFAP elevated in progressive MS vs. RRMS and controls. Correlated with baseline EDSS, 25-foot walk time, and predicted EDSS increase at 2 and 5 years. Enteric glial hyperplasia found in colonic mucosa of PPMS patient. FELINE interpretation: Enteric glia share lineage with CNS astrocytes and respond to systemic stress, supporting FELINE's emphasis on glial dysfunction as a pan-system phenomenon.

#### Chelation Evidence in MS

Lynch et al. 2000 ([PMID: 10875447](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10875447)): Nine patients with chronic progressive MS received up to 8 courses of deferoxamine over 2 years: 1 improved, 3 stable, 5 worsened. Conclusion: "no effect on disease progression can be identified."

This outcome parallels FAIRPARK-II: chelation removes functional iron while leaving trapped iron in PRLs. The correct approach is not chelation but ferroptosis inhibition and iron flow restoration.

#### Testable MS Predictions

| Prediction                                          | Test Design            | FELINE Outcome                     |
| --------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Ferroptosis inhibitor helps progressive MS          | Phase II trial in SPMS | Slows PIRA, reduces PRL expansion  |
| Anti-CD20 + ferroptosis inhibitor > anti-CD20 alone | Combination trial      | Combination superior for PIRA      |
| PRL volume predicts chelation harm                  | Post-hoc analysis      | High PRL = worse chelation outcome |
| DMF efficacy correlates with GPX4 upregulation      | Biomarker study        | Responders show higher GPX4        |

### 6.3 Regional Variation

Progressive MS shows distinct regional patterns:

- **Subcortical lesions**: Paramagnetic rim lesions (iron-laden microglia), smoldering expansion
- **Spinal cord**: Different vascular anatomy, different iron handling
- **Cortical lesions**: Less iron rim, more neuronal loss

FELINE predicts these differences reflect regional variation in E-layer capacity: subcortical white matter has the densest OL population (most iron to release), while cortical regions have different glymphatic/clearance dynamics.

---

## 7. Non-AD Neurodegenerative Diseases

### 7.1 Cross-Disease Layer Mapping

> See diagram: `diagrams/layer-entry-points.mmd`

Different diseases enter FELINE through different layers but converge on the same endpoint: iron-driven ferroptosis in vulnerable cell populations.

| Disease                       | Primary Entry Layer           | Key Mechanism                                        | Ferroptosis Evidence                    |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| **Alzheimer's**         | N (pericyte loss, BBB)        | Endfoot dual failure -> clearance + iron export loss | Brain iron elevated, GPX4 reduced       |
| **Parkinson's**         | L (alpha-syn, lysosomes)      | Lysosomal dysfunction -> iron release                | SN iron elevated, ferroptosis markers   |
| **MS**                  | I (autoimmune OL destruction) | OL death -> iron release -> PRLs                     | Iron rim lesions, OL ferroptosis        |
| **ALS**                 | N (NVU) + L (autophagy)       | Motor neuron autophagy failure + NVU damage          | Motor neuron iron, GPX4                 |
| **PSP**                 | I (astrocyte tau)             | Tau-iron cycle in astrocytes/OLs                     | Iron in all 5 brain regions             |
| **Huntington's**        | L (huntingtin, autophagy)     | Huntingtin disrupts autophagy -> iron                | Striatal iron elevated                  |
| **Prion/CJD**           | E (hepcidin-ferroportin)      | PrPSc -> hepcidin up -> ferroportin down             | Redox-active Fe(II) increased           |
| **FTD**                 | L + I                         | TDP-43/tau variants                                  | Iron accumulation documented            |
| **Friedreich's Ataxia** | L (mitochondrial)             | Frataxin deficiency -> mitochondrial iron            | Iron dyshomeostasis, lipid peroxidation |
| **MSA**                 | I (OL alpha-syn)              | Alpha-synuclein in oligodendrocytes                  | Iron metabolism dysregulation           |
| **Shingles/VZV**        | N (vasculopathy) + I          | Viral damage to NVU + ferroptosis hijacking          | HSV-1 suppresses GPX4                   |

#### Comprehensive FELINE Layer Comparison

**Fe (Iron) Layer -- Universal but Mechanism Varies**:

| Disease         | Iron Status                    | Key Finding                            | Unique Feature                            |
| --------------- | ------------------------------ | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **AD**    | Accumulation in plaques, NFTs  | Iron precedes cognitive decline        | Compartmentalized in aggregates           |
| **PD**    | Substantia nigra iron overload | Neuromelanin iron saturation           | Alpha-synuclein iron binding              |
| **ALS**   | Motor cortex accumulation      | Correlates with disease progression    | BSCB breakdown -> hemoglobin-derived iron |
| **HD**    | Striatal Cu + Fe               | CSF metals elevated BEFORE mHtt        | Copper-enhanced toxicity                  |
| **MS**    | Paramagnetic rim lesions       | Trapped in microglia at lesion edges   | Visualizable on 7T MRI                    |
| **PSP**   | All 5 brain regions elevated   | Autopsy-confirmed with Prussian blue   | Iron along myelinated fibers              |
| **FTD**   | Variable by subtype            | TDP-43 subtypes show iron              | Less characterized than AD/PD             |
| **Prion** | Redox-active Fe(II) increased  | Hepcidin elevation -> ferroportin down | Export failure mechanism                  |

**L (Lysosome) Layer -- Degree of Involvement Varies**:

| Disease         | Lysosomal Status        | Key Finding                           | FELINE Interpretation                             |
| --------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| **AD**    | Central (Nixon PANTHOS) | v-ATPase failure, LMP                 | L-layer is PRIMARY entry point for sporadic AD    |
| **PD**    | Central (GBA1, LRRK2)   | Alpha-synuclein overwhelms autophagy  | L-layer failure -> alpha-syn accumulation         |
| **HD**    | Prominent               | mHtt disrupts autophagy               | Polyglutamine disrupts lysosomal function         |
| **ALS**   | Prominent               | TDP-43 aggregates in autolysosomes    | L-layer failure -> TDP-43 accumulation            |
| **PSP**   | Secondary               | Tau handled differently than AD       | I-layer primary, L-layer secondary                |
| **MS**    | Secondary               | LANDO implicated in some studies      | I-layer primary, L-layer affected by inflammation |
| **Prion** | Overwhelmed             | PrPSc overwhelms degradative capacity | Direct lysosomal overload                         |

**I (Insulation) Layer -- Myelin and Iron Buffering**:

| Disease        | Insulation Status | Key Finding                              | FELINE Interpretation                        |
| -------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| **AD**   | Secondary         | White matter changes precede gray matter | OLs vulnerable; tau/A-beta as backup buffers |
| **PD**   | Secondary         | Alpha-synuclein in OLs (MSA variant)     | Alpha-syn as iron buffer                     |
| **MS**   | PRIMARY           | Autoimmune OL destruction                | I-layer entry, then ferroptosis cascade      |
