| **FRDA** | Affected          | Mitochondrial iron -> myelin effects     | L-layer primary, I-layer affected            |

**N (Neurovascular) Layer -- BBB and Pericyte Status**:

| Disease       | NVU Status                 | Key Finding                     | FELINE Interpretation               |
| ------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| **AD**  | PRIMARY (especially APOE4) | Pericyte loss precedes symptoms | N-layer is common entry point       |
| **PD**  | Variable                   | BBB intact in early stages      | N-layer secondary                   |
| **ALS** | Affected                   | BSCB breakdown documented       | N-layer involved, especially HERV-K |
| **VaD** | PRIMARY                    | Vascular damage by definition   | N-layer entry                       |
| **MS**  | Affected                   | BBB breach during relapses      | N-layer damaged during attacks      |
| **PSP** | Secondary                  | Brainstem vasculature affected  | Not primary entry                   |

**E (Export) Layer -- Clearance and Iron Export**:

| Disease         | Export Status     | Key Finding                              | FELINE Interpretation          |
| --------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **AD**    | Impaired          | Ferroportin reduced, glymphatic impaired | Dual failure at endfeet        |
| **PD**    | Impaired          | Ceruloplasmin reduced                    | E-layer affected, not primary  |
| **Prion** | PRIMARY           | Hepcidin up -> ferroportin down          | E-layer blockade               |
| **MS**    | Compartmentalized | Iron trapped in lesions                  | E-layer failure within lesions |
| **Aging** | Declining         | Glymphatic function decreases with age   | Universal E-layer aging        |

**Aggregation Spectrum: From Protective to Toxic**:

| Protein                   | Disease Context | Primary Role                                    | When Does It Become Toxic?                    |
| ------------------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| **A-beta**          | AD              | Iron concentration/sequestration, antimicrobial | When oligomers overwhelm plaque sequestration |
| **Tau**             | AD, PSP, FTD    | Iron binding, microtubule stabilization         | When hyperphosphorylation -> aggregation      |
| **Alpha-synuclein** | PD, MSA, DLB    | Ferrireductase, synaptic function               | When lysosomal capacity overwhelmed           |
| **TDP-43**          | ALS, FTD, LATE  | RNA processing                                  | When mislocalized from nucleus                |
| **Huntingtin**      | HD              | Various (unclear normal function)               | When polyQ expansion passes threshold         |
| **PrP**             | Prion disease   | Copper binding, neuronal protection             | When misfolded to PrPSc                       |
| **SOD1**            | ALS             | Superoxide dismutation                          | When misfolded/aggregated                     |

Key insight: Aggregation is NOT inherently pathological. It often represents failed emergency responses. The proteins aggregate BECAUSE they are attempting to handle iron or other stressors. Aggregation becomes toxic when it overwhelms clearance capacity (L-layer) or releases more iron than can be handled (I-layer overflow).

