#### FELINE as Common Substrate: The Modifier Taxonomy

FELINE describes the shared engine of neurodegeneration -- iron dysregulation leading to ferroptosis leading to cell death. What differentiates individual neurodegenerative diseases is not the engine itself but the disease-specific modifiers that determine (a) which cells are affected, (b) how fast the process runs, and (c) what additional pathology layers on top. Iron is necessary but not sufficient; each disease adds something unique.

**The Tempo Spectrum: BBB Integrity as Rate-Limiting Step**

The single most powerful predictor of disease tempo is the status of the blood-brain barrier / neurovascular unit:

| Condition                  | BBB/NVU Status                      | FELINE Tempo  | Mortality                      |
| -------------------------- | ----------------------------------- | ------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **Normal aging**     | Gradual degradation                 | Decades       | Normal lifespan                |
| **AD (APOE4)**       | Accelerated NVU damage              | Years-decades | Dementia over 8-12 years       |
| **PD**               | Largely intact; SN-specific iron    | Years-decades | Motor decline then dementia    |
| **MS (relapsing)**   | Acute immune-mediated breach        | Episodic      | Remitting disability           |
| **MS (progressive)** | Compartmentalized CNS inflammation  | Years         | Progressive disability         |
| **ALS**              | Variable BBB changes                | Months-years  | Fatal (median 3-5 years)       |
| **Shingles (HZ)**    | NVU damaged via arterial adventitia | Months-years  | Dementia risk increased 20%    |
| **VZV encephalitis** | BBB catastrophically breached       | Days          | 10-15% fatal (immunocompetent) |
| **HSV encephalitis** | BBB catastrophically breached       | Days          | Up to 70% fatal untreated      |

HSV encephalitis produces hemorrhagic necrosis of the same regions affected in AD -- medial temporal lobes, hippocampus, insular cortex, cingulate gyrus. This is FELINE on fast-forward: acute BBB breach produces massive iron release from hemorrhage, triggering rapid ferroptotic/necrotic neuronal death in hours instead of decades.

**Disease-Specific Modifiers on Top of FELINE**:

| Disease         | FELINE Substrate              | Disease-Specific Modifier                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       | Why This Disease Looks Different                                            |
| --------------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **AD**    | Iron + ferroptosis + NVU      | Sex/hormonal iron transport: menopause removes menstrual iron export; APOE4 accelerates NVU damage via CypA-MMP9; HSV-1/VZV viral debris as chronic irritant; Rahman 2025: sex-specific iron-ferritin correlation reversal in AD microglia (negative in women, positive in men) | Cortical, diffuse, dementia-dominant; strong female sex bias post-menopause |
| **PD**    | Iron + ferroptosis            | Neuromelanin iron architecture: SN neurons contain neuromelanin that buffers iron for decades then fails; alpha-synuclein initially binds iron protectively, transitions to toxic                                                                                               | Subcortical, focal (SN/striatum), movement-dominant; male sex bias          |
| **MS**    | Iron + ferroptosis + OL death | Autoimmune trigger + iron rim dynamics: immune-mediated OL death releases iron, microglia form paramagnetic rim lesions (PRLs) as smoldering ferroptotic inflammation                                                                                                           | White matter, episodic then progressive; iron rims as biomarker             |
| **ALS**   | Iron + ferroptosis            | Motor neuron metabolic vulnerability: highest metabolic rate neurons; SOD1 handles iron/copper; TDP-43 may serve protective role; possible HERV-K trigger                                                                                                                       | Motor neuron selective, rapid, fatal                                        |
| **HD**    | Iron + ferroptosis            | Genetic expansion producing genuinely toxic protein: polyQ makes huntingtin toxic (unlike protective A-beta/tau); copper + iron synergy                                                                                                                                         | Genetic, striatal, choreiform movement + dementia                           |
| **Prion** | Iron + ferroptosis            | Self-templating misfolding: PrPSc is genuinely infectious and toxic; copper-iron synergy enhances toxicity                                                                                                                                                                      | Infectious, rapid, invariably fatal                                         |

**The MS Iron Rim as FELINE Biomarker**:

Paramagnetic rim lesions (PRLs) in MS directly visualize the FELINE cascade:

1. Immune attack kills oligodendrocytes (the trigger, not part of FELINE)
2. OL death releases stored iron (Fe layer -- OLs are the most iron-rich brain cells)
3. Iron uptake by activated microglia, visible as paramagnetic rim on QSM/SWI
4. Microglia undergo ferroptosis from iron overload (L layer)
5. Myelin loss from dead OLs (I layer -- insulation failure)
6. Failed clearance of iron-laden debris (E layer)
7. Chronic smoldering expansion as the rim slowly grows outward

PRLs identify patients where FELINE-based interventions could help: iron rim present indicates active ferroptotic process (target Fe/L layers); iron rim resolving indicates potential for remyelination (ensure adequate iron for OL recovery, NOT chelation).

**The Varicella Severity Spectrum**: VZV provides a natural experiment testing FELINE's tempo prediction. The same virus, the same iron mechanisms, but vastly different tempos based solely on whether the BBB holds: chickenpox (BBB intact, no neurodegeneration), shingles (slow NVU damage via arterial adventitia, dementia risk increased over years), VZV encephalitis (BBB catastrophically breached, FELINE cascade in hours/days, 10-15% mortality).

#### The Aggregation Spectrum

```
PROTECTIVE AGGREGATION <---------------------------> TOXIC AGGREGATION

Tau (AD)              Alpha-Synuclein           mHtt (HD)
A-beta (AD)           (context-dependent)        PrPSc (Prion)
TDP-43 (ALS/FTD)

Iron-buffering        Transition state          Direct toxicity
Emergency response    Losing protective         Metal binding
                      function                  ENHANCES toxicity
```

#### Key Cross-Disease Insights

1. **Fe Layer is universal** but mechanism varies: protective compartmentalization failure (AD, PD) vs. toxic protein-metal binding (HD, Prion)
2. **L Layer (Ferroptosis) is the convergent death pathway** across ALL diseases -- strongest evidence for universal therapeutic target
3. **I Layer varies dramatically**: Aggregation can be protective (AD, FTD) or toxic (HD, Prion) -- determined by whether normal protein serves metal-handling function
4. **N Layer breakdown is EARLY in multiple diseases** (ALS, HD, Prion) -- not just AD -- suggesting NVU damage as potential universal initiator
5. **E Layer dysfunction is common** but understudied in some diseases -- glymphatic enhancement may benefit all conditions

#### Implications for Cross-Disease Therapeutics

If ferroptosis is the final common pathway across neurodegenerative diseases, then:

| Strategy                                  | Mechanism  | Diseases Applicable         | Priority         |
| ----------------------------------------- | ---------- | --------------------------- | ---------------- |
| GPX4 induction/protection                 | L layer    | ALL                         | HIGHEST          |
| Iron compartmentalization (not chelation) | Fe layer   | ALL                         | HIGHEST          |
| Glymphatic enhancement (sleep, exercise)  | E layer    | ALL                         | HIGH             |
| Lysosomal protection                      | L layer    | ALL                         | HIGH             |
| Pericyte protection                       | N layer    | AD, ALS, HD                 | Disease-specific |
| Antiviral (HSV-1, VZV)                    | N/I layers | AD, possibly others         | Disease-specific |
| Copper chelation                          | Fe layer   | HD, Prion                   | Disease-specific |
| Anti-aggregation                          | I layer    | HD, Prion (genuinely toxic) | Disease-specific |

### 7.2 ALS

ALS demonstrates FELINE mechanisms through multiple entry points, with evidence for all five layers being involved.

#### NVU Involvement

HERV-K (endogenous retrovirus) reactivation damages motor neuron NVU. BBB/blood-spinal cord barrier (BSCB) breakdown is well-documented in ALS.

**Critical finding**: Winkler et al. demonstrated 54% pericyte reduction in ALS spinal cord BEFORE motor neuron loss. This temporal sequence is exactly what FELINE predicts: N-layer damage precedes neurodegeneration.

**HERV-K mechanism**: HERV-K env protein is directly toxic to motor neurons (transgenic mice develop motor neuron disease). HERV-K reactivation may be triggered by TDP-43 loss of function (TDP-43 normally suppresses retrotransposon expression).

#### Autophagy Failure (L-Layer)

- TDP-43 aggregation impairs autophagy -- TDP-43 normally regulates autophagy genes
- SOD1 mutations increase oxidative stress and impair mitophagy
- C9orf72 repeat expansions disrupt autophagy (C9orf72 protein is involved in autophagy initiation)
- FUS mutations impair stress granule dynamics and autophagy

#### Motor Neuron Vulnerability

Motor neurons have the highest metabolic demand of any neuron type:

- Extremely long axons (up to 1 meter in humans) requiring massive mitochondrial capacity
- High iron content (for cytochrome oxidase in mitochondria along entire axon length)
- Limited regenerative capacity in CNS
- High calcium buffering demands at neuromuscular junctions
- Large soma = large surface area for potential iron-mediated damage

**GPX4 is universally depleted early in ALS**: GPX4 reduction in motor neurons is one of the earliest changes, suggesting ferroptosis vulnerability precedes clinical symptoms.

#### Iron Evidence in ALS

- Iron accumulates in motor cortex and spinal cord
- GPX4 is reduced in motor neurons
- Ferroptosis inhibitors show benefit in ALS mouse models
- Ferritin is elevated in CSF of ALS patients
- QSM-MRI shows iron accumulation in motor cortex early in disease

#### Cross-Layer Cascade in ALS

The ALS FELINE cascade:

1. N-layer: BSCB breakdown (54% pericyte loss) + HERV-K NVU damage
2. L-layer: TDP-43/C9orf72 autophagy failure -> lysosomal dysfunction
3. I-layer: Motor neuron iron compartmentalization fails
4. E-layer: Failed export from spinal cord parenchyma
5. Fe: Iron accumulates -> ferroptosis in motor neurons

This explains why riluzole (glutamate modulator) shows only modest benefit -- it addresses one contributing mechanism but not the multi-layer failure.

### 7.3 PSP and Primary Tauopathies

PSP provides an instructive test case because it is a "pure" 4R tauopathy with extensive glial involvement.

**PSP enters FELINE through the I-layer**: Unlike AD (N-layer entry), PSP pathology begins in astrocytes and oligodendrocytes with tau inclusions ("tufted astrocytes" and "coiled bodies").

**Critical discovery -- Astrocytes make their own tau in PSP**: Jackson et al. 2024 (DOI: 10.1186/s40478-024-01844-6): "In PSP but not in AD, tau-immunoreactive astrocytes have higher levels of MAPT mRNA compared to astrocytes that do not have tau aggregates." This overturns the assumption that glial tau comes solely from neuronal uptake.

**The bidirectional tau-iron cycle**:

- Iron -> Tau: Iron activates GSK-3beta, CDK5, MAPKs and inhibits PP2A, causing tau hyperphosphorylation
- Tau -> Iron: Tau aggregation sequesters iron but also disrupts normal iron handling
- Fe3+ promotes tau aggregation with 4x higher affinity than Fe2+ (Mukherjee & Panda 2021)

**Oligodendrocyte-driven spreading**: Ferrer et al. 2019 demonstrated tau seeding in white matter occurs specifically through oligodendrocytes (coiled bodies), not astrocytes: "Tau deposits were often associated with slight myelin disruption." This directly supports I-layer primacy in PSP.

**Iron in PSP -- Autopsy-confirmed**: Satoh et al. 2025 (DOI: 10.1002/mdc3.70357): Autopsy-confirmed PSP shows iron accumulation validated by Prussian blue staining (r=0.63 correlation with QSM susceptibility). Gold-standard histological confirmation.

### 7.4 Other Diseases

#### Huntington's Disease

HD enters FELINE through L-layer: huntingtin disrupts autophagy. The striatum has the highest iron content of any brain region, making it maximally vulnerable when autophagy fails.

**Copper-Huntingtin Interaction**: Mutant huntingtin sequesters copper, disrupting Cu/Zn-SOD1 and ceruloplasmin function. Since ceruloplasmin is required for ferroportin-mediated iron export, copper sequestration by mutant huntingtin indirectly impairs iron distribution from astrocytes (E-layer connection).

**WNT-Mediated BBB Dysfunction**: WNT signaling maintains BBB integrity. Mutant huntingtin disrupts WNT signaling in cerebral endothelial cells, weakening BBB -> N-layer damage. This explains why HD shows BBB abnormalities despite being classified as a "cell-autonomous" disease.

**HD-specific features**:

- PolyQ expansion directly impairs BDNF transport and mitochondrial function
- CAG repeat length correlates with iron accumulation in caudate/putamen
- Striatal medium spiny neurons have high dopamine receptor density -> dopamine metabolism generates iron-catalyzed ROS
- GPX4 reduction documented in HD striatum

#### Prion Diseases (CJD)

Prion disease enters FELINE through the E-layer: PrPSc triggers hepcidin upregulation, which degrades ferroportin, trapping iron in brain parenchyma.

**PrPC Normal Function**: The normal prion protein (PrPC) has metal-binding function. PrPC binds copper (4-5 Cu2+ ions) and iron, participating in neuronal iron homeostasis. When PrPC misfolds to PrPSc, this metal-handling function is lost.

**The Prion-Iron Axis**:

- PrPSc accumulation -> hepcidin upregulation -> ferroportin degradation -> iron trapping (Chaudhary 2021)
- Misfolded PrPSc loses copper-binding function -> copper deficiency -> ceruloplasmin dysfunction -> impaired iron export
- Iron evidence: Singh 2009 (DOI: 10.1371/journal.ppat.1000336): "increased total and redox-active Fe(II)" in prion disease
- Prion-induced ferroptosis confirmed via RAC3 pathway

**Iron-Calcium Feedback Cycle in Prion Disease**: Iron accumulation dysregulates calcium homeostasis, which activates calcineurin, which further impairs iron handling. This creates a devastating positive feedback loop unique to prion disease due to its rapidity. Calcineurin inhibitors (cyclosporine, tacrolimus) may interrupt this cycle, consistent with epidemiological data showing reduced dementia in CNI-treated transplant patients (Silva et al. 2023).

#### FTD (Frontotemporal Dementia)

FTD variants enter FELINE through different layers:

- **FTLD-TDP**: TDP-43 disrupts autophagy (L-layer). TDP-43 normally suppresses LINE-1 retrotransposon expression; its loss reactivates endogenous retroviruses -> additional cellular stress
- **FTLD-Tau** (Pick's disease): 3R tau aggregation (I-layer). 3R tau has different iron-binding properties than 4R tau
- **FTD-ALS** (C9orf72): Combined autophagy + NVU disruption (L + N layers). C9orf72 repeat expansions disrupt both autophagy initiation and nuclear-cytoplasmic transport
- **GRN (Progranulin) mutations**: Pure L-layer disease. Progranulin is a lysosomal protein; its loss causes lysosomal dysfunction. GRN mutations cause BOTH FTD AND are risk factors for LATE-NC, confirming shared lysosomal mechanism

**TMEM106B connection**: TMEM106B is the strongest genetic risk factor for LATE-NC and modifies FTD-GRN risk. TMEM106B is a lysosomal membrane protein. Its role as a modifier of BOTH FTD and LATE-NC confirms L-layer as the common pathway.

#### LINE-1 Retrotransposon Activation in FTD

TDP-43 loss of function derepresses LINE-1 retrotransposons. Activated L1 elements:

- Generate double-strand DNA breaks -> genomic instability
- Produce cytoplasmic DNA -> activate cGAS-STING innate immune pathway
- Create chronic type I interferon signaling -> neuroinflammation
- May contribute to iron dysregulation via inflammatory hepcidin induction

This connects to FELINE: TDP-43 loss -> L1 activation -> innate immune activation -> hepcidin -> ferroportin degradation -> iron trapping (L -> Fe cascade via inflammatory mediator).

#### PNS: CMT and Diabetic Neuropathy

Peripheral neuropathies show conserved FELINE mechanisms with Schwann cells replacing oligodendrocytes:

- CMT2B: Pure L-layer disease (RAB7 mutation impairs late endosome/lysosome function)
- Diabetic neuropathy: Combined N-layer (vasa nervorum damage) + I-layer (Schwann cell dysfunction)

> See diagram: `diagrams/schwann-cell-states.mmd`

#### Cancer-AD Inverse Relationship

**The Epidemiological Puzzle**

Robust epidemiological evidence shows an inverse relationship between cancer and Alzheimer's disease:

- AD patients are ~47% less likely to develop cancer (RR: 0.53)
- Cancer patients are ~39% less likely to develop AD (RR: 0.61)
- Effect strongest for breast cancer (especially ER+) and AD
- Mendelian randomization supports causality (not just survival bias)

Sources: Zheng 2024 (DOI: 10.1016/j.bbr.2024.115327), Aung 2025 (DOI: 10.1016/j.nbd.2025.107190)

**Conventional Explanations (Inadequate)**

1. **Survival bias**: Cancer patients die before developing AD -> But MR controls for this
2. **Shared risk factors**: Opposite effects of lifestyle factors -> But doesn't explain genetic correlation
3. **Detection bias**: Cancer patients get more medical attention -> But doesn't explain MR findings

**Competing Biological Hypotheses**

| Hypothesis                   | Mechanism                                                     | What It Explains                | What It Doesn't Explain     |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| **Pin1**               | Pin1 overexpressed in cancer, downregulated in AD             | Same protein affects both       | Why IRON is central to both |
| **p53**                | p53 promotes cell death; mutated in cancer, upregulated in AD | Cell survival vs death decision | Why iron chelation fails    |
| **Wnt Signaling**      | Wnt upregulated in cancer, downregulated in AD                | Proliferation vs quiescence     | Layer-specific targeting    |
| **Immune Checkpoints** | PD-1/PD-L1 involvement                                        | Inflammation involvement        | Why OLs are key             |

**FELINE Integration: Ferroptosis as the Pivot**

FELINE doesn't compete with these "upstream" explanations -- it shows WHY they matter. All these pathways converge on FERROPTOSIS:

**Critical Connection**: p53 DIRECTLY REGULATES FERROPTOSIS. p53 promotes ferroptosis by suppressing SLC7A11 (the cystine transporter): p53 up -> SLC7A11 down -> cystine uptake down -> GSH down -> GPX4 activity down -> FERROPTOSIS. This is now a well-established pathway (Ma et al. 2026, [DOI: 10.3389/fphar.2026.1724983](https://doi.org/10.3389/fphar.2026.1724983)).

Cancer cells and neurons have **opposite relationships** with ferroptosis:

| Feature                     | Cancer Cells              | Neurons                            |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| TfR1 (transferrin receptor) | INCREASED                 | Normal/decreased                   |
| Ferroportin (iron export)   | DECREASED                 | Export impaired (N/E layer damage) |
| GPX4, NRF2, FSP1            | INCREASED (defense)       | DECREASED (vulnerability)          |
| Ferritin                    | INCREASED (sequestration) | Ferritinophagy dysfunction         |
| Net Effect                  | FERROPTOSIS RESISTANT     | FERROPTOSIS VULNERABLE             |

Cancer cells are "iron addicts" -- they upregulate iron uptake, suppress export, and boost ferroptosis defenses. This makes them proliferate but also creates a systemic "iron sink" that may protect the brain.

**The Shared Ferroptosis Defense Genes**

Genes that help cancer cells resist ferroptosis also protect neurons:

- **NFS1** (cysteine desulfurase): Upregulated in tumors, protects against ferroptosis in both contexts
- **GPX4**: Master ferroptosis suppressor -- high in cancer, protective in brain
- **NRF2**: Antioxidant transcription factor -- cancer cells upregulate, neurons benefit
- **FSP1**: Ferroptosis suppressor protein 1 -- backup defense in both contexts

Source: Sun 2025 (DOI: 10.3390/biom16010032)

**The APOE Dual Role**

APOE4 increases AD risk BUT also has anti-tumor effects. High APOE expression correlates with anti-tumor immune signatures and is prevalent in early-stage tumors. APOE4 may enhance immune surveillance against nascent cancers while impairing brain iron handling.

**FELINE Integrative Model**

```
CANCER PHENOTYPE                  AD PHENOTYPE
Strong iron sequestration    <->  Poor iron sequestration
Efficient ferroptosis defense <-> Weak ferroptosis defense
Iron "trapped" in tumors     <->  Iron "trapped" in brain
Cancer cells SURVIVE         <->  Nascent tumors DIE
Neurons SURVIVE (low labile Fe) <-> Neurons DIE (ferroptosis)
-------------------------------------------------------------
LOW AD RISK + HIGH CANCER RISK <-> HIGH AD RISK + LOW CANCER RISK
```

**Testable Predictions**

| Prediction                                                 | Test                              | Expected if FELINE Correct                   |
| ---------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Cancer patients have lower CSF iron                        | Measure CSF ferritin, transferrin | Lower free iron in cancer patients           |
| GPX4 SNPs protect against BOTH diseases                    | GWAS overlap analysis             | GPX4 variants protective for both            |
| Ferroptosis-sensitive cancers associate with AD protection | Cancer subtype analysis           | Melanoma patients have lowest AD risk        |
| NRF2 activators benefit BOTH conditions                    | Dual efficacy data                | Sulforaphane reduces both AD and cancer risk |

**Clinical Implications**

1. **Shared therapeutic targets**: Interventions that restore proper iron handling might benefit both conditions
2. **Biomarker development**: Ferroptosis markers (GPX4, 4-HNE, transferrin saturation) may predict risk of both
3. **Risk stratification**: Patients with strong ferroptosis defense may be cancer-prone but AD-protected, and vice versa
4. **Drug repurposing**: Cancer drugs targeting iron metabolism might have neurological effects

This inverse relationship provides external validation for FELINE: ferroptosis is the convergent execution mechanism for neurodegeneration, and variants affecting ferroptosis susceptibility have predictable effects on both cancer and AD risk.

#### P. gingivalis: An Iron Parasite in an Iron-Dysregulated Brain

Chronic periodontitis (affecting ~11% of the global population in severe form) is a significant modifiable risk factor for Alzheimer's disease. The keystone pathogen P. gingivalis is an obligate iron parasite: it cannot synthesize protoporphyrin IX and must steal heme from the host. Its gingipains (Kgp, RgpA/B) serve as both virulence factors AND iron acquisition machinery, cleaving hemoglobin, transferrin, haptoglobin, and hemopexin. P.g. DNA and gingipains are present in human AD brains at significantly higher levels than age-matched controls (Dominy et al. 2019, p < 0.0001).

P.g. is remarkable because it simultaneously attacks all five FELINE layers: gingipains degrade transferrin to release free iron (Fe layer); LPS activates TLR4 neuroinflammation and disrupts lysosomes (L layer); gingipains fragment tau into NFT-seeding peptides (I layer); gingipains degrade tight junction proteins ZO-1 and occludin (N layer); and complement activation impairs glymphatic clearance (E layer). The Olsen (2021) "iron-attraction" hypothesis proposes that pre-existing brain iron dysregulation creates the iron-rich niche that attracts/sustains P.g. colonization, inverting the conventional causal direction. The GAIN trial of atuzaginstat (gingipain inhibitor) failed as monotherapy but showed signals in the P.g.-positive subgroup, consistent with FELINE's prediction that single-pathway targeting in multi-layer failure produces modest effects. See Appendix 4.3 for the complete analysis including the vicious cycle model, A-beta dual-function defense, and P.g. as FELINE subtype identifier.

