## 9. Open Questions

### 9.1 High Priority Studies

| Study                                                            | Design                                                                                            | FELINE Prediction                     | Impact if Confirmed                   |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| **Snta1 KO iron measurement**                              | Measure brain iron (Perls, ICP-MS) + cognition in Snta1 KO mice (which have AQP4 mislocalization) | Iron UP + cognitive deficits          | Would confirm endfoot dual failure    |
| **CSF sPDGFR-beta + iron correlation**                     | Biomarker study: correlate pericyte damage marker with brain iron MRI                             | Positive correlation                  | Would link N-layer to Fe accumulation |
| **Ferroptosis inhibitor + lysosomal enhancer combination** | Animal model: combine liproxstatin + trehalose/P7C3-A20                                           | Synergistic benefit > either alone    | Would validate multi-layer approach   |
| **CypA inhibitor trial**                                   | Test CypA inhibitors (e.g., cyclosporine analogs) in APOE4 carriers                               | Slow pericyte loss + preserve endfeet | Would validate N-layer intervention   |
| **Ferroptosis inhibitor in progressive MS**                | Phase II trial in SPMS patients on anti-CD20                                                      | Slows PIRA, reduces PRL expansion     | Would validate FELINE MS model        |
| **OL iron quantification**                                 | PIXE/SXRF quantification of cell-type-specific iron                                               | OL iron >= 3x neuronal iron           | Would confirm vulnerability hierarchy |

#### Detailed Experiment Designs

**Experiment 1: The Snta1 KO Iron Test (Highest Priority)**

This single experiment would test FELINE's core structural hypothesis. Snta1 KO mice have AQP4 mislocalized away from endfeet. If FELINE is correct, these mice should also have impaired iron export from brain parenchyma.

| Parameter                   | Protocol                             | Expected Result (FELINE)                    | Alternative Result                           |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Brain iron (Perls staining) | 6, 12, 18-month Snta1 KO vs. WT      | Progressive iron accumulation               | No iron change (refutes)                     |
| Brain iron (ICP-MS)         | Regional quantification              | Elevated in cortex, hippocampus             | Normal (refutes)                             |
| Ferroportin localization    | Immunostaining at endfeet            | Reduced at endfeet (co-loss with AQP4)      | Normal ferroportin (partial refutation)      |
| Cognition (MWM, NOR)        | Behavioral testing at each timepoint | Progressive deficits                        | No cognitive change (refutes cascade)        |
| GPX4 expression             | Western blot, IHC                    | Reduced (ferroptosis initiation)            | Normal (iron accumulates but no ferroptosis) |
| Glymphatic function         | CSF tracer injection                 | Impaired (already established for Snta1 KO) | Control comparison                           |
| Lipid peroxidation (4-HNE)  | IHC, ELISA                           | Elevated                                    | Normal                                       |

Critical controls: Include BOTH Snta1 KO (AQP4 mislocalized) and AQP4 KO (AQP4 absent) to distinguish mislocalization from absence effects. Pedersen et al. 2023 showed mislocalization had MORE impact than deletion on A-beta accumulation.

**Experiment 2: CSF Biomarker Correlation Study**

| Biomarker             | Measures                | FELINE Layer |
| --------------------- | ----------------------- | ------------ |
| sPDGFR-beta           | Pericyte damage         | N            |
| QSM-MRI               | Brain iron distribution | Fe           |
| DTI-ALPS index        | Glymphatic function     | E            |
| CSF transferrin       | Iron export capacity    | E            |
| CSF cathepsin D       | Lysosomal function      | L            |
| Myelin water fraction | Myelin integrity        | I            |

FELINE predicts: sPDGFR-beta (pericyte damage) should correlate with BOTH QSM (iron accumulation) AND DTI-ALPS (glymphatic dysfunction) in the same patients, because both depend on intact endfeet maintained by pericytes. No current study has measured all three in the same cohort.

**Experiment 3: Combination Therapy Test**

| Arm         | Agents                        | Layers Targeted | Predicted Outcome                    |
| ----------- | ----------------------------- | --------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Control     | Vehicle                       | None            | Progressive decline                  |
| Mono-L      | P7C3-A20                      | L only          | Moderate benefit                     |
| Mono-E      | Sleep optimization protocol   | E only          | Moderate benefit                     |
| Combination | P7C3-A20 + sleep optimization | L + E           | Synergistic benefit (> sum of parts) |
| Full stack  | P7C3-A20 + sleep + nimodipine | L + E + N       | Maximum benefit                      |

FELINE's core prediction is that combination > monotherapy, and the benefit should be synergistic (not merely additive) because shoring up multiple layers simultaneously prevents rerouting of the ferroptotic cascade.

**Experiment 4: Endfoot Disruption Model Comparison**

| Model                       | What It Disrupts          | What It Preserves            | Expected Iron Effect                          |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------- | ---------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Snta1 KO                    | AQP4 endfoot localization | Ferroportin (presumably)     | Moderate iron increase                        |
| Astrocyte Fpn cKO           | Ferroportin on astrocytes | AQP4 (presumably)            | Iron increase + functional deficiency         |
| Pericyte ablation (DTR)     | Entire NVU structure      | Nothing (endfoot detachment) | Maximum iron increase                         |
| APOE4 knock-in + aging      | CypA-MMP9 pathway         | Initially intact             | Age-dependent iron increase                   |
| Combined Snta1 KO + Fpn cKO | Both AQP4 AND ferroportin | Nothing at endfoot           | FELINE predicts: worst outcome (dual failure) |

The combined model (Snta1 KO + astrocyte Fpn cKO) would directly test whether dual failure is worse than either alone. If iron accumulation and cognitive decline are synergistic (not additive), this supports the endfoot dual failure concept.

### 9.2 Literature Gaps

#### The AQP4-Ferroportin Blind Spot

**PubMed search results (January 2026)**:

| Search Terms                                  | Results                                       |
| --------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| "AQP4" AND "ferroportin"                      | 0                                             |
| "aquaporin-4" AND "iron export" AND "endfoot" | 0                                             |
| "glymphatic" AND "ferroportin"                | 0                                             |
| "AQP4" AND "iron" AND "astrocyte"             | ~15 (none connecting endfoot co-localization) |

This is the central literature gap FELINE addresses: two research communities studying the same structure (astrocyte endfeet) without cross-citation.

**Adjacent literature that almost tests FELINE**:

- AQP4 KO studies measure glymphatic flow but not brain iron
- Ferroportin studies measure iron but not AQP4 status
- Endfoot disruption models exist but don't measure both outcomes simultaneously

**The simple experiment that would test FELINE**: In Snta1 KO mice (AQP4 mislocalized), measure brain iron alongside cognition and glymphatic flow. If iron is elevated AND glymphatic flow is impaired, endfoot dual failure is confirmed.

**Why this gap exists**: AQP4 researchers attend glymphatic/sleep conferences. Ferroportin researchers attend iron biology conferences. Neither group has reason to measure the other's outcome variable.

#### Endfoot Proteomics Gap

No comprehensive proteomic study of astrocyte endfeet has been published. Current knowledge of endfoot composition comes from immunostaining for individual proteins (AQP4, Kir4.1, etc.) rather than unbiased proteomics. A comprehensive endfoot proteome would reveal additional co-localized proteins and potential co-regulated systems.

### 9.3 PNS Extension

FELINE mechanisms are conserved in the peripheral nervous system, with Schwann cells replacing oligodendrocytes and vasa nervorum replacing cerebral vasculature. See **Appendix 3.3** for the comprehensive treatment.

**Layer Conservation in Peripheral Nerves:**

| Layer | CNS Component                            | PNS Equivalent                              | Status     |
| ----- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- | ---------- |
| Fe    | Iron homeostasis                         | Schwann cell iron handling via Cp           | CONSERVED  |
| L     | Lysosomal function                       | Lysosomal function (CMT2B = RAB7 mutations) | CONSERVED  |
| I     | Oligodendrocyte myelin (1 OL : 50 axons) | Schwann cell myelin (1 SC : 1 axon)         | CONSERVED  |
| N     | NVU/BBB (tight)                          | Blood-nerve barrier (more permeable)        | DIFFERENT  |
| E     | Glymphatic/astrocyte clearance           | Schwann cell clearance                      | CONSERVED* |

*Schwann cells are more effective at E-layer functions than astrocytes: they can actively phagocytose debris, switch to "repair phenotype" after injury, and do not form glial scars.

**Key PNS-CNS Parallels:**

- **Same iron export machinery**: Both astrocytes and Schwann cells use ferroportin + ceruloplasmin to supply iron to their associated neurons/axons (Mietto et al. 2021, J Neurosci)
- **Schwann cell ferroptosis**: Confirmed in diabetic peripheral neuropathy (GPX4/GSH down, ferrostatin-1 rescues), trigeminal neuralgia, and peripheral nerve injury
- **c-Jun as repair switch**: Schwann cells can activate repair phenotype (unlike CNS astrocytes which form scars); failure of c-Jun activation leads to senescence
- **NAD+ connection**: NAD+ depletion causes pathological Schwann cell dedifferentiation; NAD+ restoration returns cells to myelinating state

**Why PNS can regenerate (and CNS cannot):** The BBB is both protector and prison. PNS has macrophage access for debris clearance, vascular access for iron removal, and Schwann cell repair phenotype activation. CNS lacks all three behind the BBB. This predicts CNS senolytics should be combined with ferroptosis inhibitors (to manage iron released from dying senescent cells).

**The Endfoot Dual Failure Gap**: Do Schwann cells possess molecular equivalents to astrocyte AQP4/ferroportin at nodes of Ranvier? Schwann cells use AQP1 (not AQP4) and the same Fpn/Cp system, strengthening the conservation argument. See Appendix 3.3 for the complete molecular comparison.

## 10. Steelman Challenges

### 10.1 Core Challenges

#### The Glymphatic Controversy

**Challenge**: The glymphatic system itself is debated. Some researchers question whether bulk flow occurs in brain parenchyma.

**Defense**: Even if bulk glymphatic flow is overstated, the following are not disputed: (1) AQP4 polarization to endfeet is real and functionally important; (2) AQP4 KO/mislocalization impairs waste clearance; (3) Sleep-dependent clearance mechanisms exist. FELINE requires endfoot function, not specifically bulk glymphatic flow.

**Honest assessment**: If glymphatic flow is entirely artifact, FELINE's E-layer would need reframing around alternative clearance mechanisms. The endfoot dual failure concept (AQP4 + ferroportin co-loss) remains valid regardless of how clearance works, since both proteins depend on intact endfoot architecture.

#### The Globus Pallidus Question

**Challenge**: The globus pallidus has the highest iron content in the brain but is NOT the first region affected in AD. If iron is the key driver, why doesn't neurodegeneration start there?

**Defense**: FELINE predicts iron MISLOCALIZATION, not total iron, drives damage. The globus pallidus has robust iron-handling machinery (high ferritin, efficient compartmentalization). It fails last, not first. Regions with less robust iron handling (entorhinal cortex, hippocampus) fail first despite lower total iron because their defense capacity is lower relative to their iron burden.

The globus pallidus question actually SUPPORTS FELINE: it demonstrates that total iron is not the relevant variable -- defense capacity relative to iron burden is what matters.

#### GWAS Doesn't Show Iron Genes

**Challenge**: Genome-wide association studies for AD identify microglia/immunity genes (TREM2, CD33, BIN1), not iron metabolism genes. If iron is central, why no GWAS signal?

**Defense**:

1. FELINE proposes iron mislocalization from structural damage, not genetic iron overload
2. GWAS-identified genes DO connect to iron handling indirectly: TREM2 maintains lysosomal function (iron compartmentalization); APOE4 affects pericytes (NVU/endfoot integrity); BIN1 affects endosomal trafficking (iron handling)
3. Iron-handling genes may have small individual effects distributed across the E/I/L layers, falling below GWAS significance thresholds

#### Iron Chelation Trials Failed

**Challenge**: If iron is the problem, chelation should help. It didn't.

**Defense**: This is FELINE's strongest prediction, not a challenge. FELINE specifically predicted chelation would fail because:

1. The problem is mislocalization, not overload
2. Chelators remove FUNCTIONAL iron (accessible, properly compartmentalized)
3. TRAPPED iron (in lysosomes, plaques, ferritin aggregates) is inaccessible to chelators
4. Chelation worsens functional iron deficiency while leaving pathogenic iron untouched
5. FAIRPARK-II confirmed this prediction precisely

#### Limited Human Evidence for Ferroptosis

**Challenge**: Most ferroptosis evidence comes from cell culture and animal models. Direct human evidence is limited.

**Defense**: This is a legitimate concern. However:

1. Post-mortem AD brains show elevated lipid peroxidation markers (4-HNE, MDA)
2. GPX4 is reduced in AD brains
3. Iron rim lesions in MS are direct visualization of ferroptosis-related iron in humans
4. CSF ferroptosis biomarkers are being developed
5. The FAIRPARK-II result is indirect human evidence (chelation worsened outcomes, consistent with functional iron deficiency model)

#### Iron Accumulation as Epiphenomenon

**Challenge**: Iron accumulation could be a consequence, not a cause, of neurodegeneration.

**Defense**:

1. If epiphenomenon, chelation should not worsen outcomes (but FAIRPARK-II showed it does -- iron is functionally important)
2. Temporal studies show iron changes precede cognitive decline
3. Genetic variants affecting iron handling (HFE, transferrin) modify AD risk
4. Iron directly catalyzes ferroptosis chemistry -- not just correlated, mechanistically causal

#### Layer Order Critique

**Challenge**: FELINE's claim that N-layer damage precedes E-layer failure is not proven. Multiple causal orders could produce the same endpoints.

**Defense**: FELINE does not require a fixed layer order. Different diseases enter through different layers (Section 7.1). The key claim is that MULTIPLE layers must fail simultaneously, not that they fail in a specific sequence. The most common AD pathway (N -> E -> Fe/L -> I) is supported by epidemiological timing (vascular risk factors appear decades before symptoms), but alternative orderings are possible for different patient subgroups.

### 10.2 Advanced Challenges

#### The Familial AD Challenge

**Challenge**: FAD mutations in APP/PSEN1/PSEN2 cause AD through amyloid overproduction. If FELINE is correct that amyloid is protective, why do amyloid-overproducing mutations cause disease? The Icelandic A673T mutation REDUCES A-beta production by ~40% and PROTECTS against AD. APP duplications that INCREASE A-beta production CAUSE early-onset AD.

**Defense (requires nuance)**: FELINE must distinguish ACUTE vs. CHRONIC and AMOUNT vs. FORM.

**1. A-beta production does not equal A-beta plaque function**:

| Process                 | Effect                                       | Timeframe           |
| ----------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------- |
| A-beta production       | Increases labile monomers/oligomers          | Acute, continuous   |
| A-beta plaque formation | Sequesters toxic species into inert deposits | Chronic, protective |

Familial mutations increase A-beta production RATE -- this overwhelms clearance before protective plaques can form. The problem is not that plaques are toxic; production rate exceeds clearance capacity.

**2. The oligomer distinction is critical**:

FELINE does not claim all A-beta species are protective:

- A-beta monomers: Likely physiological (antimicrobial, metal binding)
- A-beta oligomers: TOXIC (disrupt synapses, seed pathology)
- A-beta fibrils/plaques: PROTECTIVE (inert sequestration of toxic species)

Familial mutations shift equilibrium toward oligomers by increasing production faster than clearance (Swedish, duplications), producing longer aggregation-prone species (PSEN1/2), or creating oligomer-stabilizing variants (Arctic, Dutch).

**3. A673T supports the nuanced model**:

A673T doesn't just reduce A-beta amount -- it specifically reduces oligomer formation (Limegrover et al. 2021):

> "A673T inhibits oligomer formation and lowers binding affinity to the synaptic receptors, limiting neuronal degradation"

A673T mechanisms: reduces BACE1 cleavage by 40%, alters cleavage site selection (shifts to beta'-site producing more labile species), reduces A-beta42 aggregation kinetics, and lowers synaptic binding affinity. A 104-year-old A673T carrier died with minimal pathology and preserved cognition (Kero et al. 2013).

**4. The Christchurch mutation provides the key**:

APOE3 Christchurch mutation (R136S): One carrier had PSEN1 E280A (usually -> AD at ~44) but remained cognitively intact until 70s despite MASSIVE amyloid burden. The Christchurch mutation reduces tau binding, proving plaques alone don't cause disease -- tau propagation is required for neurodegeneration.

**5. PSEN1/PSEN2 and lysosomal dysfunction**:

PSEN1/PSEN2 mutations impair lysosomal acidification (Lee et al. 2010 demonstrated PSEN1 is required for v-ATPase trafficking). FAD mutations may cause disease through L-layer failure rather than amyloid overproduction per se. The PANTHOS model (Nixon) provides support: plaques form "inside-out" from lysosomally compromised neurons.

**Revised FELINE position**: A-beta plaques are protective (sequestration). A-beta oligomers are toxic. Familial mutations accelerate oligomer accumulation faster than plaques can sequester them. This is the hardest challenge and requires the most nuanced defense.

#### The Mediterranean Diet Mechanism

**Challenge**: Mediterranean diet reduces AD risk. It is rich in iron (red wine, leafy greens). If iron is harmful, why does an iron-rich diet help?

**Defense**: The Mediterranean diet provides iron in a context of robust antioxidant defense (polyphenols, olive oil, omega-3s). These antioxidants support the L-layer (GPX4 substrates, membrane protection). The diet illustrates FELINE's point: iron is not inherently harmful -- it's harmful when defense layers are compromised.

#### Mouse Models Show Plaques Without Neurodegeneration

**Challenge**: Transgenic mice develop extensive amyloid plaques but minimal neurodegeneration. If plaques sequester toxic iron, mice should be protected.

**Defense**: Mouse models lack the multi-layer failure that FELINE requires for neurodegeneration. Mice have intact pericytes (N-layer), functional endfeet (E-layer), and young-animal iron handling. They develop plaques (because of transgene overexpression) but not the coordinated defense failure needed for ferroptotic neurodegeneration.

#### Sex Differences

**Challenge**: Women have higher AD risk than men. How does FELINE explain this?

**Defense**: Age-matched, men have equal or higher AD incidence in many cohorts. Women's higher lifetime prevalence largely reflects longer lifespan. The more specific question is why women's risk accelerates after menopause.

FELINE accounts for this through a phase-dependent multi-layer model:

**Pre-menopause** (women protected across 4 of 5 layers):

1. **F layer**: Menstrual iron depletion maintains lower baseline brain iron
2. **I layer**: Higher OPC proliferation rates (2x, Cerghet 2006/2009) + estrogen protects myelin
3. **N layer**: Later cerebrovascular disease onset than men
4. **E layer**: Estrogen suppresses hepcidin, preserving ferroportin-mediated iron export

**L-layer weakness** (lifelong): Women do not have "lower autophagy" but rather impaired autophagosome clearance despite adequate biogenesis (Du 2025, Guillot-Sestier 2021). Female microglia form autophagosomes normally but clear them slower. mTOR inhibitors lose efficacy in aged females (Congdon 2012).

**Post-menopause** (concurrent loss of multiple protections):

1. **F layer**: Iron accumulates rapidly (Bartzokis 2011: hysterectomy equalizes brain iron to men's levels)
2. **I layer**: OPC regeneration slows without estrogen
3. **N layer**: Cardiovascular protection lost
4. **E layer**: Hepcidin rises, ferroportin degrades, export fails
5. **L layer**: Already weak clearance further impaired by estrogen loss on lysosomal maturation

This model implies sex-divergent pathways: men may progress primarily through N-layer failure (complement-mediated; C1q deletion rescues males but not females in mice, Petrisko 2023), while women progress through post-menopausal multi-layer decline (neuroinflammation-dominant).

**Additional evidence**: Akinci et al. (2026, JAMA Network Open, N=503) found women had greater A-beta/tau burden yet thicker cortex and lower WMH volumes, consistent with women in this age range (60-69) still benefiting from residual pre-menopausal protections. See Appendix 6.4.8 for the full analysis.

### 10.3 Quantitative Challenges

#### Timeline Challenge

**Challenge**: FELINE implies a slow timeline from initial damage to clinical disease. How slow? Can specific timeframes be predicted?

**Response**: The timeline is decades (consistent with epidemiological data showing vascular risk factors at midlife predicting late-life dementia). Specific timeframes cannot be predicted because they depend on individual defense layer reserve capacity. This is a legitimate limitation -- FELINE cannot currently make precise temporal predictions.

#### The Anemia Question

**Challenge**: Anemia (low iron) is associated with increased dementia risk. This seems to contradict an iron-toxicity model.

**Defense**: This is consistent with FELINE. Anemia reduces iron available for:

1. Myelin synthesis (I-layer: OLs starved for iron)
2. Mitochondrial function (L-layer: reduced electron transport)
3. Hemoglobin (reduced brain oxygenation -> metabolic stress)
   FELINE predicts BOTH excess and insufficient iron are harmful -- the optimum is properly compartmentalized, adequate iron.

#### Hemochromatosis Modest Effect

**Challenge**: Hereditary hemochromatosis (massive systemic iron overload) shows only modestly increased dementia risk. If iron drives neurodegeneration, hemochromatosis should cause severe early dementia.

**Defense**:

1. The BBB partially protects the brain from systemic iron overload
2. Hemochromatosis iron is mostly in liver/heart, not brain
3. Brain hepcidin regulation partially compensates
4. FELINE emphasizes MISLOCALIZATION within the brain, not systemic overload
5. The modest effect IS consistent with FELINE: some brain iron increase occurs but is buffered by intact defense layers in most patients

### 10.4 Calcineurin Inhibitors: Opposing Effects

**Challenge**: Solid organ transplant recipients on calcineurin inhibitors (CNIs) like tacrolimus show dramatically REDUCED dementia incidence. This seems to contradict FELINE.

**Epidemiological Evidence**:

| Study                       | Population                                     | Finding                                                                      |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Taglialatela et al. 2015    | 2,644 kidney transplant patients on tacrolimus | Dementia prevalence 1.02% vs 10.13% in age-matched population (p<0.0001)     |
| Silva et al. 2023           | Tens of thousands (TriNetX database)           | Tacrolimus, cyclosporine, AND sirolimus all associated with reduced dementia |
| McAdams-DeMarco et al. 2017 | 40,918 older kidney transplant recipients      | CNI-FREE regimens had HIGHER dementia risk (HR 0.83 for CNI use)             |

This population SHOULD be at higher risk (diabetes, hypertension, ESRD are all AD risk factors), yet shows dramatically lower dementia.

**Standard Interpretation (A-beta-Centric)**: A-beta oligomers -> Calcineurin activation -> Pin1 dephosphorylation -> Dendritic spine loss. CNIs block this pathway.

**The Problem for FELINE**: FELINE holds A-beta is protective. If A-beta is protective, why would blocking "A-beta-induced" calcineurin activation help?

**Resolution: The Iron-Calcium Self-Feeding Cycle**

Recent literature reveals the standard interpretation has causation backwards. Iron drives calcium dysregulation, not A-beta:

Ryan et al. 2025 (Redox Biol, [DOI: 10.1016/j.redox.2025.103910](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.redox.2025.103910)) studying presenilin mutations:

> "loss of SEL-12 leads to elevated iron levels... Notably, reducing mitochondrial calcium in sel-12 mutants prevented this iron accumulation, indicating that elevated mitochondrial calcium drives increased cellular iron levels... inhibition of ferroptosis restores neuronal function"

Gleitze et al. 2021:

> "iron promotes the emergence of Ca2+ signals via activation of redox-sensitive Ca2+ channels... the iron-ferroptosis-Ca2+ association orchestrates the progression of cognitive dysfunctions"

**The Actual Causal Chain**:

```
Iron accumulation
       |
       v
Oxidative stress (mitochondrial superoxide)
       |
       +-------------------------------------> Lipid peroxidation
       |                                              |
       v                                              v
Ca2+ dysregulation <----------------------------> FERROPTOSIS
       |              (bidirectional amplification)
       v
Calcineurin activation  <---- CNIs BLOCK HERE
       |
       v
Pin1 dephosphorylation
       |
       v
Dendritic spine loss -> Cognitive decline
```

**Where does A-beta fit?**: A-beta is produced as an EMERGENCY RESPONSE to iron/oxidative stress. Researchers observing "A-beta present + calcineurin activation" concluded A-beta causes calcineurin activation. But both are PARALLEL downstream effects of iron toxicity. The correlation is real but the causation is wrong.

**FELINE-Compatible Explanation**:

CNIs interrupt the iron -> calcium -> calcineurin cascade at the calcineurin step. They're not blocking "A-beta toxicity" -- they're blocking a DOWNSTREAM CONSEQUENCE of iron toxicity.

```
FELINE VIEW OF CNI PROTECTION:

Iron accumulation -------------------------------------> Ferroptosis
       |                                                    ^
       v                                                    |
Oxidative stress ------------------------------------> Lipid peroxidation
       |                                                    ^
       v                                                    |
Ca2+ dysregulation <----------------------------------> More iron uptake
       |                    (self-feeding cycle via             |
       v                     DMT1 sensitization)                |
Calcineurin activation  <---- CNIs BLOCK HERE ------------------+
       |                      (interrupts amplification loop)
       v
Spine loss, synaptic dysfunction
```

**CNIs are palliative, not curative**: They reduce damage from the iron-calcium cascade but don't address root cause. However, they provide real protection because:

1. Calcineurin-mediated spine loss is genuine pathology
2. The calcium-iron cycle is self-amplifying -- blocking calcineurin may reduce the positive feedback
3. Synaptic preservation buys time for other compensatory mechanisms

**Testable Predictions**:

| Prediction                                                           | Rationale                                         | Test                                            |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| CNIs + ferroptosis inhibitors should be SYNERGISTIC                  | Hit both downstream amplifier AND root cause      | Preclinical combination studies                 |
| CNIs alone won't prevent pathology UPSTREAM of calcineurin           | Don't address iron accumulation                   | Iron imaging in CNI-treated patients            |
| CNI protection should be GREATER in early disease                    | Before iron accumulation overwhelms all pathways  | Stage-stratified analysis of transplant cohorts |
| A-beta levels may be UNCHANGED or ELEVATED in protected CNI patients | A-beta production driven by iron, not calcineurin | CSF A-beta in transplant recipients             |

**Updated Therapeutic Hierarchy**:

| Target                      | Mechanism                    | Priority | Notes                                        |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------- | -------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Ferroptosis inhibitors      | Address root cause           | HIGHEST  | GPX4 upregulation, lipid peroxide scavengers |
| Iron compartmentalization   | Address root cause           | HIGHEST  | Not chelation -- redirect to safe storage    |
| Calcineurin inhibitors      | Interrupt amplification loop | HIGH     | Palliative but genuinely protective          |
| Clearance enhancement       | Prevent threshold crossing   | HIGH     | Sleep, glymphatic, lysosomal function        |
| Generic anti-inflammatories | Modulate secondary response  | LOWER    | Don't address root cause                     |

This reconciliation demonstrates FELINE can explain findings that initially appear contradictory. The CNI data supports the iron-calcium connection that FELINE predicts.

