## 11. Falsification and Honest Assessment

### 11.1 What Would Refute FELINE

#### TIER 1: Core Falsifying Evidence (Framework-Killing)

| Finding                                                                               | Why It Would Kill FELINE                          | Current Status                                           |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Iron chelation works**                                                        | FELINE predicts chelation should fail/worsen      | Consistent: chelation fails (FAIRPARK-II)                |
| **BACE inhibitors help**                                                        | FELINE predicts A-beta serves protective function | Consistent: BACE inhibitors worsen                       |
| **Ferroptosis is NOT the convergent death mechanism**                           | Core claim: all paths converge on ferroptosis     | NOT YET: ferroptosis markers present in all examined NDs |
| **Endfoot damage does NOT cause coordinated loss of both AQP4 and ferroportin** | Core structural hypothesis                        | UNTESTED: the key experiment                             |
| **Oligodendrocytes are NOT preferentially vulnerable**                          | Predicts OLs die first due to iron load           | SUPPORTED: transcriptomic data shows OL changes earliest |

#### TIER 2: Strong Falsifying Evidence (Major Revision Required)

| Finding                                          | Why It's Problematic                                | Current Status                                                                          |
| ------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| A-beta-negative elderly have BETTER outcomes     | Would contradict protective A-beta hypothesis       | NOT FOUND: A-beta-negative elderly do well but this is consistent with defense capacity |
| Tau removal helps ACROSS ALL subgroups           | Would suggest tau is purely harmful, not protective | NOT FOUND: tau therapy shows subgroup effects (TOGETHER trial)                          |
| TREM2 agonists work WITHOUT lysosomal repair     | Would suggest microglial activation is sufficient   | NOT FOUND: INVOKE-2 (TREM2 agonist) failed                                              |
| Anti-amyloid therapy shows robust, broad benefit | Would contradict protective amyloid reframing       | NOT FOUND: benefit remains modest and subgroup-dependent                                |

### 11.2 Apparent Contradictions That FELINE Explains

#### Anti-Amyloid Brain Volume Loss

Anti-amyloid monoclonal antibodies (lecanemab, donanemab, aducanumab) cause accelerated brain volume loss despite successfully clearing amyloid plaques.

Alves/Ayton 2026 PLOS Medicine meta-analysis:

- Whole-brain atrophy: ~25-40% FASTER in treatment groups
- Hippocampal atrophy: accelerated in proportion to ARIA frequency
- Ventricular enlargement: greatest in patients with most amyloid removal

**FELINE explanation**: If A-beta serves as emergency iron-binding protein (I-layer function), then removing plaques = removing iron protection. A-beta plaques bind iron -> iron sequestered -> neurons protected. Anti-amyloid MABs clear plaques -> bound iron RELEASED into parenchyma -> labile iron pool increases -> ferroptosis -> VOLUME LOSS.

Status: CONFIRMATORY -- this is exactly what FELINE predicts.

#### LATE-NC: Regional Differences in L-Layer Vulnerability

LATE-NC (Limbic-predominant age-related TDP-43 encephalopathy neuropathologic change) affects ~25-40% of brains over age 85. It causes amnestic dementia clinically indistinguishable from AD, but with TDP-43 rather than tau.

**FELINE explanation**: TDP-43 proteinopathy is fundamentally L-layer disease. Regional differences reflect baseline lysosomal capacity:

- Motor neurons (ALS): Highest autophagic flux -> vulnerable to TDP-43 loss -> FAST degeneration (months)
- Limbic neurons (LATE-NC): Age-related lysosomal decline -> TDP-43 as MARKER of L-layer failure -> SLOW degeneration (years)

Why LATE + ADNC synergizes: Both pathologies = SAME L layer overwhelmed. GRN mutations cause BOTH FTD-TDP and are LATE-NC risk factors (lysosomal mechanism conserved). TMEM106B (lysosomal protein) is the strongest LATE-NC genetic risk factor.

Status: CONFIRMATORY -- LATE-NC is L-layer disease with regional vulnerability differences.

#### Cognitive Resilience

~20-30% of elderly with high AD pathology (Braak V-VI tau, CERAD frequent neuritic plaques) remain cognitively intact until death.

**FELINE explanation**: Plaques and tangles are protective RESPONSES, not pathogenic CAUSES. Resilience occurs when defense layers remain functional:

Resilient brain: Plaques present (I layer working, sequestering iron) + tangles present (tau binding iron) + HIGH OL abundance (I layer maintained) + HIGH astrocyte abundance (N layer intact) -> iron remains COMPARTMENTALIZED -> no ferroptosis.

Impaired brain with same pathology: Same plaques and tangles but LOW OL abundance (I layer failing) + LOW astrocyte abundance (N layer failing) -> compartmentalization FAILS -> ferroptosis -> dementia.

The key insight: OL and astrocyte abundance determines outcome, not pathology burden. This is exactly what FELINE predicts.

Status: CONFIRMATORY -- cognitive resilience confirms plaques/tangles are protective.

#### Sex Differences

Women have ~2x AD prevalence but the mechanism has been unclear. PNAS 2025 (14 cohorts, 4,726 participants) showed MEN have greater cortical thinning during healthy aging, deepening the puzzle.

**FELINE explanation**: Sex differences may reflect phase-dependent multi-layer vulnerability rather than L-layer biology alone:

- Women have impaired autophagosome clearance (not lower biogenesis) throughout life (Du 2025, Guillot-Sestier 2021). Female microglia form autophagosomes at normal rates but clear them slower.
- Pre-menopausal women are protected across F/I/N/E layers (menstrual iron loss, higher OPC turnover, later vascular disease, estrogen-mediated export)
- Post-menopause removes multiple protections concurrently: iron accumulates (F), OPC regeneration slows (I), vascular protection lost (N), ferroportin degrades (E), already-weak clearance worsens (L)
- APOE4 confers greater risk in women because it compounds existing L-layer clearance deficit AND accelerates post-menopausal N-layer collapse
- Rahman 2025: women with AD show negative iron-ferritin correlation in microglia (iron present but not stored in ferritin); men show positive (normal). This is consistent with sex-divergent iron-handling pathways and may represent a sex-specific F-layer biomarker.
- Higher microglial phagocytic capacity in women cannot compensate because phagocytosis handles EXTRACELLULAR debris while the pathology is INTRACELLULAR

Status: CONFIRMATORY -- sex differences reflect phase-dependent multi-layer vulnerability profiles.

#### Mixed Pathology

Most elderly brains (>75%) have MULTIPLE pathologies (AD + LATE-NC ~50%, AD + LBD ~25-50%, AD + vascular ~60-80%).

**FELINE explanation**: All pathologies converge because iron is the common denominator:

- A-beta plaques = I layer response to iron (sequestration)
- Tau tangles = I layer response to iron (binding)
- Alpha-synuclein = I layer response to iron (binding)
- TDP-43 = L layer marker (lysosomal failure)
- Vascular pathology = N layer failure (iron leaks into parenchyma)

Multiple pathologies = multiple defense responses to the SAME iron flood. More layer failures = less defense capacity = holes align faster. This explains younger onset and faster decline with mixed pathology.

Status: CONFIRMATORY -- mixed pathology is expected under FELINE.

#### Summary of Apparent Contradictions

| Phenomenon                                  | Initial Concern              | FELINE Explanation                                                                                                                                                         | Status     |
| ------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------- |
| Anti-amyloid brain atrophy                  | No mechanism for volume loss | A-beta sequesters iron; removal releases iron -> ferroptosis                                                                                                               | Consistent |
| LATE vs ALS (same TDP-43, different course) | No explanation for tropism   | Regional L-layer capacity differences                                                                                                                                      | Consistent |
| Cognitive resilience                        | High pathology, no dementia  | Plaques/tangles PROTECTIVE; OL/astrocyte abundance determines outcome                                                                                                      | Consistent |
| Sex differences                             | Women 2x AD risk             | Pre-menopausal multi-layer protection → post-menopausal concurrent loss of protections; impaired autophagosome clearance (L) + iron accumulation (F) + export failure (E) | Consistent |
| Mixed pathology                             | Multiple diseases co-occur   | All pathologies = different responses to SAME iron challenge                                                                                                               | Consistent |

