# GROUP 3: DISEASE-SPECIFIC APPLICATIONS

## Appendix 3.1: Detailed Disease-Specific FELINE Layer Analysis

### 3.1.1 ALS: Complete FELINE Layer Mapping

#### Fe (Iron) Layer in ALS

**Iron Accumulation Evidence:**

- Motor cortex iron elevated in ALS (MRI studies)
- Spinal cord iron increased in SOD1 mutant mice before symptom onset
- CSF ferritin elevated
- Motor neurons have high baseline iron (mitochondria-rich for high metabolic demand)

**Iron-specific findings:**

- Wang et al. 2022: GPX4 depletion in sporadic/familial ALS; GPX4 overexpression delays disease onset
- Wang et al. 2023: SPY1 regulates GCH1 and TFR1 in ALS motor neurons
- Yang et al. 2023: NRF2 activation suppresses motor neuron ferroptosis

#### L (Lysosome) Layer in ALS

**Autophagy dysfunction is central to ALS:**

- TDP-43 aggregation impairs autophagy (TDP-43 normally regulates autophagy genes)
- C9orf72 repeat expansions disrupt autophagy initiation
- SOD1 mutations increase oxidative stress and impair mitophagy
- FUS mutations impair stress granule dynamics and autophagy

**Specific L-layer evidence:**

- Autophagosome accumulation in motor neurons
- p62/SQSTM1 inclusions in ALS spinal cord
- LC3-II to LC3-I ratio abnormal
- TFEB nuclear translocation impaired

#### I (Insulation) Layer in ALS

**Motor neuron-specific vulnerability:**

- Extremely long axons (up to 1 meter in humans)
- Highest metabolic demand of any neuron type
- High iron content for mitochondria along entire axon length
- Limited regenerative capacity in CNS
- Large soma = large surface area for iron-mediated damage

**Oligodendrocyte involvement:**

- Gray matter OLs show early changes in ALS
- MCT1 (lactate transporter) reduced in OLs -> metabolic stress on motor neurons
- OL-motor neuron metabolic coupling disrupted

#### N (Neurovascular) Layer in ALS

**Blood-spinal cord barrier (BSCB) breakdown is well-documented:**

- Winkler et al. 2013: 54% pericyte reduction in ALS spinal cord BEFORE motor neuron loss
- Erythrocyte extravasation in 11/11 ALS patients vs 0/5 controls
- IgG extravasation indicating BSCB breakdown
- Tight junction protein loss

**HERV-K mechanism:**

- HERV-K env protein is directly toxic to motor neurons
- Li et al. 2015: Transgenic HERV-K mice develop motor neuron disease
- TDP-43 normally suppresses retrotransposon expression; its loss reactivates HERV-K
- HERV-K may directly damage BSCB

#### E (Export) Layer in ALS

**Glymphatic dysfunction documented early:**

- Liu et al. 2024 (Brain): DTI-ALPS index significantly lower in early-stage ALS vs controls
- Zamani et al. 2022: DCE-MRI shows glymphatic impairment before motor symptoms in TDP-43 mice
- CSF dynamics altered; TDP-43 in CSF elevated
- Possible role in disease spread via CSF (prion-like propagation)

#### ALS FELINE Summary

| Layer        | Primary/Secondary | Key Finding                          | Therapeutic Target     |
| ------------ | ----------------- | ------------------------------------ | ---------------------- |
| **Fe** | Secondary         | Iron elevated in motor cortex        | Ferroptosis inhibitors |
| **L**  | PRIMARY           | TDP-43/C9orf72 impair autophagy      | Autophagy enhancers    |
| **I**  | Secondary         | Motor neuron metabolic vulnerability | MCT1/lactate support   |
| **N**  | Affected          | 54% pericyte reduction pre-symptoms  | Pericyte protection    |
| **E**  | Early             | Glymphatic impaired at Stage 1       | Sleep optimization     |

### 3.1.2 Huntington's Disease: Complete FELINE Layer Mapping

#### Fe (Iron) Layer in HD

**Striatal iron accumulation:**

- Striatum has highest iron content of any brain region
- CAG repeat length correlates with iron accumulation in caudate/putamen
- Iron binds mutant huntingtin (mHtt) via polyQ tract and adjacent regions
- Copper-mHtt interaction disrupts ceruloplasmin function

**Specific findings:**

- Mi et al. 2019: Comprehensive review of ferroptosis in HD
- Bowman et al. 2022: CSF copper, manganese, zinc elevated BEFORE clinical markers

#### L (Lysosome) Layer in HD

**Autophagy is initially increased, then fails:**

- Early HD: Compensatory autophagy upregulation
- Progressive HD: Autophagy capacity overwhelmed
- mHtt aggregates impair cargo recognition
- Sequestration of autophagy machinery into aggregates

**Lysosomal dysfunction:**

- mHtt directly impairs lysosomal membrane integrity
- Cathepsin activity reduced in HD models
- TFEB nuclear translocation impaired

#### I (Insulation) Layer in HD

**Medium spiny neuron vulnerability:**

- High dopamine receptor density -> dopamine metabolism generates ROS
- High striatal GABA (requires iron-dependent synthesis)
- Limited antioxidant capacity compared to cortical neurons
- Extensive dendritic arborization = large membrane surface for lipid peroxidation

**OL involvement:**

- White matter changes in premanifest HD
- OL differentiation impaired in HD models
- Myelin abnormalities documented

#### N (Neurovascular) Layer in HD

**BBB disruption occurs early:**

- Di Pardo et al. 2017: BBB disruption BEFORE overt symptoms in R6/2 mice
- Tight junction derangement precedes disease onset
- mHtt aggregates in ALL NVU components (Drouin-Ouellet 2015)

**WNT-mediated mechanism:**

- Lim et al. 2017: WNT signaling dysregulated in HD iBMECs
- WNT maintains BBB integrity
- mHtt disrupts WNT -> BBB breakdown -> N-layer damage

#### E (Export) Layer in HD

**Glymphatic impairment confirmed:**

- 2024 studies show perivascular AQP4 localization reduced
- CSF clearance deficits
- mHtt may physically impair waste clearance

**Copper sequestration impairs iron export:**

- mHtt sequesters copper
- Copper is required for ceruloplasmin function
- Ceruloplasmin is required for ferroportin activity
- Copper sequestration -> impaired iron export (indirect E-layer damage)

#### HD FELINE Summary

| Layer        | Primary/Secondary | Key Finding                             | Therapeutic Target                        |
| ------------ | ----------------- | --------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **Fe** | Central           | Iron + copper accumulation              | Copper chelation + ferroptosis inhibitors |
| **L**  | PRIMARY           | mHtt overwhelms autophagy               | Autophagy enhancers                       |
| **I**  | Secondary         | MSN vulnerability, OL changes           | Antioxidants                              |
| **N**  | Early             | BBB disruption pre-symptoms             | WNT pathway                               |
| **E**  | Affected          | Glymphatic impaired, Cu->Cp dysfunction | Copper restoration                        |

### 3.1.3 Prion Diseases: Complete FELINE Layer Mapping

#### Fe (Iron) Layer in Prion Disease

**Iron is central to prion pathogenesis:**

- Singh et al. 2009: Increased total and redox-active Fe(II) in prion disease
- PrPC has iron-binding function (normal prion protein handles iron)
- PrPSc loses iron-handling function while accumulating iron
- Iron INDUCES PrPC->PrPSc conversion

**Specific findings:**

- Bhattacharjee et al. 2025: Prion-induced ferroptosis facilitated by RAC3
- Kawahara et al. 2021: PrPC essential for synaptic metal homeostasis

#### L (Lysosome) Layer in Prion Disease

**Lysosomes are directly overwhelmed:**

- PrPSc cannot be degraded by normal lysosomal mechanisms
- Self-templating amplification overwhelms clearance
- Lysosomal accumulation of PrPSc documented
- Eventually leads to LMP

**The degradation problem:**

- PrPSc is resistant to proteases
- Normal cellular quality control cannot handle misfolded prion
- Creates progressive lysosomal overload

#### I (Insulation) Layer in Prion Disease

**PrPC loss of function:**

- Normal PrPC binds 4-5 copper ions and participates in iron homeostasis
- Conversion to PrPSc removes this protective function
- Iron that was bound by PrPC becomes labile
- "Aggregation as iron buffer" model doesn't apply - PrPSc is genuinely toxic

**Neuronal vulnerability:**

- Rapid neuronal loss in prion disease
- Spongiosis reflects massive cell death
- Astrogliosis is secondary response

#### N (Neurovascular) Layer in Prion Disease

**BBB changes documented:**

- Increased permeability in prion disease
- Boland et al. 2023: Prion-infected astrocytes induce endothelial disease phenotype
- IL-6 mediates astrocyte-endothelial damage
- Endfoot retraction documented

**Astrocyte-specific dysfunction:**

- Reactive astrocytes associated with prion disease impair BBB
- Extracellular vesicles from normal astrocytes can REVERSE damage

#### E (Export) Layer in Prion Disease

**Export is directly targeted:**

- PrPSc triggers hepcidin upregulation
- Hepcidin degrades ferroportin
- Iron trapping is a direct consequence of E-layer blockade

**Glymphatic involvement:**

- Song et al. 2021: AQP4 upregulated in prion-infected brains (may be compensatory)
- Dexmedetomidine/clonidine clear PrPSc and delay incubation period (glymphatic enhancement)
- CSF spread of PrPSc contributes to disease propagation

#### Prion FELINE Summary

| Layer        | Primary/Secondary | Key Finding                       | Therapeutic Target             |
| ------------ | ----------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **Fe** | Central           | Iron INDUCES conversion           | Prevent iron-prion interaction |
| **L**  | Overwhelmed       | Cannot degrade PrPSc              | Novel degradation pathways     |
| **I**  | Loss of function  | PrPC iron-binding lost            | Not applicable                 |
| **N**  | Damaged           | Astrocyte-mediated BBB damage     | Astrocyte-targeted therapy     |
| **E**  | PRIMARY           | Hepcidin->ferroportin degradation | Hepcidin antagonists           |

### 3.1.4 Progressive Supranuclear Palsy: Complete FELINE Layer Mapping

#### Fe (Iron) Layer in PSP

**Iron accumulation in multiple brain regions:**

- Autopsy: Iron elevated in all 5 examined brain regions
- Prussian blue staining positive
- Iron along myelinated fibers (suggesting OL involvement)

#### L (Lysosome) Layer in PSP

**Secondary to tau aggregation:**

- Tau aggregation in PSP is primarily 4R tau
- Lysosomal burden from tau clearance
- But L-layer is not the primary entry point

#### I (Insulation) Layer in PSP

**PRIMARY entry point:**

- Oligodendroglial coiled bodies (tau in OLs)
- Tau in astrocytes (tufted astrocytes - characteristic of PSP)
- White matter spreading pattern
- Glial tau predominates over neuronal tau

**I-layer mechanism:**

- Astrocyte tau disrupts iron buffering function
- OL tau disrupts myelin maintenance
- Tau accumulation is PROTECTIVE RESPONSE to iron stress in glia

#### N (Neurovascular) Layer in PSP

**Secondary involvement:**

- Brainstem vasculature affected
- Not considered primary entry
- Midbrain/brainstem specific vulnerability

#### E (Export) Layer in PSP

**Less characterized but likely impaired:**

- Glymphatic studies in PSP limited
- Brainstem location may have different clearance dynamics

#### PSP FELINE Summary

| Layer        | Primary/Secondary | Key Finding                                     | Therapeutic Target     |
| ------------ | ----------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| **Fe** | Central           | Iron in all regions                             | Ferroptosis inhibitors |
| **L**  | Secondary         | Tau clearance burden                            | Not primary            |
| **I**  | PRIMARY           | Glial tau (OL coiled bodies, tufted astrocytes) | Tau-targeting in glia  |
| **N**  | Secondary         | Brainstem vasculature                           | Not primary            |
| **E**  | Unknown           | Not well characterized                          | Needs study            |

### 3.1.5 Multiple Sclerosis: Complete FELINE Layer Mapping

#### Fe (Iron) Layer in MS

**Paramagnetic rim lesions (PRLs) are the smoking gun:**

- Iron visible on 7T MRI as paramagnetic rim around chronic active lesions
- Iron trapped in activated microglia/macrophages at lesion edge
- PRLs predict worse outcomes (expansion, progression)
- PRLs count may predict treatment response

**Specific findings:**

- Haider et al. 2014: Comprehensive iron-inflammation-degeneration relationship
- Iron released from dying OLs cannot be cleared
- Chronic active lesion edge is site of ongoing ferroptosis

#### L (Lysosome) Layer in MS

**Secondary to I-layer damage:**

- LANDO (LC3-associated endocytosis) implicated
- Lysosomal function in microglia affects debris handling
- Not the primary entry point

#### I (Insulation) Layer in MS

**PRIMARY entry point (autoimmune OL destruction):**

- Autoimmune attack targets OL myelin
- OL death releases massive iron load
- Iron that was bound in myelin becomes labile
- Schwann cells (PNS) are spared by autoimmune attack (explains CNS specificity)

**Ferroptosis in OLs confirmed:**

- Jhelum et al. 2020: Ferroptosis mediates cuprizone-induced OL loss
- GPX4 reduction in MS OLs documented
- Fischer et al. 2025: DMF/DRF work via anti-ferroptotic mechanisms in OLs

#### N (Neurovascular) Layer in MS

**BBB breakdown during relapses:**

- Acute MS lesions show BBB breach
- Gadolinium enhancement = BBB breakdown
- Immune cell infiltration requires BBB disruption
- Recovery involves BBB repair

**But N-layer is secondary to I-layer:**

- The autoimmune attack enters via BBB but TARGETS myelin
- N-layer damage is means to end (reaching OLs)

#### E (Export) Layer in MS

**Iron trapped in lesions:**

- PRLs represent E-layer failure at lesion level
- Iron cannot be exported from chronic active lesion edges
- Compartmentalized export failure

**Glymphatic involvement:**

- Impaired during active disease
- May contribute to diffuse brain atrophy
- Sleep disruption common in MS -> may worsen E-layer

#### MS FELINE Summary

| Layer        | Primary/Secondary | Key Finding                  | Therapeutic Target      |
| ------------ | ----------------- | ---------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| **Fe** | Central           | PRLs visible on MRI          | Anti-ferroptotic agents |
| **L**  | Secondary         | LANDO involvement            | Not primary             |
| **I**  | PRIMARY           | Autoimmune OL destruction    | Remyelination therapies |
| **N**  | Means to end      | BBB breach for immune access | Anti-inflammatory DMTs  |
| **E**  | Compartmentalized | Iron trapped in PRLs         | PRL-targeted therapy    |

