## Appendix 3.5: The Cancer-AD Inverse Relationship

### 3.5.1 The Epidemiological Puzzle

Robust epidemiological finding:

- AD patients are ~47% less likely to develop cancer (RR 0.53)
- Cancer patients are ~39% less likely to develop AD (RR 0.61)
- Mendelian randomization supports causality, not just survival bias

### 3.5.2 Competing Hypotheses

| Hypothesis        | Mechanism                                                       | Key Molecule     |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------- |
| Pin1              | Overexpressed in cancer, downregulated in AD                    | Pin1             |
| p53               | Inactivated in cancer (survival), upregulated in AD (apoptosis) | p53              |
| Wnt signaling     | Opposite directions in both diseases                            | Wnt/beta-catenin |
| Immune checkpoint | Different immune regulation                                     | PD-1/PD-L1       |

### 3.5.3 FELINE Integration: Convergence on Ferroptosis

**Critical finding:** p53 DIRECTLY REGULATES FERROPTOSIS via SLC7A11 suppression:

- p53 elevated leads to SLC7A11 decreased leads to GSH decreased leads to ferroptosis

Cancer cells systematically RESIST ferroptosis:

- Elevated TfR1 (iron uptake)
- Reduced ferroportin (iron retention)
- Elevated GPX4, NRF2, FSP1 (ferroptosis defense)

Neurons systematically SUCCUMB to ferroptosis:

- High PUFA content (substrate)
- High iron content (catalyst)
- Limited regenerative capacity

### 3.5.4 FELINE Value-Add

FELINE doesn't compete with upstream explanations (Pin1, p53, Wnt). It shows:

1. WHY they matter (they all affect ferroptosis sensitivity)
2. WHERE they converge (iron-mediated cell death)
3. WHAT to target (ferroptosis machinery)

**Prediction:** Cancer patients should have lower CSF free iron (cells effectively sequester iron away from labile pool).

### 3.5.5 Testable Predictions

| Prediction                                        | Test                                                      |
| ------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| Ferroptosis-sensitive cancers have lowest AD risk | Compare melanoma (ferroptosis-sensitive) to breast cancer |
| GPX4 SNPs protect against both conditions         | GWAS meta-analysis                                        |
| NRF2 activators benefit both                      | Clinical trials                                           |
| CSF free iron lower in cancer patients            | Measurement study                                         |

