# GROUP 4: VIRAL AND MICROBIAL MECHANISMS

## Appendix 4.1: The Fragment Clearance Model (Viral Hypothesis Refinement)

FELINE proposes a critical refinement to the viral hypothesis of AD: viruses don't need to reactivate; persistent fragments that fail to clear are sufficient.

### 4.1.1 The Core Claim

> "The virus doesn't need to reactivate. It doesn't even need to BE there. Just FRAGMENTS that fail to clear."

```
CLEARANCE FAILURE MODEL (Pure L Layer Prediction)

Past infection (decades ago)
         |
         v
Viral fragments remain (gM proteins, LAT miRNAs, etc.)
         |
         v
Young/healthy: L layer clears them --> no problem
         |
         v
Aging/APOE4/stress: L layer degrades
         |
         v
Fragments accumulate (not virus - just debris)
         |
         v
Fragments still bioactive:
  - gM fragments block autophagy (L layer sabotage)
  - LAT miRNA fragments suppress tau/alpha-syn (I layer sabotage)
         |
         v
Loss of iron-sequestering capacity + lysosomal iron release
         |
         v
Iron maldistribution --> FERROPTOSIS
```

### 4.1.2 Why This Matters

The field spent 30 years looking for viral REACTIVATION in AD brains and largely failed. FELINE says they were looking for the wrong thing:

- The virus doesn't need to "wake up"
- It doesn't even need to BE there anymore
- Just fragments that the L layer fails to clear
- Those fragments continue sabotaging defenses

### 4.1.3 Fragment Model Predictions (All Testable)

| Prediction                                        | Test                                                | Falsifying Result                                     |
| ------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| No active virus required                          | PCR for lytic genes in AD brains                    | Widespread lytic gene expression found                |
| Viral FRAGMENTS present                           | Immunostaining for gM, LAT products in lysosomes    | Fragments absent in AD tissue                         |
| Fragment load proportional to L layer dysfunction | Correlate fragment burden with cathepsin D activity | No correlation                                        |
| Fragment load proportional to iron markers        | Correlate fragments with ferritin/iron imaging      | No correlation                                        |
| APOE4 = higher fragment persistence               | Compare fragment load E4 vs E3                      | No genotype difference                                |
| Improving clearance helps WITHOUT antivirals      | Lysosomal acidification therapy (e.g., C381) alone  | No benefit unless combined with antivirals            |
| Acyclovir has LIMITED efficacy                    | Antiviral trials in AD                              | Strong benefit (would suggest reactivation IS needed) |

### 4.1.4 Supporting Precedents

**HIV-1 Vpr protein model** (Thangaraj et al. 2021, Autophagy): Vpr protein circulates in blood of ART-treated patients with UNDETECTABLE viral load, impairs lysosomal clearance, causes alpha-synuclein to ACCUMULATE IN LYSOSOMES. No active viral replication needed. This is EXACTLY the fragment model mechanism.

**HHV-6A/HHV-7 elevated in AD** (Readhead et al. 2018, Neuron): Multi-omic analysis found increased HHV-6A and HHV-7 in AD brains, with regulatory relationships to APP metabolism genes. Multiple herpesviruses may contribute fragments.

**HHV-7 U21 routes proteins to lysosomes** (Dirck et al. 2019, Mol Biol Cell): HHV-7 glycoprotein U21 binds class I MHC and reroutes it TO LYSOSOMES. Herpesvirus proteins actively manipulate lysosomal trafficking.

### 4.1.5 Multiple Herpesviruses, Cumulative Fragment Burden

| Virus  | Seroprevalence | Latency Site        | Potential Fragment Contribution    |
| ------ | -------------- | ------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| HSV-1  | 50-80%         | Trigeminal ganglia  | gB, gM, LAT miRNAs                 |
| HSV-2  | 10-20%         | Sacral ganglia      | Similar to HSV-1                   |
| VZV    | >95%           | Dorsal root ganglia | gM (autophagy blocker), others     |
| EBV    | >90%           | B cells             | EBNA proteins, LMP1                |
| CMV    | 50-80%         | Myeloid cells       | Multiple immunomodulatory proteins |
| HHV-6A | >90%           | CNS (unique!)       | Integrates into telomeres; U21     |
| HHV-7  | >85%           | T cells             | U21 (routes MHC to lysosomes)      |

**FELINE prediction:** Total herpesvirus fragment burden (summed across all species) should correlate with AD risk better than any single virus.

**This explains conflicting literature:** Studies focusing on single viruses (HSV-1 alone) show inconsistent results. Multi-virus burden studies (like Readhead) show stronger associations.

### 4.1.6 The VALAD Trial Failure Confirms the Fragment Model

The VALAD trial (December 2025) tested valacyclovir in early AD/MCI, all HSV-seropositive:

- Valacyclovir group showed GREATER cognitive worsening
- No effect on amyloid or tau PET
- No effect on plasma p-tau217

**Why this was predicted to fail:**

Acyclovir ONLY works during active viral replication:

- Requires viral thymidine kinase (TK) for activation
- Cannot affect viral proteins that already exist
- Cannot clear viral fragments accumulated over decades
- Cannot restore lysosomal function damaged by past infections

| Model                        | Prediction                                              | VALAD Result           | Status    |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- | --------- |
| **Reactivation Model** | Blocking new virus production should help               | FAILED: worse outcomes | REFUTED   |
| **Fragment Model**     | Antivirals alone can't help (fragments already present) | Consistent             | SUPPORTED |

### 4.1.7 The APOE4 Dependency Resolution

**The epidemiological puzzle:**

- HSV-1 seroprevalence in elderly: 60-80%
- AD prevalence in elderly: ~10%
- If HSV-1 causes AD, why don't most infected people develop it?

**Answer: APOE4 requirement for L layer vulnerability**

| Study       | Finding                                               | Implication        |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------------------------- | ------------------ |
| Linard 2020 | APOE4+ with high HSV-1 IgG: aHR = 3.28 for AD         | Strong association |
| Linard 2020 | APOE4- with high HSV-1 IgG: HR 1.18 (non-significant) | NO association     |

**FELINE interpretation:**

- APOE4 carriers have baseline lysosomal dysfunction (known APOE4 effect)
- Fragments accumulate in EVERYONE with herpesvirus infections
- Only APOE4 carriers accumulate fragments to pathological threshold
- HSV-1 + APOE4 = fragment accumulation in vulnerable L layer = AD
- HSV-1 + APOE3 = fragment accumulation in competent L layer = clearance

### 4.1.8 FELINE-Unique Therapeutic Prediction

The fragment model makes a specific, testable, untested prediction:

| Intervention                                | Alone                                          | Combined           |
| ------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ------------------ |
| Antivirals (valacyclovir)                   | Prevents NEW fragments; cannot clear existing  | Part 1             |
| Lysosomal enhancers (C381, TFEB activators) | Clears existing fragments; doesn't prevent new | Part 2             |
| **COMBINATION**                       | Should be**synergistic**                 | **UNTESTED** |

**Proposed study design:**

```
                    PREVENTION ARM                     TREATMENT ARM
                    (MCI, high HSV titers)            (Early AD, HSV+)

Arm 1:  Valacyclovir only                    Valacyclovir only
Arm 2:  Lysosomal enhancer only              Lysosomal enhancer only
Arm 3:  COMBINATION                          COMBINATION
Arm 4:  Placebo                              Placebo

FELINE PREDICTION:
- Prevention: Arm 3 >> Arm 1 > Arm 2 > Arm 4
- Treatment: Arm 3 > Arm 2 >> Arm 1 approximately equals Arm 4
```

