# GROUP 6: THERAPEUTICS

## Appendix 6.1: Therapeutic Synthesis

This appendix integrates FELINE's therapeutic implications into a coherent framework.

### 6.1.1 Why Single Targets Fail

| Single Target         | Why It Fails          | FELINE Explanation                             |
| --------------------- | --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Anti-amyloid (remove) | Modest benefit + ARIA | Removes protective iron sequestration system   |
| BACE inhibitors       | Worsened cognition    | Blocks protective A-beta production            |
| Anti-tau              | Stage-dependent       | Tau buffers iron; removing it harms late-stage |
| Iron chelation        | Worsened outcomes     | Removes functional iron, leaves trapped iron   |
| Anti-inflammatory     | Failed                | Inflammation is downstream of ferroptosis      |
| TREM2 agonist         | Failed                | Can't clear without functional lysosomes       |

### 6.1.2 Layer-Specific Interventions

| Layer        | Target                    | Therapeutic Approach                                          | Status                     |
| ------------ | ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| **Fe** | Iron compartmentalization | NOT chelation; redistribution                                 | Conceptual                 |
| **L**  | Lysosomal function        | NAD+ precursors (P7C3-A20), TFEB activators, trehalose        | Preclinical/Early clinical |
| **I**  | Insulation/myelin         | OL protection, CBD (ferroportin stabilization), remyelination | Preclinical                |
| **N**  | Neurovascular             | Vascular risk reduction, pericyte protection, CypA inhibitors | Epidemiological support    |
| **E**  | Export                    | Sleep optimization, exercise, glymphatic enhancement          | Lifestyle                  |

### 6.1.3 Combination Therapy Rationale

FELINE predicts that effective therapy requires addressing multiple layers:

**Tier 1 (Foundation):**

- Ferroptosis inhibitors (block final common pathway)
- Lysosomal acidification therapy (restore L layer)

**Tier 2 (Layer-Specific):**

- Based on patient's primary failing layer
- Biomarker-guided selection

**Tier 3 (Optimization):**

- Lifestyle factors (sleep, exercise)
- Vascular risk management

### 6.1.4 Stage-Dependent Predictions

| Stage                        | Primary Goal                  | Approach                                    |
| ---------------------------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| **Prevention**         | Maintain layer integrity      | Lifestyle, vaccination (VZV), vascular risk |
| **Early MCI**          | Restore failing layer(s)      | Targeted intervention based on biomarkers   |
| **Mild AD**            | Multiple layers compromised   | Combination therapy                         |
| **Moderate-Severe AD** | Symptomatic + neuroprotection | Ferroptosis inhibitors + symptomatic        |

### 6.1.4a Sex-Stratified Therapeutic Predictions

If men and women follow partially distinct mechanistic pathways (see Appendix 5.5.12), sex-stratified trial design may be important for detecting subgroup-specific effects.

| Strategy                                  | Predicted Sex Difference | Rationale                                                                                                                                                                        |
| ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Immune modulators (vaccines, anti-CD20)   | Stronger in women        | Women's neuroinflammation-dominant pathway; HZ vaccination causally reduces dementia risk with stronger effect in women, p=0.018 (Eyting 2024, Nature, regression discontinuity) |
| Complement inhibitors (anti-C1q)          | Stronger in men          | C1q deletion rescues males not females (Petrisko 2023); men's primary pathway is N→complement                                                                                   |
| Autophagy inducers (rapamycin, trehalose) | Stronger in men          | mTOR inhibitors lose efficacy in aged females (Congdon 2012); women's clearance bottleneck limits response                                                                       |
| Iron chelation/redistribution             | Earlier window in women  | Post-menopausal iron surge creates time-limited intervention window (ages ~55-70)                                                                                                |
| Ferroptosis inhibitors                    | Sex-neutral              | Final common pathway regardless of upstream sex differences                                                                                                                      |
| Vascular/NVU interventions                | Stronger in men          | Men's primary pathway is N-layer → complement-mediated                                                                                                                          |
| Estrogen replacement (early)              | Women only               | Maintains F/I/N/E protections; timing-critical (must start peri-menopausally)                                                                                                    |

**Note:** If these pathway differences are real, failure to stratify by sex and menopausal status could contribute to null results in trials where a subgroup-specific effect exists.

### 6.1.5 Specific Drug Predictions

| Drug/Approach                            | FELINE Prediction                                                     | Confidence      |
| ---------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------- |
| P7C3-A20 (NAD+/NAMPT)                    | Should show benefit in early AD                                       | HIGH            |
| Ferroptosis inhibitors                   | Should show benefit across diseases                                   | HIGH            |
| Lysosomal acidification agents           | Should enhance anti-amyloid response                                  | MODERATE        |
| CBD/cannabinoids                         | May protect via ferroportin stabilization                             | MODERATE        |
| Anti-CD20 + ferroptosis inhibitor        | Better than anti-CD20 alone in progressive MS                         | HIGH            |
| Iron chelation                           | Should HARM without targeted delivery                                 | HIGH (observed) |
| BACE inhibitors                          | Should HARM (observed)                                                | HIGH (observed) |
| **Theracurmin** (curcumin, 368 Da) | Modest benefit; best in high baseline brain iron + APOE4              | MODERATE        |
| **Apo-Lactoferrin** (80 kDa)       | Should outperform small-molecule chelators; extracellular selectivity | HIGH            |
| Intranasal apo-lactoferrin               | Better than oral (bypasses gut iron pickup)                           | HIGH            |

### 6.1.6 The Iron Redistribution Gap

**Critical unmet need:** No approved therapy addresses iron REDISTRIBUTION.

Current approaches:

- Chelation: Removes all iron (harmful)
- Supplementation: Adds more iron (potentially harmful)

What's needed:

- Ferroportin activators (restore export)
- Ceruloplasmin support (restore iron oxidation for export)
- Hepcidin antagonists (prevent ferroportin degradation)
- Targeted iron delivery (bypass blocked pathways)

**This represents a major therapeutic opportunity if FELINE is correct.**

### 6.1.7 Size-Selective Iron Targeting (Biological Chelation)

FELINE generates a unique, testable prediction: **therapeutic success of iron-targeting interventions depends critically on molecular size**, because size determines which compartments a molecule can access.

| Property                    | Deferiprone (139 Da)             | Theracurmin (368 Da)                  | Apo-Lactoferrin (80 kDa)                              |
| --------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| BBB Penetration             | Passive diffusion (uncontrolled) | Limited passive                       | Receptor-mediated (LfR)                               |
| Cell Membrane               | Freely permeant to all           | Lipophilic; partitions into membranes | Cannot cross without receptor                         |
| Iron Selectivity            | None (chelates all Fe)           | Preferential Fe2+/Cu2+ at membranes   | 300x higher affinity than Tf; retains Fe at acidic pH |
| **FELINE Prediction** | **HARMFUL**                | **MODEST BENEFIT**              | **BEST ALIGNED**                                |
| **Clinical Evidence** | FAIRPARK-II: worsened            | Small 2018: modest benefit            | Mohamed 2019: pilot positive                          |

**Key insights:**

- **Deferiprone** (139 Da): Strips iron from ALL compartments including mitochondria and OLs; worsens functional iron deficiency
- **Theracurmin** (368 Da): Lipophilic partitioning targets membrane interface where ferroptosis executes; multi-pillar engagement (F, E, L, I layers); 27x higher bioavailability than standard curcumin
- **Apo-Lactoferrin** (80 kDa): Cannot enter cells without receptor; operates exclusively in extracellular space where pathological iron accumulates; 300x higher affinity than transferrin; retains iron binding at acidic inflammatory pH

**Optimal combination (predicted):** Apo-lactoferrin (extracellular) + Theracurmin (membrane) + ferroptosis inhibitor (intracellular). Exclude deferiprone.

> See **Appendix 6.5** for full analysis of size-dependent iron compartmentalization therapeutics.

