## Appendix 6.5: Size-Dependent Iron Compartmentalization Therapeutics

*Added v3.1 (2026-02-05). Content from FELINE_Size_Selectivity_Therapeutic_Predictions.docx. Citations verified 2026-02-05.*

### 6.5.1 Overview: Why Molecular Size Determines Therapeutic Success

FELINE's central claim distinguishes it from all other AD models: the pathological problem is not iron *excess* but iron *maldistribution* between compartments. Iron is simultaneously trapped in the wrong places (reactive microglia, endothelial cells, plaque cores) and deficient in the right places (oligodendrocytes for myelination, mitochondria for respiration).

This analysis demonstrates that FELINE generates a unique, testable, and clinically actionable prediction: **therapeutic success of iron-targeting interventions depends critically on molecular size**, because size determines which subcellular compartments a molecule can access — and therefore whether it corrects or worsens iron maldistribution.

### 6.5.2 The Size-Selectivity Principle

A molecule that penetrates all compartments indiscriminately will strip iron from both pathological and essential pools. A molecule restricted to specific compartments can selectively target pathological iron while leaving essential pools intact.

**Counterintuitive prediction**: For iron maldistribution diseases, larger molecules should outperform smaller ones. Standard pharmaceutical development optimizes for the opposite (maximal tissue penetration), which is precisely wrong for compartmentalization disorders.

### 6.5.3 Three Compounds, Three Sizes, Three Predicted Fates

| Property                    | Deferiprone                      | Curcumin/Theracurmin                  | Apo-Lactoferrin                                        |
| --------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Molecular Weight**  | 139 Da                           | 368 Da                                | ~80,000 Da                                             |
| **Relative Size**     | Smaller than glucose             | 2.5× deferiprone                     | 575× deferiprone                                      |
| **BBB Penetration**   | Passive diffusion (uncontrolled) | Limited passive                       | Receptor-mediated (LfR)                                |
| **Cell Membrane**     | Freely permeant to all           | Lipophilic; partitions into membranes | Cannot cross without receptor                          |
| **Iron Selectivity**  | None — chelates all Fe          | Preferential Fe²⁺/Cu²⁺            | 300× higher affinity than Tf; retains Fe at acidic pH |
| **FELINE Prediction** | **HARMFUL**                | **MODEST BENEFIT**              | **BEST ALIGNED**                                 |
| **Clinical Evidence** | FAIRPARK-II: worsened outcomes   | Small 2018: modest benefit            | Mohamed 2019: pilot positive                           |

### 6.5.4 Deferiprone (139 Da): The Sledgehammer

At 139 Da, deferiprone crosses the BBB by passive diffusion, penetrates all cell membranes freely, enters mitochondria, permeates lysosomes — reaches every subcellular compartment. This ubiquitous access is why it fails.

**FAIRPARK-II** (Devos et al. 2022, NEJM): 372 patients, deferiprone 30 mg/kg/day for 36 weeks. Despite confirmed brain iron reduction on QSM-MRI, motor symptoms **worsened significantly** (UPDRS-III +3.28 points). Trial stopped early for futility.

**FELINE explanation**: Indiscriminate chelation starves iron-dependent cells (oligodendrocytes, mitochondria) while failing to address compartmentalization failure.

**FELINE verdict**: Deferiprone will fail in AD for the same reasons. It depletes iron from oligodendrocytes (worsening demyelination), mitochondria (compromising energy), and GPX4 system (worsening ferroptosis vulnerability).

### 6.5.5 Curcumin/Theracurmin (368 Da): The Multi-Tool

At 368 Da with high lipophilicity, curcumin partitions preferentially into lipid bilayers — precisely where ferroptosis executes. This creates passive targeting at the membrane interface where iron-mediated damage is most lethal.

**Multi-pillar engagement**:

| FELINE Layer    | Mechanism                                                                                 |
| --------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| F (Ferroptosis) | Fe²⁺ chelation at membranes; Nrf2/ARE activation                                        |
| E (Export)      | Hepcidin suppression → ferroportin preservation (Jiao 2009: 65% hepcidin mRNA reduction) |
| L (Lysosomal)   | Autophagy enhancement                                                                     |
| I (Insulation)  | NF-κB suppression; microglial modulation                                                 |

**The bioavailability problem**: Standard curcumin achieves only 60-270 nM plasma (far below 1-20 μM needed for iron chelation). Theracurmin® achieves ~27× higher bioavailability. Small et al. (2018) showed Theracurmin 90 mg BID for 18 months improved memory + reduced FDDNP-PET binding.

**FELINE verdict**: Modest benefit likely, but insufficient for substantial iron redistribution. Works best in patients with high baseline brain iron (QSM-MRI) and APOE ε4.

### 6.5.6 Apo-Lactoferrin (80,000 Da): The Biological Scalpel

At ~80,000 Da, lactoferrin **cannot** cross cell membranes by passive diffusion. This is its greatest therapeutic advantage.

**Compartmental restriction**: Operates exclusively in extracellular space and at membrane surfaces unless actively internalized via LfR, LRP1. In FELINE, extracellular iron is precisely the pathological species: iron from dying cells, iron spilling from damaged ferritin, iron at compromised BBB. Lactoferrin literally cannot reach the iron cells need inside their own cytoplasm/mitochondria.

**pH-dependent retention**: Transferrin releases iron at acidic pH. Lactoferrin retains iron binding across pH 2-11 with 300× higher affinity. In acidotic inflammatory microenvironments around plaques, transferrin dumps iron inappropriately while lactoferrin continues sequestering.

**Receptor-mediated BBB transport**: Unlike uncontrolled small-molecule flooding, lactoferrin crosses via dedicated LfR transcytosis — regulated entry that scales with receptor density rather than barrier permeability.

**Endogenous defense restoration**: Lactoferrin is not an exogenous drug but replacement therapy for a failing endogenous system. Activated microglia synthesize lactoferrin when iron-stressed. Salivary lactoferrin declines in AD and correlates with cortical amyloid (Reseco et al. 2021).

**Clinical evidence**: Mohamed et al. (2019) pilot study showed lactoferrin improved cognition, reduced Aβ42, IL-6, p-tau, caspase-3 in AD patients.

**Critical caveat**: If oral apo-Lf picks up iron in gut and arrives as holo-Lf (iron-loaded), it could increase brain iron delivery.

### 6.5.7 Size-Layer Mapping

| FELINE Layer                | How Size Matters                                                                                                                              |
| --------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **N (Neurovascular)** | Leaky BBB floods small molecules uncontrolled; lactoferrin's receptor transport provides regulated entry                                      |
| **Fe (Ferroptosis)**  | Curcumin's lipophilicity places it at membranes; lactoferrin intercepts iron before it reaches membranes; deferiprone depletes iron from GPX4 |
| **E (Export)**        | Lactoferrin is ideal extracellular iron acceptor (300× affinity, acidic-pH retention)                                                        |
| **I (Insulation)**    | Deferiprone depletes oligodendrocyte iron (worsening I-layer); lactoferrin cannot enter OLs without receptor endocytosis                      |
| **L (Lysosomal)**     | Lactoferrin internalized via endocytosis enters lysosomal pathway — positioned at site of pathological iron release                          |

### 6.5.8 Unique Predictions Only FELINE Makes

**Prediction 1 — Size Inversion**: Therapeutic efficacy inversely correlated with molecular size. Larger molecules outperform smaller ones.

**Prediction 2 — Deferiprone in AD**: Will worsen cognitive outcomes (not just fail to help) by depleting OL iron, mitochondrial iron, GPX4 iron.

**Prediction 3 — Subgroup-Dependent Curcumin**: Theracurmin efficacy greatest in high baseline brain iron + APOE ε4 patients.

**Prediction 4 — Apo vs. Holo**: Apo-lactoferrin (iron-free) will outperform holo-lactoferrin (iron-loaded).

**Prediction 5 — Intranasal Superiority**: Intranasal apo-lactoferrin will outperform oral (bypasses gut iron pickup).

**Prediction 6 — Combination Ordering**: Optimal = apo-lactoferrin (extracellular) + Theracurmin (membrane) + ferroptosis inhibitor (intracellular). Exclude deferiprone.

### 6.5.9 Proposed Validation Trial

| Parameter          | Design                                                                                              |
| ------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Population         | Early symptomatic AD (CDR 0.5-1.0), biomarker-confirmed                                             |
| Arms               | Deferiprone 30 mg/kg/day; Theracurmin 90 mg BID; Oral apo-Lf 250 mg BID; Intranasal apo-Lf; Placebo |
| Stratification     | Baseline QSM-MRI brain iron; APOE ε4; sex                                                          |
| Duration           | 18 months                                                                                           |
| Primary Endpoint   | Change in QSM-MRI regional iron**distribution** (not just total iron)                         |
| FELINE Predictions | Deferiprone worsens; Theracurmin modest benefit; Oral apo-Lf moderate; Intranasal apo-Lf best       |

**Key design principle**: Measure iron *distribution*, not just *quantity*. FAIRPARK-II showed reducing total iron worsens outcomes. The correct metric is redistribution from pathological to functional compartments.

### 6.5.10 The Pharmaceutical Economics Problem

Standard drug development optimizes for: small size (<500 Da), universal distribution, high BBB penetration, oral bioavailability. For iron maldistribution, **every one of these works against therapeutic efficacy**:

| Standard Optimization  | Why It Fails                | What FELINE Predicts Is Needed                          |
| ---------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| Small size             | Accesses all compartments   | Large molecules restricted to pathological compartments |
| Universal distribution | Strips iron from everywhere | Compartmentally selective                               |
| High BBB penetration   | Uncontrolled entry          | Receptor-mediated transport                             |
| Oral bioavailability   | Systemic chelation          | Intranasal or targeted delivery                         |

