## Appendix 6.6: FELINE vs Existing Precision Medicine Frameworks

### 6.6.1 Comparison Table

| Framework                    | Primary Focus       | What It Provides                           | What FELINE Adds                                |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------- |
| **ATN/ATNIVS**         | Staging             | Describes WHAT pathologies present         | WHY they converge; HOW to intervene             |
| **ReCODE (Bredesen)**  | Lifestyle factors   | 36 factors, 6 subtypes, practical protocol | MECHANISTIC link (why factors converge on iron) |
| **Molecular Subtypes** | RNA clusters        | 3 data-driven clusters                     | BIOLOGICAL interpretation                       |
| **Neuropathological**  | Tau distribution    | WHERE pathology localizes                  | WHY regional differences exist                  |
| **FELINE**             | Multi-layer defense | Layer-specific intervention matching       | Iron as convergence + redistribution as goal    |

### 6.6.2 ATN/ATNIVS Mapping

ATN/ATNIVS categories map to FELINE layers:

| ATNIVS                | Meaning              | FELINE Layer                   |
| --------------------- | -------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| A (Amyloid)           | A-beta pathology     | Response to Fe/I layer failure |
| T (Tau)               | Tau pathology        | Response to Fe/L layer failure |
| N (Neurodegeneration) | Neuronal loss        | Consequence of ferroptosis     |
| I (Inflammation)      | Neuroinflammation    | Secondary to debris (E layer)  |
| V (Vascular)          | Vascular dysfunction | N layer (neurovascular)        |
| S (Synuclein)         | alpha-syn pathology  | Response to Fe/L layer failure |

**Key insight:** ATNIVS describes consequences; FELINE describes causes.

### 6.6.3 ReCODE Subtype Mapping

Bredesen's 6 subtypes can be mapped to FELINE layers:

| ReCODE Type           | Description              | Primary FELINE Layer                   |
| --------------------- | ------------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| Type 1 (Inflammatory) | Hot, inflammatory        | N layer (BBB inflammation)             |
| Type 1.5 (Glycotoxic) | Metabolic + inflammatory | N layer (pericyte damage from glucose) |
| Type 2 (Atrophic)     | Cold, hormone deficiency | L layer (trophic support failure)      |
| Type 3 (Toxic)        | Dementogen exposure      | Multiple layers depending on toxin     |
| Type 4 (Vascular)     | Vascular insufficiency   | N layer (direct)                       |
| Type 5 (Traumatic)    | Head injury              | N + I layers (BBB + white matter)      |

**Key insight:** ReCODE's empirical subtypes align with FELINE's mechanistic layers.

### 6.6.4 FELINE's Unique Contribution

1. **Iron as convergence point:** All subtypes/types/stages converge on iron maldistribution
2. **Redistribution as therapeutic goal:** Not chelation, not supplementation; FLOW restoration
3. **Layer-specific biomarkers:** Proposed panel for identifying primary failing layer
4. **Combination therapy rationale:** Based on which layers are compromised

